MAT|25|8||And the foolish said to the wise; Give us of your oil; for, behold, our lamps have gone out.
MAT|25|9||The wise answered and said: [We must refuse,] lest there should not be enough for us and for you: but go ye to them that sell, and buy for yourselves.
MAT|25|10||And while they went to buy, the bridegroom came; and they that were ready, went with him into the house of the nuptials, and the door was shut.
MAT|25|11||And at length came also the other virgins, and said: Our lord, our lord, open to us.
MAT|25|12||But he answered, and said to them: Verily I say to you, I know you not.
MAT|25|13||Watch, therefore, seeing ye know not the day nor the hour.
MAT|25|14||For, as a man that took a journey, called his servants and delivered to them his property;
MAT|25|15||to one he gave five talents; to another, two; and to another, one: to each, according to his ability: and he immediately departed.
MAT|25|16||Then he that received five talents, went and traded with them, and gained five more.
MAT|25|17||And likewise: the one of two [talents], by trading gained two more.
MAT|25|18||But he that received one, went and digged in the earth, and hid his lord's money.
MAT|25|19||And after a long time, the lord of those servants came, and received account from them.
MAT|25|20||And he who had received the five talents, came and brought five others; and said, My lord, thou gavest me five talents; behold, I have gained by trading five more to them.
MAT|25|21||His lord said to him: Well done! good and faithful servant: thou hast been faithful with a little; I will set thee over much: enter thou into the joy of thy lord.
MAT|25|22||And he of the two talents came, and said: My lord, thou gavest me two talents; behold, I have by trading gained two more to them.
MAT|25|23||His lord said to him: Well done! Good and faithful servant: thou hast been faithful with a little; I will set thee over much: enter thou into the joy of thy lord.
MAT|25|24||And he also that received the one talent, came and said: My lord, I knew thee, that thou art a hard man, reaping where thou hast not sowed, and gathering where thou hast not scattered;
MAT|25|25||and I was afraid, and I went and hid thy talent in the earth. Behold, thou hast what is thine.
MAT|25|26||His lord answered, and said to him: Wicked and slothful servant! Thou knewest me, that I reap where I have not sowed, and gather where I have not scattered!
MAT|25|27||Thou oughtest to have cast my money into the exchange; and I might have come and demanded my property with its interest.
MAT|25|28||Take therefore the talent from him, and give it to him that hath ten talents.
MAT|25|29||For, to him that hath, shall be given, and he shall have more; but from him that hath not, even what he hath shall be taken away.
MAT|25|30||And cast ye the unprofitable servant into the outer darkness: there will be weeping and gnashing of teeth.
MAT|25|31||And when the Son of man shall come in his glory, and all his holy angels with him, then will he sit upon the throne of his glory.
MAT|25|32||And before him will be gathered all nations; and he will separate them one from another, as a shepherd severeth the sheep from the goats.
MAT|25|33||And he will place the sheep on his right hand, and the goats on his left.
MAT|25|34||Then will the king say to those on his right hand: Come, ye blessed of my Father; inherit the kingdom that was prepared for you from the foundation of the world.
MAT|25|35||For I was hungry, and ye gave me food; I was thirsty, and ye gave me drink; I was a stranger, and ye took me home;
MAT|25|36||I was naked, and ye clothed me; I was sick, and ye visited me; I was in prison, and ye came to me.
MAT|25|37||Then will the righteous say to him: Our Lord, when saw we thee hungry, and fed thee? or thirsty, and gave thee drink?
MAT|25|38||And when saw we thee a stranger, and took thee home? or naked, and clothed thee?
MAT|25|39||And when saw we thee sick, or in prison, and came to thee?
MAT|25|40||And the king will answer, and say to them: Verily I say to you, That inasmuch as ye did so to one of these my little brothers, ye did so to me.
MAT|25|41||Then will he say also to them on his left hand: Go from me, ye accursed, into everlasting fire, which was prepared for the Calumniator and his angels,
MAT|25|42||For I was hungry, and ye gave me no food; and I was thirsty, and ye gave me no drink;
MAT|25|43||and I was a stranger, and ye took me not home; and I was naked, and ye clothed me not; and I was sick and in prison, and ye did not visit me.
MAT|25|44||Then will they also answer and say: Our Lord, when saw we thee hungry, or thirsty, or a stranger, or naked, or sick, or in prison, and did not minister to thee?
MAT|25|45||Then will he answer, and say to them: Verily I say to you, That in as much as ye did not so to one of these little ones, ye did not so to me.
MAT|25|46||And these will go into everlasting torment, and the righteous into everlasting life.
MAT|26|1||And it came to pass, when Jesus had concluded all these discourses, that he said to his disciples:
MAT|26|2||Ye know that after two days is the Passover; and the Son of man is betrayed to be crucified.
MAT|26|3||Then assembled the chief priests and the Scribes and the Elders of the people, at the hall of the high priest, who was called Caiaphas.
MAT|26|4||And they held a counsel against Jesus, that they might take him by guile, and kill him.
MAT|26|5||But they said: Not on the festival, lest there be a commotion among the people.
MAT|26|6||And when Jesus was at Bethany, in the house of Simon the leper,
MAT|26|7||there came to him a woman having a vase of aromatic ointment very precious, and she poured it on the head of Jesus as he was reclining.
MAT|26|8||And when his disciples saw [it] they were displeased, and said: Why is this waste?
MAT|26|9||For this [ointment] might have been sold for much, and have been given to the poor.
MAT|26|10||But Jesus knew [their dissatisfaction], and said to them: Why trouble ye the woman? She hath performed a good deed towards me.
MAT|26|11||For the poor ye have at all times with you; but I am not with you always
MAT|26|12||And this her act, pouring the ointment on my body, she hath done as it were for my burial.
MAT|26|13||Verily I say to you, That wherever this my gospel shall be proclaimed, in all the world, this thing that she hath done shall be told for a memorial of her.
MAT|26|14||Then one of the twelve, named Judas Iscariot, went to the chief priests,
MAT|26|15||and said to them: What will ye give me, if I will deliver him to you? And they promised him thirty pieces of silver.
MAT|26|16||And from that time he sought opportunity to betray him.
MAT|26|17||And on the first day of unleavened bread, the disciples came to Jesus, and said to him: Where wilt thou that we prepare for thee to eat the passover?
MAT|26|18||And he said to them: Go ye into the city, to such a man, and say to him: Our Rabbi saith, My time approaches: with thee will I keep the passover with my disciples
MAT|26|19||And his disciples did as Jesus directed them, and made ready the passover.
MAT|26|20||And when it was evening, he reclined with his twelve disciples.
MAT|26|21||And as they were eating, he said: Verily I say to you, That one of you will betray me.
MAT|26|22||And it troubled them much. And they began each one of them to say to him; My Lord is it I?
MAT|26|23||And he answered and said: One that dippeth his hand with me in the dish, he will betray me.
MAT|26|24||And the Son of man goeth, as it is written of him: but woe to that man, by whom the Son of man is betrayed. It would have been better for that man, if he had not been born.
MAT|26|25||Judas the betrayer answered and said: Rabbi, is it I? Jesus said to him: Thou hast said.
MAT|26|26||And as they were eating, Jesus took bread, and blessed, and brake; and gave to his disciples, and said: Take, eat; this is my body.
MAT|26|27||And he took the cup, and offered thanks and gave [it] to them, saying: Take, drink of this all of you.
MAT|26|28||This is my blood of the new testament, which, in behalf of many, is shed for the remission of sins.
MAT|26|29||But I say to you, that I will henceforth not drink of this product of the vine, until the day in which I shall drink it with you new in the kingdom of God.
MAT|26|30||And they sang praises, and went forth to the mount of Olives.
MAT|26|31||Then said Jesus to them: Ye will all be offended in me this night; for it is written, I will smite the shepherd, and the sheep of his flock will be dispersed.
MAT|26|32||But after I am arisen, I will go before you into Galilee.
MAT|26|33||Cephas replied, and said to him: Though all men should be offended in thee, I will never be offended in thee.
MAT|26|34||Jesus said to him: Verily I say to thee, That this night, before the cock crow, thou wilt thrice deny me.
MAT|26|35||Cephas said to him: If I were to die with thee, I would not deny thee: and so also said all the disciples.
MAT|26|36||Then came Jesus with them to a place called Gethsemane: and he said to his disciples, Sit ye here, while I go and pray.
MAT|26|37||And he took Cephas and the two sons of Zebedee, and began to be dejected and sorrowful.
MAT|26|38||And he said to them: There is anguish in my soul, even unto death. Wait for me here; and watch with me.
MAT|26|39||And retiring a little, he fell on his face, and prayed, and said: My Father, if it can be so, let this cup pass from me. Yet not as I choose, but as thou.
MAT|26|40||And he came to his disciples, and found them asleep: and he said to Cephas: So! could ye not watch with me one hour?
MAT|26|41||Wake ye, and pray, lest ye fall into temptation. The mind is prepared, but the body is infirm.
MAT|26|42||Again he went away the second time, and prayed, and said: My Father, if it cannot be that this cup pass, except I drink it, thy will be done.
MAT|26|43||And he came again and found them sleeping, for their eyes were heavy.
MAT|26|44||And he left them, and went again and prayed the third time, and used the same language.
MAT|26|45||Then he came to his disciples, and said to them: Sleep on now, and take rest. Behold, the hour is come: and the Son of man is betrayed into the hands of sinners.
MAT|26|46||Arise, let us go. Behold, he that betrayeth me hath come.
MAT|26|47||And while he was yet speaking, lo, Judas the betrayer, one of the twelve, arrived; and a great multitude with him, with swords and clubs, from the presence of the chief priests and elders of the people.
MAT|26|48||And Judas the betrayer had given them a sign, saying: He it is, whom I shall kiss: him seize ye.
MAT|26|49||And forthwith he approached Jesus, and said: Hail, Rabbi; and kissed him.
MAT|26|50||And Jesus said to him: My friend, is it for this thou hast come? Then they came up, and laid their hands on Jesus, and took him.
MAT|26|51||And lo, one of them with Jesus stretched out his hand, and drew a sword, and smote a servant of the high priest, and cut off his ear.
MAT|26|52||Then Jesus said to him: Return the sword to its place; for all they that take swords, shall die by swords.
MAT|26|53||Supposest thou that I cannot ask of my Father, and he now assign me more than twelve legions of angels?
MAT|26|54||But how then would the scriptures be fulfilled, that thus it must be?
MAT|26|55||At that time Jesus said to the multitude: Have ye come out, as against a cut-throat, with swords and clubs, to take me? I daily sat with you, and taught in the temple, and ye did not apprehend me.
MAT|26|56||And this occurred, that the writings of the prophets might be fulfilled. Then the disciples all forsook him and fled.
MAT|26|57||And they who apprehended Jesus carried him to Caiaphas the high priest, where the Scribes and Elders were assembled.
MAT|26|58||And Simon Cephas followed after him at a distance, unto the high priest's hall, and entered, and sat with the servants within, that he might see the issue.
MAT|26|59||And the chief priests and the Elders and the whole assembly sought for witnesses against Jesus, that they might put him to death;
MAT|26|60||and found them not. And many false witnesses came; and at last, two came forward,
MAT|26|61||and said: This man said, I can destroy the temple of God, and in three days rebuild it.
MAT|26|62||And the high priest rose up and said to him: Respondest thou nothing? What do these testify against thee?
MAT|26|63||And Jesus was silent. And the high priest answered, and said to him: I adjure thee by the living God, that thou tell us whether thou art the Messiah, the Son of God.
MAT|26|64||Jesus saith to him: Thou hast said. And I say to you, That hereafter ye will see the Son of man sitting on the right hand of power, and coming on the clouds of heaven.
MAT|26|65||Then the high priest rent his clothes, and said: Behold, he hath blasphemed! Why therefore should we seek for witnesses? Behold, ye have now heard his blasphemy.
MAT|26|66||What is your pleasure? They answered and said: He is liable to death.
MAT|26|67||Then they spit in his face, and buffeted him, and others smote him,
MAT|26|68||and said to him: Prophesy to us, thou Messiah, who is it smote thee?
MAT|26|69||And Cephas was sitting without in the hall, and a certain maid approached him, and said to him: Thou also wast with Jesus the Nazarean.
MAT|26|70||But he denied [it] before them all, and said: I know not what thou sayest.
MAT|26|71||And as he went out into the porch, another maid saw him, and said to them: This man was also there with Jesus the Nazarean.
MAT|26|72||And again he denied, with oaths: I know not that man.
MAT|26|73||And a little after, those standing [there] came up and said to Cephas: Certainly, thou too art one of them; and thy speech maketh thee manifest.
MAT|26|74||Then he began to imprecate and to swear, I know not that man. And in that hour the cock crew.
MAT|26|75||And Cephas remembered the declaration of Jesus, who said to him: Before the cock croweth, thou wilt three times deny me. And he went out, and wept bitterly.
MAT|27|1||And when it was morning, the chief priests and the elders of the people held a council against Jesus, how they might put him to death.
MAT|27|2||And they bound him, and carried him and delivered him up to Pilate, the president.
MAT|27|3||Then Judas the betrayer, when he saw that Jesus was condemned, repented. And he went and returned the thirty pieces of silver to the chief priests and elders;
MAT|27|4||and said: I have sinned, by betraying innocent blood. And they said: What is that to us? See to it thyself.
MAT|27|5||And he cast down the silver in the temple, and retiring, went and strangled himself
MAT|27|6||And the chief priests took up the silver, and said: It is not lawful to put it into the treasury, because it is the price of blood.
MAT|27|7||And they took counsel, and bought with it the potter's field, for a place to bury strangers.
MAT|27|8||Wherefore that field is called the field of blood, unto this day.
MAT|27|9||Then was fulfilled that which was spoken by the prophet, saying: I took the thirty [shekels] of silver, the price of the precious one, which they of the children of Israel had stipulated;
MAT|27|10||and I gave them for the potter's field, as the Lord directed me.
MAT|27|11||And Jesus stood before the president. And the resident asked him, and said to him: Art thou the king of the Jews? And Jesus said to him: Thou hast said.
MAT|27|12||And when the chief priests and elders accused him, he made no reply.
MAT|27|13||Then Pilate said to him: Hearest thou not how much they testify against thee?
MAT|27|14||But he gave him no answer, not even one word: and therefore Pilate wondered greatly.
MAT|27|15||And at each festival, the president was accustomed to release to the people one prisoner, such as they preferred.
MAT|27|16||And they had then in bonds a noted prisoner, called Bar Abas.
MAT|27|17||And when they were assembled, Pilate said to them: Whom will ye, that I release to you, Bar Abas, or Jesus who is called Messiah?
MAT|27|18||For Pilate knew that it was from enmity they had delivered him up.
MAT|27|19||And as the president was sitting on his tribunal, his wife sent to him, and said: Have thou nothing to do with that just man; for I have suffered much this day in a dream because of him.
MAT|27|20||But the chief priests and the elders persuaded the multitude that they should demand Bar Abas, and destroy Jesus.
MAT|27|21||And the president answered, and said to them: Which of the two, will ye, that I release to you? And they said: Bar Abas.
MAT|27|22||Pilate said to them: And what shall I do to Jesus who is called Messiah? They all replied: Let him be crucified.
MAT|27|23||The president said to them: But what hath he done, that is evil? And they cried out the more, and said: Let him be crucified.
MAT|27|24||And Pilate, when he saw that it availed nothing, but rather that tumult was produced, took water, and washed his hands before the eyes of the multitude, and said: I am pure from the blood of this just man: see ye to it.
MAT|27|25||And all the people answered, and said His blood be on us, and on our children!
MAT|27|26||Then released he to them Bar Abas; and scourged Jesus with whips and delivered him to be crucified.
MAT|27|27||Then the soldiers of the president took Jesus into the Praetorium, and assembled the whole regiment against him.
MAT|27|28||And they stripped him, and put on him a scarlet military cloak.
MAT|27|29||And they wove a crown of thorns, and set it on his head, and [put] a reed in his hand, and they bowed their knees before him, and mocked him, and said: Hail, thou king of the Jews.
MAT|27|30||And they spit in his face, and took the reed, and smote him on his head.
MAT|27|31||And when they had mocked him, they divested him of the cloak, and clothed him in his own garments, and led him out to be crucified.
MAT|27|32||And as they went out, they found a man of Cyrene whose name was Simon; him they compelled to bear his cross.
MAT|27|33||And they came to a place which is called Golgotha, which is interpreted a skull.
MAT|27|34||And they gave him to drink vinegar mixed with gall. And he tasted [it], and would not drink.
MAT|27|35||And when they had crucified him, they distributed his garments by lot.
MAT|27|36||And they sat down, and watched him there
MAT|27|37||And they placed over his head the cause of his death, in the writing: THIS IS JESUS, THE KING OF THE JEWS.
MAT|27|38||And there were crucified with him two robbers, the one on his right hand, and the other on his left.
MAT|27|39||And they that passed by reviled him, and shook their heads
MAT|27|40||and said: Destroyer of the temple, and builder of it in three days, deliver thyself, if thou art the Son of God, and come down from the cross.
MAT|27|41||So also the chief priests mocked, with the Scribes and Elders and Pharisees,
MAT|27|42||and said: He gave life to others, his own life he cannot preserve. If he is the king of Israel, let him now descend from the cross, and we will believe in him.
MAT|27|43||He trusted in God; let him rescue him now, if he hath pleasure in him: for he said, I am the Son of God.
MAT|27|44||In like manner the marauders also, that were crucified with him, reproached him.
MAT|27|45||And from the sixth hour there was darkness over all the land, until the ninth hour.
MAT|27|46||And about the ninth hour, Jesus cried with a loud voice and said: O God, O God; why hast thou forsaken me?
MAT|27|47||And some of them that stood there, when they heard [it], said: He calleth for Elijah.
MAT|27|48||And immediately one of them ran, and took a sponge, and filled it with vinegar, and put it on a reed, and gave him to drink.
MAT|27|49||But the rest said: Desist; we will see if Elijah will come to rescue him.
MAT|27|50||Then Jesus cried again with a loud voice, and yielded up his spirit.
MAT|27|51||And instantly, the curtain of the door of the temple was torn asunder, from the top to the bottom; and the earth shook; and the rocks rived;
MAT|27|52||and graves were opened; and many bodies of saints who slept, arose,
MAT|27|53||and came forth; and, after his resurrection, entered into the holy city, and appeared to many.
MAT|27|54||And the centurion, and they that were with him guarding Jesus, when they saw the earthquake and the things that occurred, feared greatly, and said: Verily, this was the Son of God.
MAT|27|55||And many women were there, looking on from a distance; the same who had followed Jesus from Galilee, and had ministered to him.
MAT|27|56||One of them was Mary of Magdala, also Mary the mother of James and Joses, and the mother of Zebedee's children.
MAT|27|57||And when it was evening, there came a rich man of Ramath, whose name was a Joseph, who was also a disciple of Jesus.
MAT|27|58||This man went to Pilate, and begged the body of Jesus. And Pilate directed the body to be given him.
MAT|27|59||And Joseph took the body, and wrapped it in a winding-sheet of clean linen;
MAT|27|60||and laid it in his new sepulchre, that was excavated in a rock. And he rolled a great stone against the door of the sepulchre, and departed:
MAT|27|61||And there were present Mary of Magdala, and the other Mary, who sat over against the grave.
MAT|27|62||And on the day that was next after the preparation, the chief priests and Pharisees assembled before Pilate,
MAT|27|63||and said to him: Our Lord, we remember that this deceiver said, while he was alive, After three days, I shall arise
MAT|27|64||Command, therefore to guard the sepulchre; until the third day; lest his disciples come and steal him away by night, and say to the people that he hath risen from the dead; and the last delusion be worse than the first.
MAT|27|65||Pilate said to them: Ye have soldiers: go and guard it, as ye know how.
MAT|27|66||And they went and set a guard to the sepulchre, and sealed the stone.
MAT|28|1||And in the close of the sabbath, as the first [day] of the week began to dawn, came Mary of Magdala and the other Mary, to view the sepulchre.
MAT|28|2||And lo, there was a great earthquake: for an angel of the Lord descended from heaven, and came and rolled away the stone from the door, and sat upon it.
MAT|28|3||And his aspect was like the lightning; and his raiment white like snow:
MAT|28|4||and from fear of him the keepers were astounded, and became as dead men.
MAT|28|5||And the angel answered, and said to the women: Be not ye afraid, for I know that ye seek Jesus who was crucified.
MAT|28|6||He is not here; for he is risen, as he predicted. Come ye, see the place where our Lord was laid.
MAT|28|7||And [then] go quickly, tell his disciples, that he is risen from the dead; and lo, he precedeth you to Galilee; there will ye see him. Behold, I have told you.
MAT|28|8||And they went quickly from the sepulchre, with fear and great joy, and ran to tell his disciples.
MAT|28|9||And lo, Jesus met them, and said to them: Hail, ye. And they came and clasped his feet, and worshipped him.
MAT|28|10||Then Jesus said to them: Be not afraid; but go, tell my brethren, that they go into Galilee, and there they will see me.
MAT|28|11||And while they were going, some of the guards came into the city, and told the chief priests all that had occurred.
MAT|28|12||And they assembled with the Elders, and held a council; and they gave no little money to the guards,
MAT|28|13||and said to them: Say ye, that his disciples came and stole him away by night, while we were asleep.
MAT|28|14||And if this should be reported before the President, we will pacify him, and cause you not to be troubled.
MAT|28|15||And they, having received the money, did as they were instructed. And this story is current among the Jews to this day.
MAT|28|16||And the eleven disciples went into Galilee, to the mountain which Jesus had appointed for them.
MAT|28|17||And when they beheld him, they worshipped him: but some doubted.
MAT|28|18||And Jesus came near, and discoursed with them, and said to them: All authority is given to me, in heaven and on earth. And as my Father sent me, so also I send you.
MAT|28|19||Go ye, therefore, and instruct all nations; and baptize them in the name of the Father, and of the Son, and of the Holy Spirit.
MAT|28|20||And teach them to observe all that I have commanded you. And, behold, I am with you always, unto the consummation of the worlds Amen.
MAK|1|1||The beginning of the gospel of Jesus the Messiah, the Son of God.
MAK|1|2||As it is written in Isaiah the prophet: Behold, I send my messenger before thy face, who shall prepare thy way.
MAK|1|3||The voice of one crying in the wilderness: Prepare ye the way of the Lord; make smooth his paths.
MAK|1|4||John baptized in the wilderness, and proclaimed the baptism of repentance for the remission of sins.
MAK|1|5||And there went out to him all the region of Judaea, and all the people of Jerusalem; and he baptized them in the river Jordan, while they confessed their sins.
MAK|1|6||And this John was clad in raiment of camels' hair; and was girded with a cincture of skin about his loins; and his food was locusts and wild honey.
MAK|1|7||And he proclaimed, and said: Behold, after me cometh one more powerful than I, of whom I am not worthy to stoop and untie the fastenings of his shoes.
MAK|1|8||I have baptized you with water; but he will baptize you with the Holy Spirit.
MAK|1|9||And it occurred, in those days, that Jesus came from Nazareth in Galilee, and was baptized in Jordan by John.
MAK|1|10||And immediately on his coming from the water, he saw the heavens cleft, and the Spirit descending like a dove upon him.
MAK|1|11||And there was a voice from the heavens: Thou art my beloved Son, in whom I delight.
MAK|1|12||And directly the Spirit carried him into the wilderness:
MAK|1|13||and he was there in the wilderness forty days, being tempted by Satan. And he was with the wild beasts; and angels ministered to him.
MAK|1|14||After John was delivered up, Jesus came into Galilee, and proclaimed the tidings, of the kingdom of God,
MAK|1|15||and said: The time is completed, and the kingdom of God is near. Repent ye, and believe the tidings.
MAK|1|16||And as he walked near the sea of Galilee, he saw Simon and Andrew his brother casting a net into the sea, for they were fishermen.
MAK|1|17||And Jesus said to them: Come after me, and I will make you fishers of men.
MAK|1|18||And immediately they left their nets, and went after him.
MAK|1|19||And as he passed on a little, he saw James the son of Zebedee, and John his brother, who also were in a ship, and mending their nets.
MAK|1|20||And he called them: and immediately they left Zebedee their father in the ship, with the hired servants, and went after him.
MAK|1|21||And when they entered Capernaum, he immediately taught on the sabbath in their synagogues.
MAK|1|22||And they were astonished at his doctrine; for he taught them, as having authority, and not as their Scribes.
MAK|1|23||And in their synagogue was a man, in whom was an unclean spirit; and he cried out,
MAK|1|24||and said: What have we to do with thee? Jesus thou Nazarean. Hast thou come to destroy us? I know thee, who thou art, the Holy One of God.
MAK|1|25||And Jesus rebuked him, and said: Shut thy mouth, and come out of him.
MAK|1|26||And the unclean spirit threw him down, and cried with a loud voice, and came out of him.
MAK|1|27||And they were all amazed, and inquired one of another, and said: What is this? What new doctrine is this? For with authority he commandeth the unclean spirits, and they obey him.
MAK|1|28||And immediately his fame spread into all the land of Galilee.
MAK|1|29||And he retired from the synagogue, and entered into the house of Simon and Andrew, with James and John.
MAK|1|30||And Simon's mother-in-law was lying sick with a fever: and they told him about her.
MAK|1|31||And he came, and took her hand, and raised her up; and immediately the fever left her, and she ministered to them.
MAK|1|32||And in the evening at the setting of the sun, they brought to him all them that were diseased, and demoniacs.
MAK|1|33||And all the city was collected at the door.
MAK|1|34||And he healed many who labored under divers diseases, and cast out many demons; and he suffered not the demons to speak, because they knew him.
MAK|1|35||And in the morning, he rose much before others, and retired to a solitary place, and there prayed.
MAK|1|36||And Simon and his associates sought for him.
MAK|1|37||And when they found him, they said to him: Every body is seeking for thee.
MAK|1|38||And he said to them: Go into the adjacent villages and towns; for there also I will preach, because therefore have I come.
MAK|1|39||And he preached in all their synagogues, in all Galilee, and cast out demons.
MAK|1|40||And a leper came to him, and fell at his feet, and entreated him, and said to him: If thou wilt, thou canst make me clean.
MAK|1|41||And Jesus had compassion on him, and stretched out his hand, and touched him, and said: I will; be thou clean.
MAK|1|42||And in that hour, his leprosy departed from him, and he became clean.
MAK|1|43||And he charged him, and sent him away,
MAK|1|44||and he said to him: See that thou tell no person; but go, show thyself to the priests, and offer an oblation on account of thy purification, as Moses commanded, for a testimony to them.
MAK|1|45||And he, as he went out, began to proclaim [it] much, and to divulge the matter; so that Jesus could not openly go into the city, but was without, in desert places; and they came to him from every quarter.
MAK|2|1||And Jesus again entered into Capernaum, after some days. And when they heard that he was in the house,
MAK|2|2||many were assembled, so that [the house] could not contain them, not even before the door. And he held discourse with them.
MAK|2|3||And they came to him and brought to him a paralytic, borne between four persons.
MAK|2|4||And as they could not come near him on account of the crowd, they ascended to the roof, and removed the covering of the place where Jesus was, and let down the bed on which the paralytic lay.
MAK|2|5||And when Jesus saw their faith, he said to the paralytic: My son, thy sins are forgiven thee.
MAK|2|6||And there were some Scribes and Pharisees there, who sat and reasoned in their hearts:
MAK|2|7||Who is this speaking, blasphemy? Who can forgive sins, except God only?
MAK|2|8||And Jesus knew, in his spirit, that they thus reasoned in themselves; and he said to them: Why reason ye thus in your heart?
MAK|2|9||Which is the easier, to say to a paralytic, Thy sins are forgiven thee? or to say, Arise, take up thy bed, and walk?
MAK|2|10||But that ye may know that the Son of man hath power on earth to forgive sins, he said to the paralytic,
MAK|2|11||I say to thee, Arise, take thy bed, and go to thy house.
MAK|2|12||And he arose in that hour, took up his bed, and departed in presence of them all: so that they were all amazed, and praised God, saying: We never saw the like.
MAK|2|13||And he went again to the sea; and all the multitude came to him, and he taught them.
MAK|2|14||And as he passed along he saw Levi the son of Alpheus sitting among the publicans. And he said to him: Come after me. And he arose and went after him.
MAK|2|15||And it was so, that as he reclined in his [Levi's] house, many publicans and sinners reclined with Jesus and with his disciples: for they were many, and they followed him.
MAK|2|16||And when the Scribes and Pharisees saw that he ate with publicans and with sinners, they said to his disciples: Why doth he eat and drink with publicans and sinners?
MAK|2|17||When Jesus heard [it], he said to them: The healthy need not a physician, but those laboring under disease: I came, not to call the righteous, but sinners.
MAK|2|18||And the disciples of John and of the Pharisees were fasters; and they came and said to him: Why are the disciples of John and of the Pharisees fasters, and thy disciples fast not?
MAK|2|19||Jesus said to them: Can the guests of the nuptial chamber fast so long as the bridegroom is with them? No.
MAK|2|20||But the days will come, when the bridegroom will be taken from them, and then they will fast, in that day.
MAK|2|21||No one taketh a patch of new cloth and seweth it upon an old garment, lest the supplemental new should take from the old, and the rent become the greater.
MAK|2|22||And no one putteth new wine into old sacks, lest the wine burst the sacks, and the sacks be spoiled, and the wine spilled; but they put new wine into new sacks.
MAK|2|23||And it was so, that as Jesus on a sabbath walked in the tillage grounds, his disciples walked and plucked the ears.
MAK|2|24||And the Pharisees said to him: See, how on the sabbath, they do that which is not lawful?
MAK|2|25||Jesus said to them: Have ye never read what David did, when he had need and was hungry, he and his attendants?
MAK|2|26||How he entered the house of God, when Abiathar was high priest, and ate the bread of the Lord's table, which it was not lawful for any but priests to eat, and gave [it] also to those with him?
MAK|2|27||And he said to them: The sabbath was made on man's account, and not man for the sake of the sabbath.
MAK|2|28||Therefore also the Son of man is lord of the sabbath.
MAK|3|1||And again Jesus entered into a synagogue. And there was a man there, whose hand was withered.
MAK|3|2||And they watched him, that if he should heal on the sabbath, they might accuse him.
MAK|3|3||And he said to the man of the withered hand: Stand up in the midst.
MAK|3|4||And he said also to them: Is it lawful to do good on the sabbath, or to do evil? to give life to a person, or to destroy? But they were silent
MAK|3|5||And he looked on them with indignation, being grieved with the hardness of their heart. And he said to the man: Stretch forth thy hand. And he stretched forth, and his hand was restored.
MAK|3|6||And the Pharisees went out, that very hour, with the domestics of Herod, and held a consultation against him, how they might destroy him.
MAK|3|7||And Jesus retired with his disciples to the sea. And many people joined him from Galilee, and from Judaea,
MAK|3|8||and from Jerusalem, and from Idumaea, and from beyond Jordan, and from Tyre, and from Sidon: great multitudes,--- when they heard all that he did, came to him.
MAK|3|9||And he told his disciples to bring him a ship, on account of the multitude, lest they should crowd upon him
MAK|3|10||For he had healed many, so that they rushed upon him, in order to touch him.
MAK|3|11||And they who were afflicted with unclean spirits, when they saw him, fell down and cried out, and said: Thou art the Son of God.
MAK|3|12||And he charged them much, not to make him known.
MAK|3|13||And he ascended a mountain, and called whom he pleased; and they came to him.
MAK|3|14||And he chose twelve to be with him, whom he would send out to preach,
MAK|3|15||and who would have power to heal the sick, and to cast out demons.
MAK|3|16||And to Simon he gave the name of Cephas.
MAK|3|17||And to James the son of Zebedee and to John the brother of James, he gave the name of Boanerges, that is, Sons of thunder.
MAK|3|18||And [he chose also] Andrew, and Philip, and Bartholomew, and Matthew, and Thomas, and James the son of Alpheus, and Thaddeus, and Simon the Canaanite,
MAK|3|19||And Judas Iscariot, who betrayed him. And they came to the house:
MAK|3|20||and the multitude assembled again, so that they could not eat bread.
MAK|3|21||And his kinsmen heard, and went out to take him; for they said: He is out of his reason.
MAK|3|22||And those Scribes that had come down from Jerusalem, said: Beelzebub is in him; and by the prince of demons he expelleth demons.
MAK|3|23||And Jesus called them, and said to them, by similitudes: How can Satan cast out Satan?
MAK|3|24||For if a kingdom be divided against itself, that kingdom cannot stand.
MAK|3|25||And if a house be divided against itself, that house cannot stand.
MAK|3|26||And if Satan rise up against himself and be divided, he cannot stand, but is at an end.
MAK|3|27||No one can enter the house of a strong man, and plunder his goods, unless he first bind the strong man; and then he may rob his house.
MAK|3|28||Verily I say to you: All sins, and the blasphemies that men may utter, may be forgiven them:
MAK|3|29||but whoever shall blaspheme against the Holy Spirit, to him for ever there is no forgiveness; but he is obnoxious to eternal judgment.
MAK|3|30||Because they had said: An unclean spirit is in him.
MAK|3|31||And his mother and his brothers came, and, standing without, sent to call him to them.
MAK|3|32||And the multitude were sitting around him, and they said to him: Lo, thy mother and thy brothers, without, call for thee.
MAK|3|33||He replied, and said to them: Who is my mother? and who are my brothers?
MAK|3|34||And he looked upon those who sat by him, and said: Behold my mother! and, behold my brothers!
MAK|3|35||For whoever shall do the pleasure of God, he is my brother, and my sister, and my mother.
MAK|4|1||And again he began to teach by the side of the sea. And great multitudes were assembled about him; so that he embarked and sat in a ship on the sea, and all the multitude stood on the land by the side of the sea.
MAK|4|2||And he taught them much by similitudes. And in his teaching, he said:
MAK|4|3||Hear ye: Behold a sower went forth to sow.
MAK|4|4||And as he sowed, some [seed] fell on the side of the path; and a bird came, and devoured it.
MAK|4|5||And other [seed] fell on a rock, so that it had not much earth; and it soon shot up, because it had no depth of earth.
MAK|4|6||But when the sun was up, it wilted; and because it had no root, it dried up.
MAK|4|7||And other [seed] fell among thorns. And the thorns grew up, and choked it, and it yielded no fruits.
MAK|4|8||And other [seed] fell on good ground, and came up, and grew, and yielded fruits; some thirty, some sixty, and some a hundred.
MAK|4|9||And he said: Whoever hath ears to hear, let him hear.
MAK|4|10||And when they were by themselves, those with him, together with the twelve, asked him [concerning] this similitude.
MAK|4|11||And Jesus said to them: To you it is given to know the mystery of the kingdom of God; but to them without, all is in similitudes:
MAK|4|12||that when they see, they may see and not see, and when they hear, they may hear and not understand; lest they should be converted, and their sins be forgiven them.
MAK|4|13||And he said to them: Do ye not understand this similitude? And how will ye understand all similitudes?
MAK|4|14||The sower that sowed, sowed the word.
MAK|4|15||And those by the side of the path, are they in whom the word is sown; and as soon as they have heard [it], Satan cometh, and taketh away the word that was sown in their hearts.
MAK|4|16||And those sown on the rock, are they who, when they hear the word, immediately with joy receive it.
MAK|4|17||And they have no root in them, but are temporary; and when there is affliction or persecution on account of the word, they are quickly stumbled.
MAK|4|18||And those sown among thorns, are they that hear the word,
MAK|4|19||and the cares of this world, and the deceitfulness of riches, and the residue of other lusts enter in and choke the word, and it is without fruits.
MAK|4|20||And those sown on good ground are they that hear the word, and receive it, and bear fruits, by thirties, and by sixties, and by hundreds.
MAK|4|21||And he said to them: Is a lamp brought to be placed under a bushel, or under a bed? Is it not to be placed on a light-stand?
MAK|4|22||For there is nothing hid, which will not be exposed; and nothing concealed, which will not be made manifest.
MAK|4|23||If any one have ears to hear, let him hear.
MAK|4|24||And he said to them: Take heed what ye hear: with what measure ye measure, it shall be measured to you: and there shall more be given to you who hear.
MAK|4|25||For to him that hath, will more be given; and from him that hath not, even what he hath, will be taken from him.
MAK|4|26||And he said: So is the kingdom of God, as if a man should cast seed into the ground,
MAK|4|27||and should sleep and rise, by night and by day, and the seed should grow and shoot up, he knoweth not how.
MAK|4|28||For the earth bringeth forth the fruit; first the plant, and subsequently the ear, and at last the complete wheat in the ear.
MAK|4|29||And when the fruit is ripe, immediately cometh the sickle, because the harvest hath arrived.
MAK|4|30||And he said: To what shall we liken the kingdom of God? and with what similitude shall we compare it?
MAK|4|31||It is like a grain of mustard seed which, when it is sown in the earth, is the least of all seeds sown on the earth;
MAK|4|32||and when it is sown it springeth up, and becometh greater than all herbs, and produceth great branches, so that birds can lodge under its shadow.
MAK|4|33||And by many such similitudes,---similitudes such as they could hear,---Jesus discoursed with the people.
MAK|4|34||And without similitudes he did not converse with them: but to his disciples, between himself and them, he explained every thing.
MAK|4|35||And he said to them, the same day at evening: Let us pass over to the other side.
MAK|4|36||And they sent away the multitudes: and they conducted him in the ship as he was. And there were also with him other little ships.
MAK|4|37||And there was a great tempest and wind: and the waves beat upon the ship, and it was near being filled.
MAK|4|38||And Jesus was asleep on a pillow in the hinder part of the ship. And they came and awoke him, and said to him: Our Rabbi, carest thou not, that we perish?
MAK|4|39||And he arose, and rebuked the wind, and said to the sea: Cease; be still. And the wind ceased, and there was a great calm.
MAK|4|40||And he said to them: Why were ye so fearful? and why have ye not faith?
MAK|4|41||And they feared with great fear: and they said, one to another: Who is this, that even the winds and the sea obey him!
MAK|5|1||And he came to the other side of the sea, to the country of the Gadarenes.
MAK|5|2||And as he went out of the ship, there met him from the place of sepulchres a man in whom was an unclean spirit.
MAK|5|3||And he dwelt in the place of sepulchres; and no one could confine him with chains:
MAK|5|4||because, as often as he had been confined with fetters and chains, he had broken the chains and burst the fetters: and no one could subdue him.
MAK|5|5||And continually, by night and by day, he was in the place of sepulchres, and cried and wounded himself with stones.
MAK|5|6||And when he saw Jesus at a distance, he ran and worshipped him;
MAK|5|7||and cried with a loud voice, and said: What have I to do with thee, Jesus, thou Son of the High God? I adjure thee by God, that thou torment me not.
MAK|5|8||For he had said to him: Come out of the man, thou unclean spirit.
MAK|5|9||And he demanded of him: What is thy name? And he replied to him: Our name is Legion; for we are many.
MAK|5|10||And he besought him much, that he would not send him out of the country.
MAK|5|11||And there was there by the mountain, a great herd of swine grazing.
MAK|5|12||And the demons besought him, and said: Send us upon those swine, that we may enter them.
MAK|5|13||And he permitted them. And those unclean spirits went out, and entered the swine: and the herd, of about two thousand, ran to a precipice, and fell into the sea, and were strangled in the waters.
MAK|5|14||And they who tended them, fled and told [it] in the city and in the villages: and they came out to see what had occurred.
MAK|5|15||And: they came to Jesus, and saw him in whom the demons had been,---him in whom had been the legion,--- clothed, and sober, and sitting; and they were afraid.
MAK|5|16||And those who had seen [it] told them how it occurred to him who had the demons, and also concerning the swine.
MAK|5|17||And they began to request him, that he would go from their border.
MAK|5|18||And as he ascended the ship, the late demoniac requested that he might continue with him.
MAK|5|19||And he suffered him not, but said to him: Go home to thy people, and tell them what the Lord hath done for thee, and hath compassionated thee.
MAK|5|20||And he went, and began to publish in Decapolis, what Jesus had done for him. And they were all amazed.
MAK|5|21||And when Jesus had passed by ship to the other side, great multitudes again assembled about him as he was on the shore of the sea.
MAK|5|22||And one of the rulers of the synagogue, whose name was Jairus, came, and, on seeing him, fell at his feet,
MAK|5|23||and besought him much, and said to him: My daughter is very sick; but come and lay thy hand on her, and she will be cured, and will live.
MAK|5|24||And Jesus went with him; and a great company attended him, and pressed upon him.
MAK|5|25||And a woman who had had a defluxion of blood twelve years,
MAK|5|26||and who had suffered much from many physicians, and had expended all she possessed, and was not profited, but was even the more afflicted;
MAK|5|27||when she heard of Jesus, came behind him in the press of the crowd, and touched his garment
MAK|5|28||For she said: If I but touch his garment, I shall live.
MAK|5|29||And immediately the fountain of her blood dried up; and she felt in her body that she was healed of her plague.
MAK|5|30||And Jesus at once knew in himself, that virtue had issued from him: and he turned to the throng, and said: Who touched my clothes?
MAK|5|31||And his disciples said to him: Thou seest the throngs that press upon thee; and sayest thou, Who touched me?
MAK|5|32||And he looked around, to see who had done this.
MAK|5|33||And the woman, fearing and trembling, for she knew what had taken place in her, came and fell down before him, and told him all the truth.
MAK|5|34||And he said to her: My daughter, thy faith hath made thee live: go in peace; and be thou healed of thy plague.
MAK|5|35||And while he was speaking, some domestics of the ruler of the synagogue came, and said: Thy daughter is dead: why therefore troublest thou the teacher?
MAK|5|36||But Jesus heard the word they spoke, and said to the ruler of the synagogue: Fear not; only believe.
MAK|5|37||And he suffered no one to go with him, except Simon Cephas, and James, and John the brother of James.
MAK|5|38||And they came to the house of the ruler of the synagogue; and he saw, that they were in a tumult, and weeping, and howling.
MAK|5|39||And he entered in and said to them: Why are ye in a tumult, and weep? The maid is not dead, but is asleep.
MAK|5|40||And they laughed at him. But Jesus put them all out. And he took the maids father, and her mother, and those that accompanied him, and entered into where the maid lay.
MAK|5|41||And he took the maid's hand, and said to her: Maiden, arise.
MAK|5|42||And immediately the maid arose, and walked; for she was twelve years old. And they were astonished with a great astonishment.
MAK|5|43||And he enjoined it upon them much, that no one should know of it. And he directed, that they should give her to eat.
MAK|6|1||And Jesus departed from there and came to his own city, and his disciples attended him.
MAK|6|2||And when the sabbath came, he began to teach in the synagogue. And many who heard [him] were astonished, and said: Whence hath he obtained these things? And, what wisdom is this, which is given to him! and that such mighty works are done by his hands!
MAK|6|3||Is not this the carpenter, the son of Mary, and the brother of James and of Joses and of Judas and of Simon? And are not his sisters here with us? And they were stumbled in him.
MAK|6|4||And Jesus said to them: There is no prophet who is little, except in his own city, and among his kindred, and at home.
MAK|6|5||And he could not there do even one mighty work, except that he laid his hand on a few sick, and healed them.
MAK|6|6||And he wondered at the defect of their faith. And he travelled about the villages and taught.
MAK|6|7||And he called his twelve, and began to send them forth, two and two; and he gave them authority over unclean spirits, to cast them out.
MAK|6|8||And he commanded them to take nothing for the journey, except a staff only; neither a wallet, nor bread, nor brass in their purses;
MAK|6|9||but to be shod with sandals, and not put on two coats.
MAK|6|10||And he said to them: Into whatever house ye enter, there abide till ye leave the place.
MAK|6|11||And whoever will not receive you, nor hear you, when ye go out from that place shake off the dust that is under your feet, for a testimony to them. Verily I say to you, There will be comfort for Sodom and Gomorrah in the day of judgment rather than for that city.
MAK|6|12||And they went out and proclaimed, that [men] should repent.
MAK|6|13||And they cast out many demons, and many of the sick they anointed with oil, and healed them.
MAK|6|14||And Herod the king heard of Jesus,---for his name had become known to him,---and he said: John the Baptizer hath risen from the dead: and therefore it is, mighty deeds are done by him.
MAK|6|15||Others said: He is Elijah: and others: He is a prophet, like one of the prophets.
MAK|6|16||But when Herod heard [of him], he said: He is that John whose head I struck off: he is risen from the dead.
MAK|6|17||For Herod had sent and seized John and bound him in prison, on account of Herodias, his brother Philips wife, whom he had taken.
MAK|6|18||For John had said to Herod: It is not lawful for thee to take thy brother's wife.
MAK|6|19||And Herodias herself was an enemy to him, and wished to kill him, but was not able.
MAK|6|20||For Herod was afraid of John, because he knew him to be a just and holy man: and he observed him, and gave ear to him in many things and did [the things], and he heard him with satisfaction.
MAK|6|21||And there was a noted day, when Herod made a supper, in the house of his nativity, for his nobles and the chiliarchs and the chiefs of Galilee.
MAK|6|22||And the daughter of Herodias came in, and danced; and she pleased Herod and those reclining with him. And the king said to the maid: Ask of me what thou pleasest, and I will give it thee.
MAK|6|23||And he swore to her: Whatever thou shalt ask, I will give thee, even to the half of my kingdom.
MAK|6|24||And she went out, and said to her mother: What shall I ask of him? She said to her: The head of John the Baptizer.
MAK|6|25||And she soon entered with eagerness to the king, and said: I desire that thou, this hour, give me in a dish the head of John the Baptizer.
MAK|6|26||And it pained the king greatly; yet, on account of the oath, and on account of the guests, he would not deny her:
MAK|6|27||and the king sent immediately an executioner, and commanded [him] to bring the head of John. And he went, and struck off the head of John in the prison;
MAK|6|28||and brought it on a dish, and gave it to the maid; and the maid gave it to her mother.
MAK|6|29||And his disciples heard [of it]; and they came and took up the corpse, and laid it in a sepulchre.
MAK|6|30||And the legates assembled before Jesus, and told him all they had done, and all they had taught.
MAK|6|31||And he said to them: Come, let us go into a desert by ourselves, and rest a little. For there were many going and coming, and they had not opportunity even to eat bread.
MAK|6|32||And they went by ship to a desert place by themselves.
MAK|6|33||But many saw them, as they departed, and knew them; and from all the cities, they ran thither by land before him.
MAK|6|34||And Jesus disembarked and saw great multitudes: and he compassionated them, because they were like sheep having no shepherd. And he began to teach them many things.
MAK|6|35||And when the time was advanced, his disciples came to him, and said to him: This is a desert place, and the time is advanced.
MAK|6|36||Dismiss them, that they may go into the fields around us and into the villages, and may buy themselves bread; for they have nothing to eat.
MAK|6|37||And he said to them: Give ye them to eat. They say to him: Shall we go and buy bread of the value of two hundred denarii, and give them to eat?
MAK|6|38||And he said to them: Go, see how many loaves ye have here. And when they had seen, they say to him: Five loaves and two fishes.
MAK|6|39||And he bid them make the people recline on the grass by companies.
MAK|6|40||And they reclined, by companies of a hundred, and of fifty.
MAK|6|41||And he took the five loaves and the two fishes, and looked towards heaven, and blessed and brake the bread, and gave to his disciples to set before them: and they divided [also] the two fishes among them all.
MAK|6|42||And they all ate, and were satisfied.
MAK|6|43||And they took up twelve baskets full of the fragments and of the fishes.
MAK|6|44||And they who had eaten bread were five thousand men.
MAK|6|45||And he immediately constrained his disciples to take ship, and go before him to the other side, to Bethsaida, while he dismissed the multitudes.
MAK|6|46||And when he had dismissed them, he went to a mountain to pray.
MAK|6|47||And when evening came, the ship was in the middle of the sea, and he alone on the land.
MAK|6|48||And he saw them straining themselves in rowing; for the wind was against them. And in the fourth watch of the night, Jesus came to them walking on the waters; and he was disposed to pass by them.
MAK|6|49||And they saw him walking on the waters, and they supposed that the appearance was a spectre: and they cried out.
MAK|6|50||For they all saw him, and were afraid. And immediately he spoke with them, and said to them: Take courage; it is I; fear not.
MAK|6|51||And he entered into the ship to them; and the wind ceased. And they were greatly amazed, and astonished among themselves.
MAK|6|52||For they did not learn by the bread; because their heart was stupid.
MAK|6|53||And when they had passed to the other shore, they came to the land of Gennesaret.
MAK|6|54||And when they went out of the ship, immediately the men of the place knew him.
MAK|6|55||And they ran through all that region, and began to bring forth them that were sick, bearing them on beds to where they heard he was.
MAK|6|56||And wherever he entered into villages or cities, the sick were laid in he streets: and they besought him, that they might touch but the extremity of his raiment. And all they that touched him, were healed.
MAK|7|1||And there gathered about him Pharisees and Scribes, who had come from Jerusalem.
MAK|7|2||And they saw some of his disciples eating bread, with their hands unwashed; and they censured it.
MAK|7|3||For all the Jews and the Pharisees, unless they carefully wash their hands do not eat; because they hold fast the tradition of the Elders.
MAK|7|4||And [coming] from the market-place, except they baptize, they do not eat. And there are many other things which they have received to observe, [such as] the baptisms of cups, and of pots, and of brazen vessels, and of couches.
