LUK|1|7||But they had no child, because Elisabeth was barren: and they were both advanced in life.
LUK|1|8||And it occurred, that as he performed the priestly functions in the order of his ministration before the Lord,
LUK|1|9||according to the usage of the priesthood, it fell to him to offer the incense. And he went into the temple of the Lord,
LUK|1|10||and the whole multitude of the people were praying without, at the time of incense.
LUK|1|11||And the angel of the Lord appeared to Zachariah, standing on the right side of the altar of incense.
LUK|1|12||And when Zachariah saw him, he was agitated, and fear fell upon him.
LUK|1|13||And the angel said to him: Fear not, Zachariah; for thy prayer is heard, and thy wife Elisabeth will bear thee a son, and thou shalt call his name John.
LUK|1|14||And thou wilt have joy and gladness: and many will rejoice at his birth.
LUK|1|15||For he will be great before the Lord; and he will not drink wine nor strong drink, and will be filled with the Holy Spirit even from his mother's womb.
LUK|1|16||And many of the children of Israel will he convert to the Lord their God.
LUK|1|17||And he will go before him, in the spirit and power of Elijah the prophet, and will turn the heart of the fathers unto the children, and them that are disobedient to the knowledge of the righteous, and will prepare a perfect people for the Lord.
LUK|1|18||And Zachariah said to the angel: How shall I know this? For I am old, and my wife is advanced in life.
LUK|1|19||The angel answered, and said to him: I am Gabriel, who stand before God; and I am sent to converse with thee, and to tell thee these things.
LUK|1|20||Henceforth thou wilt be dumb, and unable to speak, until the day when these things take place: because thou believedst not my words, which will be fulfilled in their time.
LUK|1|21||And the people were standing and waiting for Zachariah; and they wondered at his tarrying so long in the temple.
LUK|1|22||And when Zachariah came forth, he could not speak with them: and they understood that he had seen a vision in the temple: and he made many signs to them, and remained speechless.
LUK|1|23||And when the days of his ministration were accomplished, he came to his house.
LUK|1|24||And it was after those days, that Elisabeth his wife conceived. And she secluded herself five months; and she said:
LUK|1|25||These things hath the Lord done for me, in the days when he looked upon me to take away my reproach among men.
LUK|1|26||And in the sixth month, the angel Gabriel was sent by God into Galilee, to a city named Nazareth,
LUK|1|27||to a virgin espoused to a man whose name was Joseph, of the house of David; and the virgin's name was Mary.
LUK|1|28||And the angel entered the house, and said to her: Peace to thee, thou full of grace! The Lord is with thee: and blessed art thou among women.
LUK|1|29||And when she saw [him], she was agitated by his speech; and she pondered, what this salutation could mean.
LUK|1|30||And the angel said to her: Fear not, Mary; for thou hast found favor with God.
LUK|1|31||For lo, thou wilt conceive in thy womb, and wilt bear a son, and wilt call his name Jesus.
LUK|1|32||He will be great, and will be called the Son of the Most High, and the Lord God will give him the throne of his father David.
LUK|1|33||And he will reign over the house of Jacob for ever; and of his reign there will be no end.
LUK|1|34||And Mary said to the angel: How can this be, as I have not known a man?
LUK|1|35||The angel replied, and said to her: The Holy Spirit will come, and the power of the Most High will overshadow thee; therefore he that is born of thee is holy, and will be called the Son of God.
LUK|1|36||And lo, Elisabeth thy kinswoman, even she too hath conceived a son in her old age; and this is the sixth month with her who is called barren.
LUK|1|37||Because nothing is difficult for God.
LUK|1|38||Mary said: Behold, I am the handmaid of the Lord; be it to me, according to thy word. And the angel departed from her.
LUK|1|39||And Mary arose in those days, and went hastily to the mountain [district], to a city of Judaea;
LUK|1|40||and entered the house of Zachariah, and saluted Elisabeth.
LUK|1|41||And it was so, that when Elisabeth heard the salutation of Mary, the child leaped in her womb, and she was filled with the Holy Spirit.
LUK|1|42||And she cried out with a loud voice, and said to Mary: Blessed art thou among women; and blessed is the fruit of thy womb.
LUK|1|43||And whence is this to me, that the mother of my Lord should come to me?
LUK|1|44||For lo, as the voice of thy salutation fell upon my ears, with great joy the child leaped in my womb.
LUK|1|45||And happy is she that believed; for there will be a fulfillment of those things that were told her by the Lord.
LUK|1|46||And Mary said: My soul doth magnify the Lord:
LUK|1|47||and my spirit rejoiceth in God the author of my life.
LUK|1|48||For he hath looked upon the humble condition of his hand maid; and lo, henceforth all generations will ascribe blessedness to me.
LUK|1|49||And He that is mighty hath done for me great things; and holy is his name.
LUK|1|50||And his mercy is on them that fear him, for generations and posterities.
LUK|1|51||He hath wrought victory with his arm; and hath scattered the proud in the imagination of their heart.
LUK|1|52||He hath cast down the mighty from their thrones, and hath exalted the lowly.
LUK|1|53||The hungry hath he satisfied with good things, and the rich hath he sent away empty.
LUK|1|54||He hath aided Israel his servant, and remembered his mercy,
LUK|1|55||(as he spoke with the fathers,) with Abraham and his seed, for ever.
LUK|1|56||And Mary remained with Elisabeth about three months, and returned to her home.
LUK|1|57||And Elisabeth's time of bringing forth arrived; and she bore a son.
LUK|1|58||And her neighbors and relatives heard that the Lord had magnified his mercy to her, and they rejoiced with her.
LUK|1|59||And it occurred, that on the eighth day they came to circumcise the child. And they called him by the name of his father, Zachariah.
LUK|1|60||And his mother answered and said: Not so; but John, shall he be called.
LUK|1|61||And they said to her: There is no one among thy kindred called by that name.
LUK|1|62||And they made signs to his father, how he would have him named.
LUK|1|63||And he asked for a tablet, and wrote, and said: John is his name. And every one was surprised.
LUK|1|64||And immediately his mouth was opened, and his tongue; and he spoke, and praised God.
LUK|1|65||And fear came upon all their neighbors; and these things were talked of in all the mountain [district] of Judaea.
LUK|1|66||And all who heard, pondered them in their heart, and said: What will this child be? And the hand of the Lord was with him.
LUK|1|67||And Zachariah his father was filled with the Holy Spirit, and prophesied, and said:
LUK|1|68||Blessed be the Lord God of Israel, who hath visited his people, and wrought redemption for them:
LUK|1|69||And hath raised up a horn of redemption for us, in the house of David his servant:
LUK|1|70||as he spake by the mouth of his holy prophets, who were of old,
LUK|1|71||that he would redeem us from our enemies, and from the hand of all that hate us.
LUK|1|72||And he hath exercised his mercy to our fathers, and hath remembered his holy covenants,
LUK|1|73||and the oath that he sware to Abraham our father, that he would grant to us,
LUK|1|74||to be redeemed from the hand of our enemies; and that we should worship before him, without fear,
LUK|1|75||all our days, in rectitude and uprightness.
LUK|1|76||And thou, child, wilt be called a prophet of the Most High; for thou wilt go before the face of the Lord, to prepare his way,
LUK|1|77||that he may give the knowledge of life to his people, and forgiveness of their sins,
LUK|1|78||through the compassion of the mercy of our God; whereby the day-spring from on high will visit us,
LUK|1|79||to give light to them that sit in darkness, and in the shadow of death; and to guide our feet into the way of peace.
LUK|1|80||And the child grew, and was strengthened in spirit. And he was in the wilderness, until the day of his manifestation to Israel.
LUK|2|1||And in those days it occurred, that a decree went forth from Augustus Caesar, that all the people of his dominion should be enrolled.
LUK|2|2||And this enrollment was first made under the presidency of Quirinus in Syria.
LUK|2|3||And everyone went to his own city to be enrolled.
LUK|2|4||And Joseph also went up from Nazareth of Galilee to Judaea, to the city of David which is called Bethlehem, because he was of the house and lineage of David,
LUK|2|5||with Mary his espoused, then pregnant, to be enrolled.
LUK|2|6||And it was while they were there, that the days for her to bring forth were completed.
LUK|2|7||And she brought forth her firstborn son, and wrapped him in bandages, and laid him in the stall; for they had no place where they could lodge.
LUK|2|8||And there were shepherds in that region, who abode there and kept watch of their flocks by night.
LUK|2|9||And lo, the angel of God came to them, and the glory of the Lord shone upon them: and they feared with great fear.
LUK|2|10||And the angel said to them: Fear not; for, behold I announce to you great joy, which will be to all the world.
LUK|2|11||For there is born to you this day a deliverer, who is the Lord Messiah, in the city of David
LUK|2|12||And this is the sign for you: Ye will find the babe wrapped in bandages, and placed in a stall.
LUK|2|13||And instantly there were seen with the angel, the many hosts of heaven, praising God, and saying:
LUK|2|14||Glory to God in the highest [heavens], and on earth peace and good hope for men.
LUK|2|15||And it was so, that when the angels had gone from them into heaven, the shepherds conferred with one another, and said: Let us go down to Bethlehem, and see this thing which hath occurred, as the Lord hath made known to us.
LUK|2|16||And they came hastily, and found Mary and Joseph, and the babe laid in the stall.
LUK|2|17||And when they saw, they made known the information which was given to them concerning the child.
LUK|2|18||And all that heard, wondered at the things that were told them by the shepherds.
LUK|2|19||And Mary laid up all these things, and pondered them in her heart.
LUK|2|20||And the shepherds returned glorifying and praising God for all that they had seen and heard, as it was told them.
LUK|2|21||And when the eight days for the circumcision of the child were completed, his name was called JESUS; as he was named by the angel, before he was conceived in the womb.
LUK|2|22||And when the days of their purification were completed, according to the law of Moses, they carried him to Jerusalem, to present him before the Lord:
LUK|2|23||(as it is written in the law of the Lord, that every male opening the womb shall be called holy to the Lord:)
LUK|2|24||and to offer a sacrifice, according as it is written in the law of the Lord, A pair of turtle-doves, or two young pigeons.
LUK|2|25||And there was a certain man in Jerusalem, whose name was Simeon. This man was upright and just, and was waiting for the consolation of Israel, and the Holy Spirit was upon him.
LUK|2|26||And it had been told him by the Holy Spirit, that he would not see death, until he should see the Messiah of the Lord.
LUK|2|27||This man came, by the Spirit, into the temple; and when his parents brought in the child Jesus, to do for him as is commanded in the law,
LUK|2|28||he took him in his arms, and blessed God, and said:
LUK|2|29||My Lord, now release thou thy servant in peace, as thou hast said:
LUK|2|30||for lo, my eyes have seen thy mercy,
LUK|2|31||which thou hast prepared in the presence of all nations,
LUK|2|32||a light for a revelation to the Gentiles, and a glory for thy people Israel.
LUK|2|33||And Joseph and his mother were astonished at those things which were spoken concerning him.
LUK|2|34||And Simeon blessed them, and said to Mary his mother: Behold, this [child] is set forth for the fall and for the rising of many in Israel, and for a standard of contention;
LUK|2|35||(and also a dart will pierce thy own soul); that the thoughts of the hearts of many may be disclosed.
LUK|2|36||And Hanna, a prophetess, the daughter of Phanuel, of the tribe of Asher,---she also was aged in days, and, from her maidenhood, had lived seven years with her husband,
LUK|2|37||and was a widow of about eighty and four years, and departed not from the temple, but worshipped by day and by night with fasting and prayer;
LUK|2|38||and she too stood up, in that hour, and gave thanks to the Lord, and spoke of him to every one that waited for the redemption of Jerusalem.
LUK|2|39||And when they had accomplished all things, according to the law of the Lord, they returned to Galilee, to their city Nazareth.
LUK|2|40||And the child grew, and was strengthened in spirit, and was filled with wisdom; and the grace of God was upon him.
LUK|2|41||And his people went up to Jerusalem every year, at the feast of the passover.
LUK|2|42||And when he was twelve years old, they went up to the feast, as they were accustomed.
LUK|2|43||And when the days were completed, they returned: but the child Jesus remained at Jerusalem, and Joseph and his mother knew not [of it];
LUK|2|44||for they supposed he was with his companions. And when they had travelled a day's journey, they sought him among their people, and [inquired] of every one that knew them.
LUK|2|45||And they did not find him. And they returned again to Jerusalem, searching for him.
LUK|2|46||And after three days, they found him in the temple, sitting in the midst of the teachers, and listening to them, and asking them questions.
LUK|2|47||And all they that heard him, were astonished at his wisdom and his answers.
LUK|2|48||And when they saw him they were amazed. And his mother said to him: My son, why hast thou done so to us? For lo, I and thy father have been seeking for thee with great anxiety.
LUK|2|49||He said to them: Why did ye seek me? Do ye not know, that it behooveth me to be in my Father's house?
LUK|2|50||But they did not comprehend the word that he spoke to them.
LUK|2|51||And he went down with them, and came to Nazareth, and was obedient to them. And his mother laid up all these things in her heart.
LUK|2|52||And Jesus increased in stature, and in wisdom, and in grace, before God and men.
LUK|3|1||And in the fifteenth year of the reign of Tiberius Caesar, in the presidency of Pontius Pilate in Judaea, while Herod was Tetrarch in Galilee, and Philip his brother Tetrarch in Ituraea and in the region of Trachonitis, and Lysanias Tetrarch of Abilene,
LUK|3|2||in the high priesthood of Annas and of Caiaphas; the word of God was upon John the son of Zachariah, in the wilderness.
LUK|3|3||And he came into all the region about the Jordan, proclaiming the baptism of repentance for the forgiveness of sins.
LUK|3|4||As it is written in the book of the discourses of Isaiah the prophet, who said: The voice of one crying in the wilderness, Prepare ye the way of the Lord; and make straight paths in the plain for our God.
LUK|3|5||All valleys shall be filled up, and all mountains and hills be lowered; and the hillock shall be levelled down, and the rough place become smooth.
LUK|3|6||And all flesh shall see the life which is of God.
LUK|3|7||And he said to the multitudes, who came to him to be baptized: Ye progeny of vipers, who hath instructed you to flee from the future wrath?
LUK|3|8||Bring forth, therefore, fruits comporting with repentance. And begin not to say in yourselves: We have Abraham for our father; for I say to you, that God can, from these stones, raise up sons to Abraham.
LUK|3|9||And lo, the ax is put to the root of trees. Every tree therefore that beareth not good fruits, is hewed down, and falleth into the fire.
LUK|3|10||And the multitudes asked him, and said: What, then, shall we do?
LUK|3|11||He answered and said to them: Whoever hath two tunics, let him give [one] to him that hath none; and whoever hath food, let him do the same.
LUK|3|12||And publicans also came to be baptized. And they said to him: Teacher, what shall we do?
LUK|3|13||And he said to them: Exact no more than ye are required to exact.
LUK|3|14||And those serving in war inquired of him, and said: And what shall we do? He said to them: Be insolent to no one, and oppress no one, and let your pay satisfy you.
LUK|3|15||And while the people were thinking of John, and all pondered in their heart, whether he were the Messiah;
LUK|3|16||John answered and said to them: Behold, I baptize you with water; but after me cometh one mightier than I, the strings of whose shoes I am not worthy to untie; he will baptize you with the Holy Spirit and with fire.
LUK|3|17||He holdeth his winnowing shovel in his hand, and he will make clean his threshing floor; and the wheat he gathereth into his garners, and the chaff he will burn with fire not extinguished.
LUK|3|18||And many other things also, he taught and proclaimed to the people.
LUK|3|19||But Herod the Tetrarch, because he was reproved by John, on account of Herodias the wife of his brother Philip, and on account of all the evil things he had done,
LUK|3|20||added this also to them all, that he shut up John in prison.
LUK|3|21||And it occurred, when all the people were baptized, that Jesus also was baptized. And as he prayed, the heavens were opened;
LUK|3|22||and the Holy Spirit descended upon him, in the bodily likeness of a dove: and there was a voice from heaven, which said: Thou art my beloved Son, in whom I have delight.
LUK|3|23||And Jesus was about thirty years old. And he was accounted the son of Joseph, the son of Heli,
LUK|3|24||the son of Matthat, the son of Levi, the son of Melchi, the son of Janna, the son of Joseph,
LUK|3|25||the son of Mattathias, the son of Amos, the son of Nahum, the son of Esli, the son of Naggai,
LUK|3|26||the son of Maath, the son of Mattathias, the son of Shimei, the son of Joseph, the son of Judah,
LUK|3|27||the son of Joanna, the son of Rhesa, the son of Zorubbabel, the son of Salathiel, the son of Neri,
LUK|3|28||the son of Melchi, the son of Addi, the son of Cosam, the son of Elmodam, the son of Er,
LUK|3|29||the son of Joses, the son of Eliezer, the son of Joram, the son of Matthat, the son of Levi,
LUK|3|30||the son of Simeon, the son of Judah, the son of Joseph, the son of Jonam, the son of Eliakim,
LUK|3|31||the son of Melcah, the son of Mainan, the son of Mattatha, the son of Nathan, the son of David,
LUK|3|32||the son of Jesse, the son of Obed, the son of Boaz, the son of Salmon, the son of Nahshon
LUK|3|33||the son of Amminadab, the son of Ram, the son of Hezron, the son of Pharez, the son of Judah
LUK|3|34||the son of Jacob, the son of Isaac, the son of Abraham, the son of Terah, the son of Nahor,
LUK|3|35||the son of Serug, the son of Reu, the son of Peleg, the son of Eber, the son of Salah,
LUK|3|36||the son of Cainan, the son of Arphaxad, the son of Shem, the son of Noah, the son of Lamech,
LUK|3|37||the son of Methuselah, the son of Enoch, the son of Jared, the son of Mehalaleel, the son of Cainan,
