ROM|6|12||Therefore let not sin reign in your dead body, so that ye obey its lusts.
ROM|6|13||And also give not up your members as instruments of evil unto sin, but give up yourselves to God, as those who have been resuscitated from the dead; and let your members be instruments for the righteousness of God.
ROM|6|14||And sin shall not have dominion over you; for ye are not under the law, but under grace.
ROM|6|15||What then? Shall we sin, because we are not under the law, but under grace? Far be it.
ROM|6|16||Know ye not, that to whomsoever ye give up yourselves to serve in bondage, his servants ye are, whom ye serve; whether it be to sin, or whether it be to righteousness, that ye give ear?
ROM|6|17||But thanks be to God, that ye were [once] the servants of sin but have [now] from the heart obeyed that form of doctrine to which ye are devoted.
ROM|6|18||And when ye were emancipated from sin, ye became servants to righteousness.
ROM|6|19||(I speak as among men, because of the infirmity of your flesh.)As ye [once] gave up your members to the servitude of pollution and iniquity, so also now give ye up your members to the servitude of righteousness and sanctity.
ROM|6|20||For when ye were the servants of sin, ye were emancipated from righteousness.
ROM|6|21||And what harvest had ye then, in that of which ye are now ashamed? For the result thereof is death.
ROM|6|22||And now, as ye have been emancipated from sin, and have become servants to God, your fruits are holy; and the result thereof is life everlasting.
ROM|6|23||For the wages of sin is death; but the free gift of God is life eternal, through our Lord Jesus Messiah.
ROM|7|1||Or do ye not know, my Brethren.(for I am speaking to them that know the law,) that the law hath dominion over a man, as long as he is alive?
ROM|7|2||Just as a woman, by the law, is bound to her husband, as long as he is alive: but if her husband should die, she is freed from the law of her husband.
ROM|7|3||And if, while her husband is alive, she should adhere to another man, she would become an adulteress: but if her husband should die, she is freed from the law; and would not be an adulteress though joined to another man.
ROM|7|4||And now, my brethren, ye also have become dead to the law, by the body of Messiah; that ye might be joined to another, [even] to him who arose from the dead; and might yield fruits unto God.
ROM|7|5||For while we were in the flesh, the emotions of sin which are by the law, were active in our members, that we should bear fruits unto death.
ROM|7|6||But now we are absolved from the law, and are dead to that which held us in its grasp: that we might henceforth serve in the newness of the spirit, and not in the oldness of the letter.
ROM|7|7||What shall we say then? Is the law sin?, Far be it. For I had not learned sin, except by means of the law: for I had not known concupiscence, had not the law said, Thou shalt not covet:
ROM|7|8||and by this commandment, sin found occasion, and perfected in me all concupiscence: for without the law, sin was dead.
ROM|7|9||And I, without the law, was alive formerly; but when the commandment came, sin became alive, and I died;
ROM|7|10||and the commandment of life was found by me [to be] unto death.
ROM|7|11||For sin, by the occasion which it found by means of the commandment, seduced me; and thereby slew me.
ROM|7|12||Wherefore, the law is holy; and the commandment is holy, and righteous, and good.
ROM|7|13||Did that which is good, therefore, become death to me? Far be it. But sin, that it might be seen to be sin, perfected death in me by means of that good [law]; that sin might the more be condemned, by means of the commandment.
ROM|7|14||For we know, that the law is spiritual; but I am carnal, and sold to sin.
ROM|7|15||For what I am doing, I know not: and what I would, I do not perform; but what I hate, that I do.
ROM|7|16||And if I do what I would not, I testify of the law, that it is right.
ROM|7|17||And then, it is no more I who do that thing; but sin, which dwelleth in me.
ROM|7|18||For I know, that in me, (that is, in my flesh,) good dwelleth not: because, to approve the good, is easy for me; but to do it, I am unable.
ROM|7|19||For I do not perform the good, which I would perform; but the bad, which I would not perform, that I do perform.
ROM|7|20||And if I do what I would not, it is not I that do it, but sin which dwelleth in me.
ROM|7|21||I find therefore a law coinciding with my conscience, which assenteth to my doing good, whereas evil is near to me.
ROM|7|22||For I rejoice in the law of God, in the interior man.
ROM|7|23||But I see another law in my members, which warreth against the law of my conscience, and maketh me a captive to the law of sin which existeth in my members
ROM|7|24||O, a miserable man, am I! Who will rescue me from this body of death?
ROM|7|25||I thank God; by means of our Lord Jesus Messiah [I shall be rescued.] Now, therefore, in my conscience, I am a servant of the law of God; but in my flesh, I am a servant of the law of sin.
ROM|8|1||There is therefore no condemnation, to them who, in Jesus Messiah, walk not after the flesh.
ROM|8|2||For the law of the spirit of life, which is in Jesus Messiah, hath emancipated thee from the law of sin and death.
ROM|8|3||Inasmuch as the law was impotent, by means of the weakness of the flesh, God sent his Son in the likeness of sinful flesh, on account of sin; that He might, in his flesh, condemn sin;
ROM|8|4||so that the righteousness of the law might be fulfilled in us; since it is not in the flesh that we walk, but in the Spirit.
ROM|8|5||For they who are in the flesh, do mind the things of the flesh: and they who are of the Spirit, do mind the things of the Spirit.
ROM|8|6||For minding the things of the flesh, is death; but minding the things of the Spirit, is life and peace.
ROM|8|7||Because minding the things of the flesh, is enmity towards God: for it doth not subject itself to the law of God, because it is not possible.
ROM|8|8||And they who are in the flesh cannot please God.
ROM|8|9||Ye, however, are not in the flesh, but in the Spirit; if the Spirit of God truly dwelleth in you. And if in any one there is not the Spirit of Messiah he is none of his.
ROM|8|10||But if Messiah is in you, the body is dead, in regard to sin; and the Spirit is alive in regard to righteousness.
ROM|8|11||And if the Spirit of him, who raised our Lord Jesus Messiah from the dead, dwelleth in you; he who raised our Lord Jesus Messiah from the dead, will also vivify your dead bodies, because of his Spirit that dwelleth in you.
ROM|8|12||Now we are debtors, my Brethren, not to the flesh, that we should walk according to the flesh:
ROM|8|13||(For if ye live according to the flesh, ye are to die. But if, by the Spirit, ye mortify the practices of the body, ye will live.
ROM|8|14||For they who are led by the Spirit of God, they are the sons of God:)
ROM|8|15||For ye have not received the spirit of bondage, again to fear; but ye have received the Spirit of adoption, by which we cry, Father, our Father.
ROM|8|16||And this Spirit testifieth to our spirit, that we are the sons of God.
ROM|8|17||And if sons, then heirs; heirs of God, and participators of the inheritance of Jesus Messiah: so that, if we suffer with him, we shall also be glorified with him.
ROM|8|18||For I reckon, that the sufferings of the present time, are not comparable with the glory which is to be developed in us.
ROM|8|19||For the whole creation is hoping and waiting for the development of the sons of God.
ROM|8|20||For the creation was subjected to vanity, not by its own choice, but because of him who subjected it,
ROM|8|21||in the hope, that also the creation itself would be emancipated from the bondage of corruption, into the liberty of the glory of the sons of God.
ROM|8|22||For we know, that all the creatures are groaning and travailing in pain unto this day.
ROM|8|23||And not only they, but we also in whom are the first fruits of the Spirit, we groan within ourselves, and look anxiously for the adoption of sons, the redemption of our bodies.
ROM|8|24||Because we live in hope. But hope that is seen, is not hope: for if we saw it, how should we hope for it?
ROM|8|25||But if we hope for that which is not seen, we are in patient waiting.
ROM|8|26||So also the Spirit aideth our weakness. For we know not what to pray for, in a proper manner; but the Spirit prayeth for us, with groans not expressible:
ROM|8|27||and the explorer of hearts, he knoweth what is the mind of the Spirit; because he prayeth for the saints, agreeably to the good pleasure of God.
ROM|8|28||And we know that he aideth him in all things, for good, who love God; them whom he predestined to be called.
ROM|8|29||And he knew them, previously; and he sealed them with the likeness of the image of his Son; that He might be the first-born of many brothers.
ROM|8|30||And those whom he previously sealed, them he called: and those whom he called, them he justified: and those whom he justified, them he glorified.
ROM|8|31||What then shall we say of these things? If God [is] for us; who [is] against us?
ROM|8|32||And, if he spared not his Son, but gave him up for us all, how shall he not give us all things, with him?
ROM|8|33||Who will set himself against the chosen of God? It is God who justifieth.
ROM|8|34||Who is it that condemneth? Messiah died, and arose, and is on the right hand of God, and maketh intercession for us.
ROM|8|35||What will sever me from the love of Messiah? Will affliction? or distress? or persecution? or famine? or nakedness? or peril? or the sword?
ROM|8|36||As it is written: For thy sake, we die daily: and, we are accounted as sheep for the slaughter.
ROM|8|37||But in all these things we are victorious, by means of him who loved us.
ROM|8|38||For I am persuaded, that neither death, nor life, nor angels, nor principalities, nor powers, nor things present, nor things to come,
ROM|8|39||nor height, nor depth, nor any other creature, will be able to sever me from the love of God, which is in our Lord Jesus Messiah.
ROM|9|1||I say the truth in Messiah, and do not misrepresent; and my conscience beareth me witness in the Holy Spirit;
ROM|9|2||that I have great sorrow, and the sadness of my heart is unceasing.
ROM|9|3||For I have prayed, that I myself might be accursed from Messiah, for my brethren and my kinsmen in the flesh:
ROM|9|4||who are sons of Israel, to whom belonged the adoption of sons, and the glory, and the covenants, and the law, and the ministration, and the promises, and the fathers;
ROM|9|5||and from among whom, Messiah appeared in the flesh, who is God over all; to whom be praises and benediction, for ever and ever; Amen.
ROM|9|6||Not, however, that the word of God hath actually failed. For all are not Israel, who are of Israel.
ROM|9|7||Neither are they all sons, because they are of the seed of Abraham: for it was said, In Isaac shall thy seed be called.
ROM|9|8||That is, it is not the children of the flesh, who are the children of God; but the children of the promise, are accounted for the seed.
ROM|9|9||For the word of promise was this: At that time will I come, and Sarah shall have a son.
ROM|9|10||Nor this only; but Rebecca also, when she had cohabited with one [man], our father Isaac,
ROM|9|11||before her children were born, or: had done good or evil, the choice of God was predeclared; that it might stand, not of works, but of him who called.
ROM|9|12||For it was said: The elder shall be servant to the younger.
ROM|9|13||As it is written: Jacob have I loved, and Esau have I hated.
ROM|9|14||What shall we say then? Is there iniquity with God? Far be it.
ROM|9|15||Behold, to Moses also he said: I will have pity, on whom I will have pity; and I will be merciful, to whom I will be merciful.
ROM|9|16||Therefore, it is not of him who is willing, nor of him who runneth, but of the merciful God.
ROM|9|17||For in the scripture, he said to Pharaoh: For this very thing, have I raised thee up; that I might shew my power in thee, and that my name might be proclaimed in all the earth.
ROM|9|18||Wherefore, he hath pity upon whom he pleaseth; and whom he pleaseth, he hardeneth.
ROM|9|19||But, perhaps thou wilt say: Of what [then] doth he complain? For, who hath resisted his pleasure?
ROM|9|20||Thou, thus! Who art thou? O man; that thou repliest against God! Shall the potter's vessel say to the former of it, Why hast thou formed me so?
ROM|9|21||Hath not the potter dominion over his clay out of the same mass to make vessels, one for honor, and another for dishonor?
ROM|9|22||And if God, being disposed to exhibit his wrath and to make known his power, in abundance of long-suffering, brought wrath upon the vessels of wrath which were complete for destruction;
ROM|9|23||and made his mercy flow forth upon the vessels of mercy, which were prepared by God for glory;
ROM|9|24||namely, upon us who are called, not of the Jews only, but also of the Gentiles:
ROM|9|25||As also he said in Hosea: I will call them my people, who were not my people; and will pity, whom I have not pitied:
ROM|9|26||For it shall be, that in the place where they were called: Not my people, there shall they be called: The children of the living God.
ROM|9|27||And Isaiah proclaimed concerning the children of Israel: Though the number of the children of Israel should be as the sand on the sea, a remnant of them will live.
ROM|9|28||He hath finished and cut short the matter: and the Lord will do it on the earth.
ROM|9|29||And according to what Isaiah had before said: If the Lord of hosts had not favored us with a residue, we had been as Sodom, and had been like Gomorrha.
ROM|9|30||What shall we say then? That the Gentiles, who ran not after righteousness, have found righteousness, even the righteousness which is by faith:
ROM|9|31||But Israel, who ran after the law of righteousness, hath not found the law of righteousness.
ROM|9|32||And why? Because [they sought it], not by faith, but by the works of the law. For they stumbled at that stumbling-stone:
ROM|9|33||As it is written, Behold, I lay in Zion a stumbling-stone, and a stone of offence: and he who believeth in him, shall not be ashamed.
ROM|10|1||My Brethren, The desire of my heart, and my intercession with God for them, is, that they might have life.
ROM|10|2||For I bear them witness, that there is in them a zeal for God; but it is not according to knowledge.
ROM|10|3||For they know not the righteousness of God, but seek to establish their own righteousness: and therefore they have not submitted themselves to the righteousness of God.
ROM|10|4||For Messiah is the aim of the law, for righteousness, unto every one that believeth in him.
ROM|10|5||For Moses describeth the righteousness, which is by the law, thus: Whoever shall do these things, shall live by them.
ROM|10|6||But the righteousness which is by faith, saith thus: Thou shalt not say in thy heart, Who ascendeth to heaven, and bringeth Messiah down?
ROM|10|7||Or, Who descendeth to the abyss of the grave, and bringeth up Messiah from the place of the dead?
ROM|10|8||But what saith it? The thing is near to thy mouth, and to thy heart: that is, the word of faith, which we proclaim.
ROM|10|9||And if thou shalt confess with thy mouth our Lord Jesus, and shalt believe with thy heart, that God hath raised him from the dead; thou shalt live.
ROM|10|10||For the heart that believeth in him, is justified; and the mouth that confesseth him, is restored to life.
ROM|10|11||For the scripture saith: Every one that believeth in him, shall not be ashamed.
ROM|10|12||And in this, it discriminateth neither Jews nor Gentiles. For there is one Lord over them all, who is rich, towards every one that calleth on him.
ROM|10|13||For every one that shall call on the name of the Lord, will have life.
ROM|10|14||How then shall they call on him, in whom they have not believed? Or, how shall they believe in him, of whom they have not heard? Or, how shall they hear, without a preacher?
ROM|10|15||Or, how shall they preach, if they are not sent forth? As it is written: How beautiful are the feet of the heralds of peace, and of the heralds of good things?
ROM|10|16||But all of them have not obeyed the proclamation of the gospel. (For, Isaiah said: My Lord, who hath believed our proclamation?)
ROM|10|17||Therefore, faith is from the hearing of the ear; and the hearing of the ear, is from the word of God.
ROM|10|18||But I say: Have they not heard? And, lo, their proclamation hath gone out into all the earth; and their words to the ends of the world.
ROM|10|19||But I say: Did not Israel know? First, Moses said, thus: I will awaken your emulation, by a people which is not a people; and by a disobedient people, I will provoke you.
ROM|10|20||And Isaiah was bold, and said: I was seen by those who sought me not; and I was found by those who inquired not for me.
ROM|10|21||But to Israel, he said: All the day, have I stretched out my hands to a contentious and disobedient people.
ROM|11|1||But I say: Hath God cast off his people? Far be it. For I also am of Israel, of the seed of Abraham, of the tribe of Benjamin.
ROM|11|2||God hath not cast off those his people whom he before knew. Do ye not know, what, in the scripture of God, he said to Elijah? When he had complained to God against Israel, and said:
ROM|11|3||My Lord, they have slain thy prophets, and have thrown down thy altars; and I am left alone; and they seek my life.
ROM|11|4||And it was said to him, by revelation: Behold, I have reserved for myself seven thousand men, who have not bowed their knees, and have not worshipped Baal.
ROM|11|5||So also at the present time, a remnant is preserved, by the election of grace.
ROM|11|6||But if by grace, it is not by works: otherwise, grace is not grace. And if by works, it is not by grace: Otherwise, work is not work.
ROM|11|7||What then? Israel did not obtain that which it sought: but the election obtained it; and the rest of them were blinded in their heart,
ROM|11|8||(as it is written: God gave them a stupid spirit, and eyes to see not, and ears to hear not), unto this very day.
ROM|11|9||And again, David said: Let their table become a snare before them; and let their recompense be a stumbling block.
ROM|11|10||Let their eyes be darkened, that they see not; and let their back, at all times, be bowed down.
ROM|11|11||But I say: Have they so stumbled as to fall entirely? Far be it. Rather, by their stumbling, life hath come to the Gentiles, for [awakening] their jealousy.
ROM|11|12||And if their stumbling was riches to the world, and their condemnation riches to the Gentiles; how much more their completeness?
ROM|11|13||But [it is] to you Gentiles, I am speaking: as I am a legate to the Gentiles, I honor my ministry;
ROM|11|14||if, perhaps, I may provoke emulation in the children of my flesh, and may vivify some of them.
ROM|11|15||For if the rejection of them, was a reconciliation of the world; what will their conversion be, but life from the dead?
ROM|11|16||For, if the first-fruits [are] holy, then the mass [is] also: and if the root is holy, then also the branches.
ROM|11|17||And if some of the branches were plucked off; and thou, an olive from the desert, wast in-grafted in their place, and hast become a participator of the root and fatness of the olive-tree;
ROM|11|18||do not glory over the branches. For if thou gloriest, thou sustainest not the root, but the root sustaineth thee.
ROM|11|19||And shouldst thou say, The branches were plucked off, that I might be grafted into their place.
ROM|11|20||Very true. They were plucked off, because they believed not; and thou standest by faith. Be not exalted in thy mind, but fear.
ROM|11|21||For if God spared not the natural branches, perhaps he will not spare you.
ROM|11|22||Behold now the benignity and the severity of God: on them who fell, severity; but on thee, benignity, if thou continuest in that benignity; and if not, thou also wilt be plucked off.
ROM|11|23||And they, if they do not continue in their destitution of faith, even they will be grafted in; for God is able to graft them in again.
ROM|11|24||For if thou wast plucked from the wild olive-tree, which was natural to thee, and wast grafted, contrary to thy nature, into a good olive-tree; how much more may they be grafted into their natural olive-tree?
ROM|11|25||And that ye, my brethren, may not be wise in your own apprehension, I wish you to know this mystery, that blindness of heart hath in some measure befallen Israel, until the fullness of the Gentiles shall come in:
ROM|11|26||and then, will all Israel live. As it is written: A deliverer will come from Zion, and will turn away iniquity from Jacob.
ROM|11|27||And then will they have the covenant that proceedeth from me, when I shall have forgiven their sins.
ROM|11|28||Now, in the gospel, they are enemies for your sake; but in the election, they are beloved for the fathers' sake.
ROM|11|29||For God is not changeable in his free gift and in his calling.
ROM|11|30||For as ye too were formerly disobedient to God, and have now obtained mercy, because of their disobedience;
ROM|11|31||so also are they now disobedient to the mercy, which is upon you, that there may be mercy on them likewise.
ROM|11|32||For God hath shut up all men in disobedience, that upon all men he might have mercy.
ROM|11|33||O the depth of the riches, and the wisdom, and the knowledge of God! For man hath not searched out his judgments; and his ways are inscrutable.
ROM|11|34||For who hath known the mind of the Lord? Or who hath been a counsellor to him?
ROM|11|35||Or who hath first given to him, and then received from him?
ROM|11|36||Because, all is from him, and all by him, and all through him: to whom be praises and benedictions, for ever and ever: Amen.
ROM|12|1||I beseech you, therefore, my brethren, by the mercies of God, that ye present your bodies a living sacrifice, holy and acceptable to God, by a rational service [of him].
ROM|12|2||And be not conformed to this world; but be ye transformed, by the renovation of your minds: and discern ye what is the good and acceptable and perfect pleasure of God.
ROM|12|3||And, by the grace given to me, I say to you all: Do not carry thoughts, beyond what ye ought to think; but think with modesty, as God hath distributed to each one his measure of faith.
ROM|12|4||For as we [severally] have many members in one body, and all those members have not the same functions;
ROM|12|5||so also we, who are [collectively] many persons, are one body in Messiah, and are naturally members of each other.
ROM|12|6||But we have different gifts, according to the grace given to us. There is that of prophecy, according to the measure of his faith.
ROM|12|7||And there is that of ministration, possessed by one in his ministry. And there is that of a teacher, in his teaching.
ROM|12|8||And there is that of a consoler, in his consoling: And that of a giver, with simplicity: And that of a presider, with dexterity: And of a sympathizer, with cheerfulness.
ROM|12|9||Let not your love be guileful: but be haters of evil things, and adherers to good things.
ROM|12|10||Be affectionate to your brethren: and love one another. Be foremost in honoring one another.
ROM|12|11||Be active; and not slothful. Be fervent in spirit. Be laborers for our Lord.
ROM|12|12||Be joyful in your hope. Be patient under your afflictions. Be persevering in prayer.
ROM|12|13||Be communicators to the wants of the saints. Be kind to strangers.
ROM|12|14||Bless your persecutors: bless, and curse not.
ROM|12|15||Rejoice with them who rejoice: and weep with them who weep.
ROM|12|16||What estimation ye make of yourselves, [make] also of your brethren. And indulge not high thoughts; but unite yourselves with the lowly minded. And be not wise in your own estimation.
ROM|12|17||And repay to no man evil for evil: but let it be your study to do good before all men.
ROM|12|18||And if possible, so far as it dependeth on you, live in peace with every man.
ROM|12|19||And be ye not avengers of yourselves, my beloved: but give place to wrath. For it is written: If thou dost not execute judgment for thyself, I will execute judgment for thee, saith God.
ROM|12|20||And if thy adversary be hungry, feed him: and if he be thirsty, give him drink. For if thou doest these things to him, thou wilt heap coals of fire on his head.
ROM|12|21||Be ye not overcome by evil; but overcome evil with good.
ROM|13|1||Let every soul be subject to the authorities of magistracy. For there is no authority which is not from God: and the authorities which exist, are established by God.
ROM|13|2||He therefore who opposeth the authority, opposeth the establishment of God; and they who oppose them, shall receive judgment.
ROM|13|3||For judges are not a terror to good deeds, but to evil deeds. Wouldst thou then not be afraid of the authority? Do good, and thou shalt have praise from it.
