ROM|14|6||He that esteemeth a day, esteemeth [it] for his Lord: and he that esteemeth not a day, for his Lord, he doth not esteem [it.] And he that eateth, eateth to his Lord, and giveth thanks to God: and he that eateth not, to his Lord he eateth not, and giveth thanks to God.
ROM|14|7||For there is not one of us, who liveth for himself: and there is not one, who dieth for himself.
ROM|14|8||Because, if we live, to our Lord it is we live; or if we die, to our Lord it is we die. Whether we live, therefore, or whether we die, we are our Lord's.
ROM|14|9||Moreover, for this cause Messiah died, and revived, and arose; that he might be Lord of the dead and of the living.
ROM|14|10||But thou, why dost thou judge thy brother? or, why dost thou despise thy brother? For we must all stand before the judgment seat of Messiah,
ROM|14|11||as it is written: As I live, saith the Lord, to me every knee shall bow; and to me every tongue shall give praise.
ROM|14|12||So then, every one of us must give account of himself to God.
ROM|14|13||Henceforth, judge ye not one another; but rather, judge ye this, that thou erect not a stumbling-block for thy brother.
ROM|14|14||I know indeed, and am persuaded by the Lord Jesus, that there is nothing which is unclean in itself; but to him who thinketh any thing to be unclean, to him only it is defiled.
ROM|14|15||But if thou grievest thy brother, because of food, thou walkest not in love. On account of food, destroy not him for whom Messiah died.
ROM|14|16||And let not our good thing be matter of reproach.
ROM|14|17||For the kingdom of God, is not food and drink; but is righteousness, and peace, and joy in the Holy Spirit.
ROM|14|18||For he who is in these things a servant of Messiah, is pleasing to God, and approved before men.
ROM|14|19||Now let us strive after peace, and after the edification of one another.
ROM|14|20||And let us not, on account of food, destroy the work of God. For every thing is, [indeed,] pure; yet it is evil, to the man who eateth with stumbling.
ROM|14|21||It is proper, that we neither eat flesh, nor drink wine, nor [do] any thing, whereby our brother is stumbled.
ROM|14|22||Thou art one in whom there is faith; keep it to thyself, before God. Blessed is he, who doth not condemn himself, in that thing which he alloweth.
ROM|14|23||For he who eateth and doubteth, is condemned; because [he eateth] not in faith. For every thing which is not of faith, is sin.
ROM|15|1||We then who are strong, ought to bear the infirmity of the weak, and not to please ourselves.
ROM|15|2||But each of us should please his neighbor, in good things, as conducive to edification.
ROM|15|3||Because Messiah also did not please himself; but, as it is written: The reviling of thy revilers fell upon me.
ROM|15|4||For every thing written of old, was written for our instruction; that we, by patience and by the consolation of the scriptures, might possess hope.
ROM|15|5||And may the God of patience and of consolation, grant to you, to think in harmony one with another, in Jesus Messiah;
ROM|15|6||so that with one mind and one mouth, ye may glorify God, the Father of our Lord Jesus Messiah.
ROM|15|7||Wherefore, receive ye and bear up one another, as also Messiah received you, to the glory of God.
ROM|15|8||Now I say, that Jesus Messiah ministered to the circumcision, in behalf of the truth of God, in order to confirm the promise [made] to the fathers;
ROM|15|9||and that the Gentiles might glorify God for his mercies upon them, as it is written: I will confess to thee among the Gentiles, and to thy name will I sing psalms.
ROM|15|10||And again he said: Rejoice, ye Gentiles, with his people.
ROM|15|11||And again he said: Praise the Lord, all ye Gentiles; [and] laud him, all ye nations.
ROM|15|12||And again Isaiah said: There will be a root of Jesse; and he that shall arise, will be a prince for the Gentiles; and in him will the Gentiles hope.
ROM|15|13||Now may the God of hope fill you with all joy and peace, by faith; that ye may abound in his hope, by the power of the Holy Spirit.
ROM|15|14||Now I am persuaded, my Brethren, even I, concerning you; that ye too are full of goodness, and are replenished with all knowledge, and are able also to instruct others.
ROM|15|15||Yet I have written rather boldly to you, my Brethren, that I might put you in remembrance; because of the grace which is given to me by God,
ROM|15|16||that I should be a minister of Jesus Messiah among the Gentiles, and should subserve the gospel of God, that the oblation of the Gentiles might be acceptable, and be sanctified by the Holy Spirit.
ROM|15|17||I have therefore a glorying in Jesus Messiah, before God.
ROM|15|18||Yet I presume not to speak of any thing [done] for the obedience of the Gentiles, which Messiah hath not wrought by me, in word and in deeds,
ROM|15|19||by the power of signs and wonders, and by the power of the Holy Spirit; so that from Jerusalem I have made a circuit quite to Illyricum, and have fulfilled the announcement of the Messiah;
ROM|15|20||while I was careful not to preach where the name of Messiah had been invoked, lest I should build upon another man's foundation;
ROM|15|21||but, it is written: They, to whom mention of him had not been made, will see him; and they, who had not heard, will be obedient.
ROM|15|22||And on this account, I have been many times prevented from coming to you.
ROM|15|23||But now, since I have no place in these regions, and as I have been desirous for many years past to come to you,
ROM|15|24||when I go to Spain, I hope to come and see you; and that ye will accompany me thither, when I shall have been satisfied, in some measure, with visiting you.
ROM|15|25||But I am now going to Jerusalem, to minister to the saints.
ROM|15|26||For they of Macedonia and Achaia, have been willing to make up a contribution for the needy saints who are at Jerusalem.
ROM|15|27||They were willing, because they were also debtors to them: for if the Gentiles have been participators with them in the Spirit, they are debtors to serve them also in things of the flesh.
ROM|15|28||When therefore, I shall have accomplished this, and shall have sealed to them this fruit, I will pass by you into Spain.
ROM|15|29||And I know that when I come to you, I shall come in the fullness of the blessing of the gospel of Messiah.
ROM|15|30||And I beseech you, my Brethren, by our Lord Jesus Messiah, and by the love of the Spirit, that ye labor with me in prayer to God for me;
ROM|15|31||that I may be delivered from them in Judaea, who believe not and that the ministration, which I carry to the saints in Jerusalem, may be well received;
ROM|15|32||and that, by the good pleasure of God, I may come to you with joy, and may take comfort with you.
ROM|15|33||And may the God of peace be with you all: Amen.
ROM|16|1||And I commend to you Phebe, our sister, who is a servant of the church in Cenchrea:
ROM|16|2||that ye may receive her in our Lord, as is just for saints; and that ye may assist her, in whatever thing she may ask of you: for she also hath been assistant to many, and to me also.
ROM|16|3||Salute ye Priscilla and Aquila, my fellow-laborers in Jesus Messiah;
ROM|16|4||who, for my life, surrendered their own necks; and to whom, not only I am grateful, but also all the churches of the Gentiles.
ROM|16|5||And give a salutation to the church which is in their house. Salute my beloved Epenetus, who was the first-fruits of Achaia in Messiah.
ROM|16|6||Salute Mary, who hath toiled much with you.
ROM|16|7||Salute Andronicus and Junia, my relatives, who were in captivity with me, and are of note among the legates, and were in Messiah before me.
ROM|16|8||Salute Amplias, my beloved in our Lord.
ROM|16|9||Salute Urbanus, a laborer with us in Messiah; and my beloved Stachys.
ROM|16|10||Salute Apelles, chosen in our Lord. Salute the members of the house of Aristobulus.
ROM|16|11||Salute Herodion, my kinsman. Salute the members of the house of Narcissus, who are in our Lord.
ROM|16|12||Salute Tryphena and Tryphosa, who toil in our Lord. Salute my beloved Persis, who toiled much in our Lord.
ROM|16|13||Salute Rufus, chosen in our Lord; and his and my mother.
ROM|16|14||Salute Asyncritus, and Phlegon, and Hermas, and Patrobas, and Hermes, and the brethren who are with them.
ROM|16|15||Salute Philologus and Julia, Nereus and his sister, and Olympas, and all the saints who are with them.
ROM|16|16||Salute one another, with a holy kiss. All the churches of Messiah salute you.
ROM|16|17||And I beseech you, my Brethren, that ye beware of them who cause divisions and stumblings [among you], aside from the doctrine which ye have learned: and that ye stand aloof from them.
ROM|16|18||For they who are such, do not serve our Lord Jesus Messiah, but their own belly: and by bland speeches and good wishes, they beguile the hearts of the simple.
ROM|16|19||But your obedience is known to every one. I therefore rejoice in you: and I would have you be wise in what is good, and blameless in what is evil.
ROM|16|20||And the God of peace will soon crush Satan under your feet. The grace of our Lord Jesus Messiah, be with you.
ROM|16|21||Timothy, my fellow-laborer, and Lucius, and Jason, and Sosipater, my kinsmen, salute you.
ROM|16|22||I Tertius, who have written this epistle, salute you in the Lord.
ROM|16|23||Gaius, hospitable to me and to all the church, saluteth you. Erastus, the steward of the city, and Quartus a brother, salute you.
ROM|16|24||Now unto God, who is able to establish you, (according to my gospel, which is proclaimed concerning Jesus Messiah; and according to the revelation of the mystery, which was hidden from the times that are past,
ROM|16|25||but is at this time revealed, by means of the scriptures of the prophets; and by the command of the eternal God, is made known to all the Gentiles, for the obedience of faith;)
ROM|16|26||[to him] who only is wise, be glory, through Jesus Messiah, for ever and ever: Amen.
ROM|16|27||The grace of our Lord Jesus Messiah, be with you all: Amen.
1CO|1|1||Paul, called and sent by Jesus Messiah in the good pleasure of God; and Sosthenes, a brother;
1CO|1|2||to the church of God which is at Corinth, to the [people] called and sanctified, who are sanctified in Jesus Messiah; and to all them, in every place, who invoke the name of our Lord Jesus Messiah, their and our [Lord]:
1CO|1|3||Grace [be] with you, and peace; from God our Father, and from our Lord Jesus Messiah.
1CO|1|4||I thank my God at all times on your behalf, for the grace of God which is given to you in Jesus Messiah;
1CO|1|5||that in every thing ye are enriched by him, in all discourse, and in all knowledge;
1CO|1|6||even as the testimony of Messiah was confirmed among you:
1CO|1|7||so that ye are not inferior in any one of his gifts; but are waiting for the manifestation of our Lord Jesus Messiah:
1CO|1|8||who will confirm you unto the end, so that ye may be blameless in the day of our Lord Jesus Messiah.
1CO|1|9||God is faithful; by whom ye have been called into the fellowship of his Son, Jesus Messiah, our Lord.
1CO|1|10||And I beseech you, my Brethren, by the name of our Lord Jesus Messiah, that to you all there may be one language; and that there may be no divisions among you: but that ye may become perfectly of one mind, and of one way of thinking.
1CO|1|11||For concerning you, my Brethren, it hath been reported to me by the house of Chloe, that there are contentions among you.
1CO|1|12||And this I state: That one of you saith, I am of Paul; and another saith, I am of Apollos; and another saith, I am of Cephas; and another saith, I am of Messiah.
1CO|1|13||Now was Messiah divided? Or was Paul crucified for you? Or were ye baptized in the name of Paul?
1CO|1|14||I thank my God that I baptized none of you, except Crispus and Gaius;
1CO|1|15||lest any one should say, that I baptized in my own name.
1CO|1|16||I moreover baptized the household of Stephanas: but further, I know not that I baptized any other.
1CO|1|17||For Messiah did not send me to baptize, but to preach; not with wisdom of words, lest the cross of Messiah should be inefficient.
1CO|1|18||For a discourse concerning the cross is, to them who perish, foolishness; but to us who live, it is the energy of God.
1CO|1|19||For it is written: I will destroy the wisdom of the wise; and I will dissipate the intelligence of the sagacious.
1CO|1|20||Where is the wise? Or where is the scribe? Or where is the disputant of this world? Lo, hath not God showed, that the wisdom of this world is folly?
1CO|1|21||For in the wisdom of God, because the world by wisdom knew not God, it pleased God, by the foolishness of preaching, to quicken them who believe.
1CO|1|22||Because the Jews ask for signs, and the Gentiles demand wisdom.
1CO|1|23||But we preach Messiah as crucified; [which is] a stumbling-block to the Jews, and foolishness to the Gentiles;
1CO|1|24||but to them who are called, both Jews and Gentiles, Messiah is the energy of God, and the wisdom of God.
1CO|1|25||Because the foolishness of God, is wiser than men; and the feebleness of God, is stronger than men.
1CO|1|26||For look also at your calling, my Brethren; that not many among you are wise, according to the flesh; and not many among you are mighty, and not many among you are of high birth.
1CO|1|27||But God hath chosen the foolish ones of the world, to shame the wise; and he hath chosen the feeble ones of the world, to shame the mighty;
1CO|1|28||and he hath chosen those of humble birth in the world, and the despised, and them who are nothing, to bring to naught them who are something:
1CO|1|29||so that no flesh might glory before him.
1CO|1|30||And ye, moreover, are of him in Jesus Messiah; who hath become to us wisdom from God, and righteousness and sanctification, and redemption:
1CO|1|31||according to that which is written: He that glorieth, let him glory in the Lord.
1CO|2|1||And I, my Brethren, when I came to you, did not preach to you the mystery of God in magnificent speech, nor in wisdom.
1CO|2|2||And I did not govern myself among you, as if I knew any thing, except only Jesus Messiah; and him also as crucified.
1CO|2|3||And in much fear and much trembling, was I with you.
1CO|2|4||And my speech and my preaching were not with the persuasiveness of the discourses of wisdom; but with the demonstration of the Spirit, and with power:
1CO|2|5||that your faith might not arise from the wisdom of men, but from the power of God.
1CO|2|6||Yet we do speak wisdom, among the perfect; the wisdom not of this world, nor of the potentates of this world, who will come to naught.
1CO|2|7||But we speak the wisdom of God, in a mystery; the wisdom which was hidden, and which God predetermined before the world was, for our glory:
1CO|2|8||which no one of the potentates of this world knew; for had they known it, they would not have crucified the Lord of glory.
1CO|2|9||But, as it is written: The eye hath not seen, nor hath the ear heard, nor hath it entered into the heart of man, that which God hath prepared for those who love him.
1CO|2|10||But God hath revealed it to us, by his Spirit; for the Spirit exploreth all things, even the profound things of God.
1CO|2|11||For what man is there, who knoweth that which is in a man, except it be the spirit of the man, which is in him? So also, that which is in God, no one knoweth, except the Spirit of God.
1CO|2|12||Now we have received, not the spirit of the world, but the Spirit which is from God; that we might know the free gifts, which are given to us by God.
1CO|2|13||Which things we also speak; not in the teaching of the words of man's wisdom, but in the teaching of the spirit; and we compare spirituals with spirituals.
1CO|2|14||For a man in his natural self, receiveth not spirituals; for they are foolishness to him. Neither can he know them; for they are discerned by the Spirit.
1CO|2|15||But he that is spiritual, judgeth of all things: and he is judged of by no one.
1CO|2|16||For who hath known the mind of the Lord, that he should instruct him? But we have the mind of Messiah.
1CO|3|1||And I, my Brethren, could not talk with you, as with spiritual [persons], but as with the carnal, as with babes in Messiah.
1CO|3|2||I gave you milk, and did not give you solid food: for ye were not then able to receive it; and even now, ye are not able.
1CO|3|3||For ye are still in the flesh. For, as there are among you envying, and contention, and parties, are ye not carnal, and walking in the flesh?
1CO|3|4||For, while one of you saith, I am of Paul; and another saith, I am of Apollos; are ye not carnal?
1CO|3|5||For, who is Paul, or who is Apollos, but the ministers by whom ye believed, each one as the Lord gave to him?
1CO|3|6||I planted, and Apollos watered; but God produced the growth.
1CO|3|7||Not therefore he that planted, is to be accounted of, nor he that watered, but God who produced the growth.
1CO|3|8||And he that planted, and he that watered are on a par; each receiveth his reward, according to his labor.
1CO|3|9||For we labor with God: and ye are God's husbandry, and God's edifice.
1CO|3|10||According to the grace of God which was given me, I laid the foundation like a wise architect; and another buildeth on it. But let each one see, how he buildeth on it.
1CO|3|11||For any other foundation can no man lay, different from that which is laid, which is Jesus Messiah.
1CO|3|12||And if any one buildeth on this foundation, either gold, or silver, or precious stones, or wood, or hay, or stubble;
1CO|3|13||the work of each will be exposed to view; for the day will expose it; because it is to be tested by fire; and the fire will disclose the work of each, of what sort it is.
1CO|3|14||And that builder whose work shall endure, will receive his reward.
1CO|3|15||And he, whose work shall burn up, will suffer loss; yet himself will escape; but it will be, as from the fire.
1CO|3|16||Know ye not, that ye are the temple of God? and that the Spirit of God dwelleth in you?
1CO|3|17||Whoever shall mar the temple of God, God will mar him: for the temple of God is holy, which [temple] ye are.
1CO|3|18||Let no one deceive himself. Whoever among you thinketh that he is wise in this world, let him become a fool, that he may be wise.
1CO|3|19||For the wisdom of this world is fatuity with God: for it is written, He catcheth the wise in their own craftiness.
1CO|3|20||And again: The Lord knoweth the devices of the wise, that they are vain.
1CO|3|21||Wherefore, let no one glory in men: for all things are yours;
1CO|3|22||whether Paul, or Apollos, or Cephas, or the world, or life, or death, or things present, or things to come; all things are yours:
1CO|3|23||and ye are Messiah's, and Messiah is God's.
1CO|4|1||Let us be so accounted of by you, as the servants of Messiah, and the stewards of the mysteries of God.
1CO|4|2||Now it is required of stewards, that each be found faithful.
1CO|4|3||But to me, it is a light matter to be judged of by you, or by any man whatever; nay, I am no judge of myself.
1CO|4|4||(For I am not conscious in myself of any thing [flagrant]; yet I am not by this justified; for the Lord is my judge.)
1CO|4|5||Therefore pronounce not judgments before the time, [or] until the Lord come, who will pour light upon the hidden things of darkness, and will make manifest the thoughts of [men's] hearts: and then will each one have [due] praise from God.
1CO|4|6||These things, my Brethren, I have stated concerning the person of myself and of Apollos, for your sakes; that, in us, ye might learn not to think [of men], above what is written; and that no one might exalt himself in comparison with his fellow, on account of any person.
1CO|4|7||For who exploreth thee? Or what hast thou, which thou didst not receive? And if thou receivedst it, why gloriest thou, as if thou didst not receive it?
1CO|4|8||Now ye are yourselves full, and enriched; and, without us, are on thrones! And I wish ye were enthroned; that we also might reign with you.
1CO|4|9||But I suppose, that God hath placed us legates the last, as for death; since we have become a spectacle to the world, to angels and to men.
1CO|4|10||We are fools, on account of Messiah; but ye are wise in Messiah! We are feeble; but ye are strong! Ye are lauded, we are contemned.
1CO|4|11||Unto this hour, we hunger, and thirst, and are naked, and are buffeted, and have no permanent home:
1CO|4|12||and we toil, working with our own hands: they defame us, and we bless: they persecute us, and we endure it:
1CO|4|13||they revile us, and we entreat them: we are as the filth of the world, and the expiation for all men, up to this time.
1CO|4|14||I write these things, not to shame you; but I instruct you, as dear children.
1CO|4|15||For though ye have a myriad of teachers in Messiah, yet not many fathers; for in Jesus Messiah, I have begotten you by preaching.
1CO|4|16||I beseech you, therefore, that ye be like me.
1CO|4|17||For this cause have I sent to you Timothy, who is my beloved son, and faithful in the Lord, that he might bring to your recollection my ways in Messiah, agreeably to what I teach in all the churches.
1CO|4|18||Now some of you are inflated, as though I would not [dare] come to you.
1CO|4|19||But I will come to you speedily, if God be willing: and I will know, not the speech of them who exalt themselves, but their power:
1CO|4|20||for the kingdom of God is not in word, but in power.
1CO|4|21||What will ye? Shall I come to you with the rod, or with love and a gentle spirit?
1CO|5|1||In short, it is reported, there is whoredom among you; and such whoredom as is not even named among the heathen, that a son should even take the wife of his father.
1CO|5|2||And ye are inflated, and have not rather sitten down in grief, that he who hath done this deed might be separated from you.
1CO|5|3||And I, while distant from you in body but present with you in spirit, have already, as if present, judged him who perpetrateth this deed;
1CO|5|4||that ye all assemble together, in the name of our Lord Jesus Messiah, and I with you in spirit, together with the energy of our Lord Jesus Messiah;
1CO|5|5||and that ye deliver him over to Satan, for the destruction of the flesh, that in spirit he may have life, in the day of our Lord Jesus Messiah.
1CO|5|6||Your glorying is not praiseworthy. Know ye not, that a little leaven leaveneth the whole mass?
1CO|5|7||Purge out from you the old leaven, that ye may be a new mass, as ye are unleavened. For our passover is the Messiah, who was slain for us.
1CO|5|8||Therefore let us celebrate the festival, not with the old leaven, nor with the leaven of wickedness and bitterness, but with the leaven of purity and sanctity.
1CO|5|9||I wrote to you by letter, not to commingle with whoremongers.
1CO|5|10||But I say not, with the whoremongers who are in the world, nor [speak I] of the avaricious, or of the rapacious, or of the idol-worshippers, otherwise ye would be obliged to go out of the world.
1CO|5|11||But this is what I wrote to you, that ye commingle not, if any one is called a brother, and is a whoremonger, or avaricious, or an idol-worshipper, or a railer, or a drunkard, or rapacious, with him who is such, not even to eat bread.
1CO|5|12||For what business have I to judge them who are without? But those within the body, judge ye,
1CO|5|13||and those without, God judgeth; and remove ye the wickedness from among you.
1CO|6|1||Dare any of you, when he hath a controversy with his brother, litigate before the iniquitous, and not before the sanctified?
1CO|6|2||Or know ye not, that the sanctified will judge the world? And if the world will be judged by you, are ye unfit to decide trivial causes?
1CO|6|3||Know ye not, that we shall judge angels? How much more things that are of the world?
1CO|6|4||But if ye have a controversy about a worldly matter, seat ye on the bench for you those who are contemned in the church!
1CO|6|5||For shame to you I say [it]. So, there is not even one wise man among you, who is competent to do equity between a brother and his brother:
1CO|6|6||but a brother litigateth with his brother, and also before them that believe not!
1CO|6|7||Now therefore ye condemn yourselves, in that ye have litigation one with another. For why do ye not rather suffer wrong? why not rather be defrauded?
1CO|6|8||But ye yourselves commit wrong, and ye defraud even your brethren.
1CO|6|9||Or do ye not know, that the unrighteous will not inherit the kingdom of God? Do not mistake; neither whoremongers, nor idol-worshippers, nor adulterers, nor debauchers, nor liers with males,
1CO|6|10||nor the avaricious, nor thieves, nor drunkards, nor railers, nor extortioners, will inherit the kingdom of God.
1CO|6|11||And these things have been in some of you: but ye are washed, and are sanctified, and made righteous, in the name of our Lord Jesus the Messiah, and by the Spirit of our God.
1CO|6|12||Every thing is in my power: but every thing is not profitable to me. Every thing is in my power; but none [of them] shall have dominion over me.
1CO|6|13||Food is for the belly; and the belly is for food; but God will bring them both to naught. But the body is not for whoredom, but for our Lord; and our Lord for the body.
1CO|6|14||And God hath raised up our Lord; and he will raise us up, by his power.
1CO|6|15||Know ye not, that your bodies are the members of the Messiah? Shall one take a member of the Messiah, and make it the member of a harlot? Far be it.
1CO|6|16||Or know ye not, that whoever joineth himself to a harlot, is one body [with her]? For it is said, They twain shall be one body.
1CO|6|17||But he that joineth himself to our Lord, is with him one spirit.
1CO|6|18||Flee whoredom. For every [other] sin which a man committeth, is external to his body; but he that committeth whoredom, sinneth against his own body.
1CO|6|19||Or know ye not, that your body is the temple of the Holy Spirit who abideth in you, whom ye have received from God? And ye are not your own.
1CO|6|20||For ye are bought with a price. Therefore, glorify ye God, with your body, and with your spirit, which are God's.
1CO|7|1||And concerning the things of which ye wrote to me, it is praiseworthy for a man not to approach a woman.
1CO|7|2||But, on account of whoredom, let each have his own wife and let a woman have her own husband.
1CO|7|3||And let the man render to his wife the kindness which is due; and so also the woman to her husband.
1CO|7|4||The woman is not the sovereign over her body, but her husband: so also the man is not the sovereign over his body, but the wife.
1CO|7|5||Therefore, deprive not one another, except when ye both consent, at the time ye devote yourselves to fasting and prayer; and return again to the same disposition, that Satan tempt you not because of the concupiscence of your body.
1CO|7|6||But this I say, as to weak persons, not of positive precept.
1CO|7|7||For I would that all men might be like me in purity. But every man is endowed with his gift of God; one thus, and another so.
1CO|7|8||And I say to them who have no wives, and to widows, that it is advantageous to them to remain as I am.
1CO|7|9||But if they cannot endure [it], let them marry: for it is more profitable to take a wife, than to burn with concupiscence.
1CO|7|10||And on them who have wives, I enjoin,not I, but my Lord,that the woman separate not from her husband.
1CO|7|11||And if she separate, let her remain without a husband, or be reconciled to her husband; and let not the man put away his wife.
1CO|7|12||And to the rest, say I, I, not my Lord,that if there be a brother, who hath a wife that believeth not, and she is disposed to dwell with him, let him not put her away.
1CO|7|13||And that woman, who hath a husband that believeth not, and he is disposed to dwell with her let her not forsake her husband.
1CO|7|14||For the husband who believeth not, is sanctified by the wife that believeth; and the wife who believeth not, is sanctified by the husband that believeth: otherwise their children would be impure; but now are they pure.
1CO|7|15||But if the unbeliever separateth, let him separate: A brother or sister is not in bondage in such cases: it is to peace, God hath called us.
1CO|7|16||For how knowest thou, O wife, whether thou wilt procure life to thy husband? Or, thou husband, knowest thou, whether thou wilt procure life to thy wife?
1CO|7|17||Every one, however, as the Lord hath distributed to him, and every one as God hath called him, so let him walk. And also thus I enjoin upon all the churches.
1CO|7|18||Is a circumcised person called, let him not revert to uncircumcision: and if one uncircumcised be called, let him not become circumcised.
1CO|7|19||For circumcision is nothing, neither is uncircumcision; but the keeping of God's commands.
1CO|7|20||Let every one continue in the vocation, in which he was called.
1CO|7|21||If thou wert called, being a servant; let it not trouble thee. But if thou canst be made free, choose it rather than to serve.
1CO|7|22||For he that is called by our Lord, being a servant, is God's freedman: likewise, he that is called, being a free man, is the Messiah's servant.
1CO|7|23||Ye are bought with a price; become not the servants of men.
1CO|7|24||Let every one, my Brethren, continue with God, in whatever [state] he was called.
1CO|7|25||And concerning virginity, I have no precept from God; but I give counsels as a man who hath obtained mercy from God to be a believer.
1CO|7|26||And I think this is suitable, on account of the necessity of the times; it is advantageous for a man to remain as he is.
1CO|7|27||Art thou bound to a wife? Seek not a release. Art thou free from a wife? Seek not a wife.
1CO|7|28||But if thou takest a wife, thou sinnest not. And if a maiden is given to a husband, she sinneth not. But they who are such, will have trouble in the body: but I am forbearing to you.
1CO|7|29||And this I say, my Brethren, that the time to come is short; so that they who have wives, should be as if they had none;
1CO|7|30||and they who weep, as if they wept not; and they who rejoice, as if they rejoiced not; and they who buy, as if they acquired not;
1CO|7|31||and those occupied with this world, not going beyond the just using: for the fashion of this world is passing away.
1CO|7|32||And therefore I wish you to be without solicitude. For he who hath not a wife, considereth the thing of his Lord, how he may please his Lord.
1CO|7|33||And he who hath a wife, is anxious about the world, how he may please his wife.
1CO|7|34||There is a difference also between a wife and a maiden. She who is without a husband, thinketh of things pertaining to her Lord, that she may be holy in her body and in her spirit. But she who hath a husband, thinketh of things pertaining to the world, how she may please her husband.
1CO|7|35||And this I say for your advantage; I am not laying a snare for you; but that ye may be faithful towards your Lord, in a suitable manner, while not minding worldly things.
1CO|7|36||But if any one thinketh that there is reproach, on account of his maiden [daughter], because she hath passed her time, and he hath not presented her to a husband, [and] it be fitting that he present her; let him do what he desireth, he sinneth not; let her be married.
1CO|7|37||But he who hath firmly determined in his own mind, and nothing compelleth him, and he can act his own pleasure, and he so judgeth in his heart, that he keep his maiden [daughter], he doeth commendably.
1CO|7|38||And therefore, he who presenteth his maiden [daughter], doeth commendably; and he who presenteth not his maiden [daughter], doeth very commendably.
1CO|7|39||A woman, while her husband liveth, is bound by the law; but if her husband sleepeth [in death], she is free to marry whom she pleaseth, [yet] only in the Lord.
1CO|7|40||But she is happier, in my opinion, if she remain so: and I think also, that I have the Spirit of God.
1CO|8|1||And concerning sacrifices to idols, we know, that in all of us there is knowledge; and knowledge inflateth, but love edifieth.
1CO|8|2||And if any one thinketh that he knoweth any thing he knoweth nothing yet, as he ought to know [it].
1CO|8|3||But if any one loveth God, that man is known of him.
1CO|8|4||As to the eating of the sacrifices of idols, therefore, we know that an idol is nothing in the world; and that there is no other God, but one.
1CO|8|5||For although there are what are called gods, whether in heaven, or on earth, (as there are gods many, and lords many,)
1CO|8|6||yet to us, on our part, there is one God, the Father, from whom are all things, and we in him; and one Lord, Jesus the Messiah, by whom are all things, and we also by him.
1CO|8|7||But there is not [this] knowledge in every man; for there are some, who, to the present time, in their conscience, eat [it] as an offering to idols; and because their conscience is weak, it is defiled.
1CO|8|8||But food doth not bring us near to God; for if we eat, we do not abound; and if we eat not, we are not in want.
1CO|8|9||See to it, however, lest this your authority become a stumbling-block to the weak.
1CO|8|10||For if one should see thee in whom there is knowledge, reclining in the temple of idols, will not his conscience, seeing he is a weak person, be encouraged to eat what is sacrificed?
1CO|8|11||And by thy knowledge, he who is feeble, and on account of whom the Messiah died, will perish.
1CO|8|12||And if ye thus sin against your brethren, and wound the consciences of the feeble, ye sin against the Messiah.
1CO|8|13||Wherefore, if food is a stumbling-block to my brother, I will for ever eat no flesh, lest I should be a stumbling-block to my brother.
1CO|9|1||Am I not a free man? Or, am I not a legate? Or, have I not seen Jesus Messiah our Lord? Or, have ye not been my work in my Lord?
1CO|9|2||And if I have not been a legate to others, yet I have been so to you; and ye are the seal of my legateship.
1CO|9|3||And [my] apology to my judgers, is this:
1CO|9|4||Have we not authority, to eat and to drink?
1CO|9|5||Or have we not authority to carry about with us a sister as a wife; just as the other legates, and the brothers of our Lord, and as Cephas?
1CO|9|6||Or I only, and Barnabas, have we no right to forbear labor?
1CO|9|7||Who, that serveth in war, [doth so] at his own expense? Or who, that planteth a vineyard, eateth not of its fruits? Or who, that tendeth sheep, eateth not of the milk of his flocks?
1CO|9|8||Is it as a man, I say these things? Behold, the law also saith them.
1CO|9|9||For it is written in the law of Moses, Thou shalt not muzzle the ox that thresheth. Hath God regard for oxen?
1CO|9|10||But manifest it is, for whose sake he said it. And indeed, for our sakes it was written: because the plougher ought to plough in hope, and the thresher in hope of fruit.
1CO|9|11||If we have sowed among you the things of the Spirit, is it a great matter, if we reap from you the things of the body?
1CO|9|12||And if others have this prerogative over you, doth it not belong still more to us? Yet we have not used this prerogative; but we have endured every thing, that we might in nothing impede the announcement of the Messiah.
1CO|9|13||Know ye not, that they who serve in a temple, are fed from the temple? And they who serve at the altar, participate with the altar?
1CO|9|14||Thus also hath our Lord commanded, that they who proclaim his gospel, should live by his gospel.
1CO|9|15||But I have used none of these things: and I write not, that it may be so done to me; for it would be better for me to actually die, than that any one should make void my glorying.
1CO|9|16||For while I preach, I have no [ground of] glorying; because necessity is laid upon me, and woe to me, if I preach not.
1CO|9|17||For if I do this voluntarily, there is a reward for me: but if involuntarily, a stewardship is intrusted to me.
1CO|9|18||What then is my reward? [It is,] that when I preach, I make the announcement of the Messiah without cost, and use not the prerogative given me in the gospel.
1CO|9|19||Being free from them all, I have made myself servant to every man; that I might gain many:
1CO|9|20||and with the Jews, I was as a Jew, that I might gain the Jews; and with those under the law, I was as under the law, that I might gain them who are under the law;
1CO|9|21||and to those who have not the law, I was as without the law, (although I am not without law to God, but under the law of the Messiah,) that I might gain them that are without the law.
1CO|9|22||I was with the weak, as weak, that I might gain the weak: I was all things to all men, that I might vivify every one.
1CO|9|23||And this I do, that I may participate in the announcement.
1CO|9|24||Know ye not that they who run in the stadium, run all of them; yet it is one who gaineth the victory. Run ye, so as to attain.
1CO|9|25||For every one who engageth in the contest, restraineth his desires in every thing. And they run, to obtain a crown that perisheth; but we, one that perisheth not.
1CO|9|26||I therefore so run, not as for something unknown; and I so struggle, not as struggling against air;
1CO|9|27||but I subdue my body, and reduce it to servitude; lest, when I have preached to others, I myself should be a reprobate.
1CO|10|1||And, my Brethren, I would have you know, that our fathers were all of them under the cloud, and they all passed through the sea;
1CO|10|2||and they were all baptized by Moses, in the cloud and in the sea;
1CO|10|3||and they all ate the same spiritual food;
1CO|10|4||and they all drank the same spiritual drink; for they drank from the spiritual rock that attended them, and that rock was the Messiah.
1CO|10|5||But with a multitude of them, God was not pleased; for they fell in the wilderness.
1CO|10|6||Now these things were an example for us, that we should not hanker after evil things as they hankered.
1CO|10|7||Neither should we serve idols, as some of them served; as it is written, The people sat down to eat and to drink, and rose up to sport.
1CO|10|8||Neither let us commit whoredom, as some of them committed; and there fell in one day twenty and three thousand.
1CO|10|9||Neither let us tempt the Messiah, as some of them tempted; and serpents destroyed them.
1CO|10|10||Neither murmur ye, as some of them murmured; and they perished by the destroyer.
1CO|10|11||All these things which befell them, were for an example to us; and they are written for our instruction, on whom the end of the world hath come.
1CO|10|12||Wherefore, let him who thinketh he standeth, beware lest he fall.
1CO|10|13||No trial cometh on you, but what pertaineth to men: and God is faithful, who will not permit you to be tried beyond your ability, but will make an issue to your trial, that ye may be able to sustain it.
1CO|10|14||Wherefore, my Beloved, flee from idolatry.
1CO|10|15||I speak as to the wise; judge ye what I say.
1CO|10|16||The cup of thanksgiving which we bless, is it not the communion of the blood of the Messiah? And the bread which we break, is it not the communion of the body of the Messiah?
1CO|10|17||As therefore that bread is one, so we are all one body; for we all take to ourselves from that one bread.
1CO|10|18||Behold the Israel who are in the flesh; are not they who eat the victims, participators of the altar?
1CO|10|19||What then do I say? That an idol is any thing? Or, that an idol's sacrifice is any thing? No.
1CO|10|20||But that what the Gentiles sacrifice, they sacrifice to demons, and not to God. And I would not, that ye should be associates of demons.
1CO|10|21||Ye cannot drink the cup of our Lord, and the cup of demons; and ye cannot be partakers at the table of our Lord, and at the table of demons.
1CO|10|22||Or, would we sedulously provoke our Lord's jealousy? Are we stronger than he?
1CO|10|23||Every thing is in my power; but every thing is not profitable. Every thing is in my power; but every thing doth not edify.
1CO|10|24||Let no one seek his own things, but also the things of his fellow-man.
1CO|10|25||Whatever is sold in the flesh-market, eat ye, without an inquiry on account of conscience:
1CO|10|26||for the earth is the Lord's, in its fullness.
1CO|10|27||And if one of the Gentiles invite you, and ye are disposed to go, eat ye whatever is set before you, without an inquiry on account of conscience.
1CO|10|28||But if any one shall say to you, This pertaineth to a sacrifice; eat not, for the sake of him who told you, and for conscience's sake.
1CO|10|29||The conscience I speak of, is not your own, but his who told you. But why is my liberty judged of, by the conscience of others?
1CO|10|30||If I by grace partake, why am I reproached for that, for which I give thanks?
1CO|10|31||If therefore ye eat, or if ye drink, or if ye do any thing, do all things for the glory of God.
1CO|10|32||Be ye without offence to the Jews, and to the Gentiles, and to the church of God:
1CO|10|33||even as I also, in every thing, please every man; and do not seek what is profitable to me, but what is profitable to many; that they may live.
1CO|11|1||Be ye imitators of me, as I am of the Messiah.
1CO|11|2||Moreover I commend you, my Brethren, that in all things ye are mindful of me, and that ye hold fast the precepts as I delivered them to you.
1CO|11|3||And I would have you know, that the head of every man is the Messiah, and the head of the woman is the man, and the head of the Messiah is God.
1CO|11|4||Every man, who prayeth or prophesieth with his head covered, dishonoreth his head.
1CO|11|5||And every woman, who prayeth or prophesieth with her head uncovered, dishonoreth her head; for she is on a level with her whose head is shaven.
1CO|11|6||For if a woman be not covered, let her also be shorn; but if it be shameful for a woman to be shorn or shaven, let her be covered.
1CO|11|7||The man, indeed, ought not to cover his head, because he is the likeness and glory of God: but the woman is the glory of the man.
1CO|11|8||For the man was not from the woman, but the woman from the man.
1CO|11|9||Neither was the man created for the woman's sake, but the woman for the man's sake.
1CO|11|10||For this cause ought the woman to have on her head [the mark of] authority, because of the angels.
1CO|11|11||Nevertheless, the man is not without the woman, nor the woman without the man, in our Lord.
1CO|11|12||For as the woman [was] from the man, so the man is by the woman; and every thing is from God.
1CO|11|13||Judge for yourselves, among yourselves; is it becoming, that a woman pray to God with her head uncovered?
1CO|11|14||Doth not nature teach you, that in a man, if his hair groweth long, it is a reproach to him?
1CO|11|15||But for a woman, if her hair is abundant, it is a glory to her; for her hair is given to her for a covering.
1CO|11|16||But if any one is contentious about these things, we on our part have no such custom, nor hath the church of God.
1CO|11|17||This which I now enjoin, is not as praising you; for ye have not made progress, but have deteriorated.
1CO|11|18||Because, first; when ye assemble in the church, there are, I hear, divisions among you; and I partly believe it.
1CO|11|19||For there are to be contentions among you, that the approved among you may be known.
1CO|11|20||When therefore ye come together, ye eat and drink, not as is becoming on the day of our Lord.
1CO|11|21||But, one and another proceedeth to eat his own supper; and one is hungry, and another is drunken.
1CO|11|22||What! have ye no houses in which ye can eat and drink? Or, despise ye the church of God, and shame them who have nothing? What shall I say to you? Shall I praise you? In this I praise you not.
1CO|11|23||For I have received from our Lord, that which I imparted to you; that our Lord Jesus, on the night he was betrayed, took bread,
1CO|11|24||and blessed, and brake [it], and said: "Take, eat; this is my body, which is broken for your sakes: thus do ye, in remembrance of me."
1CO|11|25||So, after they had supped, he gave also the cup, and said: "This cup is the new testament in my blood: thus do ye, as often as ye drink [it], in remembrance of me."
1CO|11|26||For as often as ye eat this bread, and drink this cup, ye commemorate the death of our Lord, until his advent.
1CO|11|27||He therefore, who eateth of the bread of the Lord, and drinketh of his cup, and is not worthy of it, is guilty of the blood of the Lord, and of his body.
1CO|11|28||For this reason, a man should examine himself, and then eat of this bread, and drink of this cup:
1CO|11|29||for, whoever eateth and drinketh of it, while he is unworthy, eateth and drinketh condemnation on himself, by not discerning the body of the Lord.
1CO|11|30||For this cause, many among you are diseased and sickly, and many sleep.
1CO|11|31||For if we would judge ourselves, we should not be judged.
1CO|11|32||But when we are judged by our Lord, we are really chastised, that we may not be condemned with the world.
1CO|11|33||Wherefore, my Brethren, when ye assemble to eat, wait ye one for another.
1CO|11|34||And let him who is hungry, eat at home; that ye may assemble, not for condemnation. And as to other things, I will give you directions when I come.
1CO|12|1||And concerning spirituals, my brethren, I would have you know,
1CO|12|2||that ye have been pagans; and have been, without distinction, led away after idols, in which there is no speech.
1CO|12|3||I therefore inform you, that there is no man, that speaketh by the Spirit of God, who saith that Jesus is accursed: neither can a man say that Jesus is the Lord, except by the Holy Spirit.
1CO|12|4||Now there are diversities of gifts; but the Spirit is one.
1CO|12|5||And there are diversities of ministrations; but the Lord is one.
1CO|12|6||And there are diversities of energies; but God, who worketh all in all men, is one.
1CO|12|7||And to each man, there is given a manifestation of the Spirit, that it may aid him.
1CO|12|8||To one, by the Spirit, there is given a word of wisdom; and to another, by the same Spirit, there is given a word of knowledge:
1CO|12|9||to another, by the same Spirit, faith: to another, by the same Spirit, gifts of healing:
1CO|12|10||and to another, miracles: and to another, prophecy: and to another, the discerning of spirits: and to another, [divers] kinds of tongues: and to another, the interpretation of tongues.
1CO|12|11||But all these, worketh that one Spirit; and he distributeth to every one as he pleaseth.
1CO|12|12||For as the body is one, and in it are many members; and all those members of the body, though many, are one body; so also is the Messiah.
1CO|12|13||For all of us, likewise, by one Spirit, have been baptized into one body, whether Jews or Gentiles, whether slaves or free; and all of us have drinked in one Spirit.
1CO|12|14||For a body also, is not one member, but many.
1CO|12|15||For if the foot should say, Because I am not the hand, I am not of the body; is it, on that account, not of the body?
1CO|12|16||Or if the ear should say, Because I am not the eye, I am not of the body; is it, on that account, not of the body?
1CO|12|17||And if the whole body were an eye, where would be the hearing? Or if it were all hearing, where would be the smelling?
1CO|12|18||But now hath God placed every one of the members in the body, according to his pleasure.
1CO|12|19||And if they were all one member, where would be the body?
1CO|12|20||But now they are many members, yet but one body.
1CO|12|21||The eye cannot say to the hand, Thou art not needful to me: nor can the head say to the feet, Ye are not needful to me.
1CO|12|22||But rather, those members which are accounted feeble, are indispensable.
1CO|12|23||And those which we think dishonorable in the body, on them we heap more honor; and those that are uncomely, on them we put the more decoration.
1CO|12|24||For the honorable members in us, have no need of honor: for God hath tempered the body, and given more honor to the member which is inferior;
1CO|12|25||that there might be no disunion in the body, but that all the members, equally, might care for one another;
1CO|12|26||so that, when one member is in pain, they will all sympathize; and if one member is exalted, all the members will be exalted.
1CO|12|27||Now ye are the body of Messiah, and members in your place.
1CO|12|28||For God hath placed in his church, first, legates; after them, prophets; after them, teachers; after them, workers of miracles; after them, the gifts of healing, and helpers, and leaders, and [various] kinds of tongues.
1CO|12|29||Are they all legates? Are they all prophets? Are they all teachers? Are they all workers of miracles?
1CO|12|30||Have all of them the gifts of healing? Do they all speak with tongues? Or do they all interpret?
1CO|12|31||And if ye are emulous of the superior gifts, on the other hand, I show to you a better way.
1CO|13|1||If I could speak in every tongue of men, and in that of angels, and there should be no love in me, I should be like brass that resoundeth, or the cymbal that maketh a noise.
1CO|13|2||And if there should be in me [the gift of] prophecy, and I should understand all the mysteries, and every science; and if there should be in me all faith, so that I could move mountains, and love should not be in me, I should be nothing.
1CO|13|3||And if I should feed out to the destitute all I possess; and if I should give my body to be burned; and there should be no love in me, I gain nothing.
1CO|13|4||Love is long-suffering, and is kind; love is not envious; love is not boisterous; and is not inflated;
1CO|13|5||and doth nothing that causeth shame; and seeketh not her own; is not passionate; and thinketh no evil;
1CO|13|6||rejoiceth not in iniquity, but rejoiceth in the truth;
1CO|13|7||beareth all things, believeth all things, hopeth all, and endureth all.
1CO|13|8||Love will never cease. But prophesyings will end; and tongues will be silent; and knowledge will vanish.
1CO|13|9||For we know but partially; and we prophesy but partially.
1CO|13|10||But when completeness shall come, then that which is partial will vanish away.
1CO|13|11||When I was a child, I talked as a child, and I reasoned as a child, and I thought as a child: but when I became a man, I laid aside the things of childhood.
1CO|13|12||And now we see, as by a mirror, in similitude; but then face to face: now I know partially; but then shall I know, just as I am known.
1CO|13|13||For these three things are abiding, faith, and hope, and love; but the greatest of these is love.
1CO|14|1||Follow after love; and be emulous of the gifts of the Spirit, and especially, that ye may prophesy.
1CO|14|2||For he that speaketh in a tongue, speaketh not unto men, but unto God; for no one understandeth what is said; yet in the spirit, he speaketh a mystery.
1CO|14|3||But he that prophesieth, speaketh unto men, for edification, and exhortation, and consolation.
1CO|14|4||He that speaketh in a tongue, edifieth himself: and he that prophesieth, edifieth the church.
1CO|14|5||Now I would that ye all spoke with tongues, but rather that ye prophesied; for greater is he that prophesieth, than he that speaketh in a tongue, unless he interpret; and if he interpret, he edifieth the church.
1CO|14|6||And now, my brethren, if I should come among you, and speak to you in tongues, what should I profit you; unless I should speak to you either by revelation, or by knowledge, or by prophecy, or by doctrine?
1CO|14|7||For even inanimate things that emit sound, whether pipe or harp, if they make no distinction between one sound and another, how will it be known, what is sung or what is harped?
1CO|14|8||And if the trumpet shall give an uncertain sound, who will prepare himself for the battle?
1CO|14|9||So likewise if ye utter a discourse in a tongue, and there is no interpretation given, how will it be known what ye have said? Ye will have been as if ye spoke into the air.
1CO|14|10||For lo, there are many kinds of tongues in the world; and there is not one of them without meaning.
1CO|14|11||But if I do not know the import of the sound, I shall be a barbarian to him that speaketh, and the speaker will be a barbarian to me.
1CO|14|12||So also ye, since ye are emulous of the gifts of the Spirit for the edification of the church, seek ye to excel.
1CO|14|13||And let him that speaketh in a tongue, pray that he may interpret.
1CO|14|14||For if I should pray in a tongue, my spirit prayeth, but my understanding is without fruits.
1CO|14|15||What then shall I do? I will pray with my spirit, and will pray with my understanding; and I will sing with my spirit, and will sing with my understanding.
1CO|14|16||Otherwise, if thou blessest in the spirit, how shall he that filleth the place of one unlearned, say Amen, on thy giving thanks; for he knoweth not what thou sayest?
1CO|14|17||Thou blessest, indeed, very well; but thy neighbor is not edified.
1CO|14|18||I thank God, that I speak with tongues more than all of you.
1CO|14|19||But in the church, I would rather speak five words with my understanding, that I might instruct others, than a myriad of words in a tongue.
1CO|14|20||My brethren, be ye not children in your thoughts; but to evil things be ye infants; and in your thoughts be men.
1CO|14|21||In the law it is written, With a foreign speech, and in another tongue, will I speak with this people; and even so also they will not hearken to me, saith the Lord.
1CO|14|22||Wherefore, tongues are established for a sign, not to the believers, but to them that believe not. But prophesyings are not for those who believe not, but for them that believe.
1CO|14|23||If therefore the whole church assemble, and they all speak with tongues, and there come in unlearned persons, or such as believe not, will they not say: These people are crazy?
1CO|14|24||But if ye should be all prophesying, and one unlearned or an unbeliever should come among you, he is explored by you all, and rebuked by you all;
1CO|14|25||and the secrets of his heart are laid open [to him]: and so he will fall upon his face, and will worship God, and say: Verily, God is in you.
1CO|14|26||I therefore say [to you] my brethren, that when ye assemble, whoever of you hath a psalm, let him speak; and whoever hath a doctrine, and whoever hath a revelation, and whoever hath a tongue, and whoever hath an interpretation. Let them all be for edification.
1CO|14|27||And if any speak in a tongue, let two speak or at most, three; and let them speak one by one; and let [some] one interpret.
1CO|14|28||And if there is none to interpret, let him that speaketh in a tongue, be silent in the church; and let him speak to himself and to God.
1CO|14|29||And as to prophets, let two or three speak, and let the rest judge.
1CO|14|30||And if to another sitting by, there should be a revelation, let the first stop speaking.
1CO|14|31||For ye can all prophesy, one by one; so that every one may learn, and every one be comforted.
1CO|14|32||For the spirit of the prophets is subject to the prophets.
1CO|14|33||Because, God is not [the author] of tumult, but of peace, as in all churches of the saints.
1CO|14|34||Let your women be silent in the church: for it is not permitted them to speak, but to be in subjection, as also the law saith.
1CO|14|35||And if they wish to be informed on any subject, let them ask their husbands at home: for it is unbecoming for women to speak in the church.
1CO|14|36||What! was it from you that the word of God came forth? Or did it reach only to you?
1CO|14|37||And if any one among you thinketh that he is a prophet, or that he is spiritual, let him recognize the things which I write to you, as being the precepts of our Lord.
1CO|14|38||But if any one be ignorant, let him be ignorant.
1CO|14|39||Wherefore, my brethren, be emulous of prophesying: and to speak with tongues, prohibit not.
1CO|14|40||But let every thing be done with decency and regularity.
1CO|15|1||And I make known to you, my brethren, the gospel which I preached to you, and which ye received, and in which ye stand,
1CO|15|2||and by which ye have life. In what terms I preached to you, ye remember; unless ye have believed in vain.
1CO|15|3||For I delivered to you from the first, as I had received it; that the Messiah died on account of our sins, as it is written:
1CO|15|4||and that he was buried and arose on the third day, as it is written:
1CO|15|5||and that he was seen by Cephas; and after him, by the twelve:
1CO|15|6||and after that, he was seen by more than five hundred brethren at once; many of whom survive at the present time, and some of them sleep.
1CO|15|7||And subsequently to this, he was seen by James; and after him, by all the legates.
1CO|15|8||And last of them all, he was seen by me, as it were by an abortion.
1CO|15|9||I am the least of the legates; and am not worthy to be called a legate; because I persecuted the church of God.
1CO|15|10||But by the grace of God, I am what I am: and his grace, that was in me, was not in vain; but I labored more than they all:not I, but his grace that was with me.
1CO|15|11||Whether I, therefore, or whether they, so we preached; and so ye believed.
1CO|15|12||And if the Messiah is proclaimed, as rising from the dead; how is it that there are some among you, who say, There is no reviviscence of the dead?
1CO|15|13||And if there is no reviviscence of the dead, the Messiah also hath not risen.
1CO|15|14||And if the Messiah hath not risen, our preaching is vain, and your faith also vain.
1CO|15|15||And we too are found false witnesses of God; for we have testified concerning God, that he raised up the Messiah, when he did not raise him up.
1CO|15|16||For, if the dead will not arise, the Messiah also hath not risen.
1CO|15|17||And if the Messiah rose not, your faith is inane; and ye are yet in your sins:
1CO|15|18||and also, doubtless, they who have fallen asleep in the Messiah, have perished.
1CO|15|19||And if, in this life only, we have hope in the Messiah, we are the most miserable of all men.
1CO|15|20||But now the Messiah hath risen from the dead, and become the first-fruits of them that slept.
1CO|15|21||And as by a man came death, so also by a man came the reviviscence of the dead.
1CO|15|22||For as it was by Adam, that all men die, so also by the Messiah they all live:
1CO|15|23||every one in his order; the Messiah was the first-fruits; afterwards, they that are the Messiah's, at his coming.
1CO|15|24||And then will be the end, when he shall have delivered up the kingdom to God the Father; when every prince, and every sovereign, and all powers shall have come to naught.
1CO|15|25||For he is to reign, until he shall put all his enemies under his feet.
1CO|15|26||And the last enemy, death, will be abolished.
1CO|15|27||For he hath subjected all under his feet. But when he said, that every thing is subjected to him, it is manifest that he is excepted, who subjected all to him.
1CO|15|28||And when all shall be subjected to him, then the Son himself will be subject to him who subjected all to him, so that God will be all in all.
1CO|15|29||Otherwise, what shall they do who are baptized for the dead, if the dead rise not? Why are they baptized for the dead?
1CO|15|30||And why also do we stand every hour in peril?
1CO|15|31||I protest, my brethren, by your exultation, which is mine in our Lord Jesus the Messiah, that I die daily.
1CO|15|32||If, as amongst men, I was cast to wild beasts at Ephesus, what did it profit me, if the dead rise not? "Let us eat and drink; for to-morrow we die."
1CO|15|33||Be not deceived; "Evil stories corrupt well-disposed minds."
1CO|15|34||Let your hearts be righteously excited, and sin not: for there are some, in whom is not the love of God: it is to your shame, I say it.
1CO|15|35||But some one of you may say: How will the dead arise? and with what body will they come forth?
1CO|15|36||Foolish man! The seed which thou sowest, is not quickened, unless it die.
1CO|15|37||And that which thou sowest, thou sowest not the body that is to be, but the naked kernel of wheat or barley, or of the other grains:
1CO|15|38||and God giveth it a body, as he pleaseth; and to each of the grains its natural body.
1CO|15|39||And every body is not alike; for the body of a man is one thing, and that of a beast is another, and that of a bird is another, and that of a fish is another.
1CO|15|40||And there are bodies celestial, and bodies terrestrial; but the glory of the celestial [bodies] is one, and that of the terrestrial is another.
1CO|15|41||And the glory of the sun is one thing, and the glory of the moon is another, and the glory of the stars is another; and one star exceedeth another star in glory.
1CO|15|42||So also in the reviviscence of the dead. They are sown in corruption, they arise without corruption:
1CO|15|43||they are sown in dishonor, they arise in glory: they are sown in weakness, they arise in power:
1CO|15|44||it is sown an animal body, it ariseth a spiritual body. For there is a body of the animal life, and there is a body of the spirit.
1CO|15|45||So also is it written: "Adam, the first man, became a living soul;" the second Adam [became] a quickening spirit.
1CO|15|46||And the spiritual was not first; but the animal, and then the spiritual.
1CO|15|47||The first man was of dust from the earth; the second man was the Lord from heaven.
1CO|15|48||As he was of the dust, so also those who are of the dust; and as was he who was from heaven, so also are the heavenly.
1CO|15|49||And as we have worn the likeness of him from the dust, so shall we wear the likeness of him from heaven.
1CO|15|50||But this I say, my brethren that flesh and blood cannot inherit the kingdom of heaven: neither doth corruption inherit incorruption.
1CO|15|51||Lo, I tell you a mystery; we shall not all sleep, but we shall all be changed,
1CO|15|52||suddenly, as in the twinkling of an eye, at the last trumpet, when it shall sound; and the dead will arise, without corruption; and we shall be changed.
1CO|15|53||For this which is corruptible, is to put on incorruption; and that which dieth, will put on immortality.
1CO|15|54||And when this that is corruptible, shall put on incorruption, and this that dieth, immortality; then will take place the word that is written, "Death is absorbed in victory."
1CO|15|55||Where is thy sting, O death? And where is thy victory, O grave?
1CO|15|56||Now the sting of death is sin; and the strength of sin is the law.
1CO|15|57||But thanks be to God, that giveth us the victory, through our Lord Jesus the Messiah.
1CO|15|58||Wherefore, my brethren and my beloved, be ye steadfast, and be not vacillating; but be ye at all times abundant in the work of the Lord; seeing ye know, that your labor is not in vain in the Lord.
1CO|16|1||And as to the collection for the saints, as I directed the churches of the Galatians, so do ye.
1CO|16|2||On each first day of the week, let every one of you lay aside and preserve at home, what he is able; that there may be no collections when I come.
1CO|16|3||And when I come, those whom ye shall select, I will send with a letter, to carry your bounty to Jerusalem.
1CO|16|4||And if it should be suitable that I also go, they shall go with me.
1CO|16|5||And I will come to you, when I pass from Macedonia; for I am about to pass through Macedonia.
1CO|16|6||And perhaps I shall remain with you, or winter with you; that ye may accompany me whither I go.
1CO|16|7||For I am not disposed to see you now, as I pass along; because I hope to spend some time with you, if my Lord permit me.
1CO|16|8||For I shall continue at Ephesus until Pentecost:
1CO|16|9||because a great door is opened to me, which is full of occupations; and the opposers are numerous.
1CO|16|10||And if Timothy come to you, see that he may be without fear among you; for he doeth the work of the Lord, as I do.
1CO|16|11||Therefore, let no one despise him; but conduct him on in peace, that he may come to me; for I wait for him with the brethren.
1CO|16|12||As for Apollos, my brethren, I entreated him much to go with the brethren to you; but his inclination was not to go to you now; but when he shall have opportunity, he will go to you.
1CO|16|13||Watch ye, stand firm in the faith, act like men, be valiant.
1CO|16|14||Let all your affairs be conducted with love.
1CO|16|15||I beseech you, my brethren, concerning the household of Stephanas; (for ye know, that they were the first-fruits of Achaia, and that they have devoted themselves to ministering to the saints;)
1CO|16|16||that ye also give ear to them who are such; and to every one, that laboreth with us and aideth.
1CO|16|17||And I rejoice at the arrival of Stephanas and Fortunatus and Achaicus: for they have supplied that wherein ye were deficient towards me.
1CO|16|18||And they have refreshed my spirit, and yours: therefore acknowledge ye them who are such.
1CO|16|19||All the churches that are in Asia, salute you. Aquila and Priscilla, with the church in their house, salute you much in the Lord.
1CO|16|20||All the brethren salute you. Salute ye one another with a holy kiss.
1CO|16|21||The salutation in the handwriting of myself, Paul.
1CO|16|22||Whoever loveth not our Lord Jesus the Messiah, let him be accursed: our Lord cometh.
1CO|16|23||The grace of our Lord Jesus the Messiah be with you.
1CO|16|24||And my love be with you all, in the Messiah, Jesus. Amen.
2CO|1|1||Paul a legate of Jesus the Messiah, by the good pleasure of God; and Timothy a brother; to the church of God that is at Corinth, and to all the saints that are in all Achaia.
2CO|1|2||Grace be with you, and peace, from God our Father, and from our Lord Jesus the Messiah.
2CO|1|3||Blessed be God, the Father of our Lord Jesus the Messiah, the Father of mercies, and the God of all consolation;
2CO|1|4||who comforteth us in all our afflictions, that we also might be able to comfort those who are in all afflictions, with the consolation wherewith we are comforted by God.
2CO|1|5||For, as the sufferings of the Messiah abound in us, so also our consolation aboundeth by the Messiah.
2CO|1|6||And whether we be afflicted, it is for your consolation and for your life that we are afflicted; or whether we be comforted, it is, that ye may be comforted; and that there may be in you an eagerness, wherewith ye may endure those sufferings which we also suffer.
2CO|1|7||And our hope concerning you is steadfast: for we know, that if ye partake of the sufferings, ye will also partake of the consolation.
2CO|1|8||But, my brethren, we wish you to know, respecting the affliction that was upon us in Asia, that we were afflicted exceedingly, beyond our strength, insomuch that our life was ready to terminate.
2CO|1|9||And we passed a sentence of death upon ourselves, that our confidence might not be in ourselves, but in God, who raiseth up the dead;
2CO|1|10||who rescued us from imminent death: and we hope that he will again rescue us,
2CO|1|11||by the aid of your prayers in our behalf; so that his gift to us may be a favor done for the sake of many, and many may praise him on our account.
2CO|1|12||For our rejoicing is this, the testimony of our conscience, that in simplicity and purity, and by the grace of God, and not in the wisdom of the flesh, we have conducted ourselves in the world, and especially towards you.
2CO|1|13||We write no other things unto you, than those which ye know and acknowledge. And I trust, ye will acknowledge them to the end:
2CO|1|14||as ye have also partially acknowledged that we are your rejoicing, as ye also are ours, in the day of our Lord Jesus the Messiah.
2CO|1|15||And in this confidence, I was before disposed to come to you, that ye might receive the grace doubly;
2CO|1|16||and to pass by you into Macedonia, and again to come to you from Macedonia, and [so] ye would accompany me to Judaea.
2CO|1|17||When therefore I thus purposed, did I purpose as one inconsiderate? Or, were the things I purposed, things of the flesh; so that there should be in them Yes, yes, and No, no?
2CO|1|18||God is the witness, that our word to you was not Yes and No.
2CO|1|19||For the Son of God, Jesus the Messiah, who was preached to you by us, [namely,] by me, by Sylvanus, and by Timotheus, was not Yes and No; but it was Yes in him.
2CO|1|20||For all the promises of God in him, the Messiah, are Yes; for which cause, we through him give [our] Amen, to the glory of God.
2CO|1|21||Now it is God who establisheth us, with you, in the Messiah, and hath anointed us,
2CO|1|22||and hath sealed us, and hath given the earnest of his Spirit in our hearts.
2CO|1|23||Moreover, I call God for a witness on my soul, that it was in order to spare you, that I came not to Corinth.
2CO|1|24||Not that we are lords over your faith, but we are helpers of your joy; for it is by faith ye stand.
2CO|2|1||And I determined this with myself, that I would not again come to you in sadness.
2CO|2|2||For if I should make you sad, who would make me joyful, unless he whom I had made sad?
2CO|2|3||And I wrote that very thing to you, lest when I came, those persons whom I ought to make joyful, should make me sad. For I have confidence concerning you, that my joy is the joy of you all.
2CO|2|4||And in much affliction, and in anguish of heart, I wrote those things to you, with many tears; not that ye might have sorrow, but that ye might know the exceeding love I have for you.
2CO|2|5||And if one hath caused grief, he hath not grieved me [only], but,that the declaration may not bear too hard on youin a measure, all of you.
2CO|2|6||And sufficient for him, is this rebuke proceeding from many:
2CO|2|7||so that, on the other hand, ye ought to forgive him and console him; lest he who is such a man, should be swallowed up with excessive grief.
2CO|2|8||I therefore beseech you, that ye confirm to him your love.
2CO|2|9||For it was for this also that I wrote [to you], that I might learn by a trial, whether ye would be obedient in every thing.
2CO|2|10||And whom ye forgive, I also [forgive]: for that which I forgave to any one, for your sakes I forgave it, in the presence of the Messiah;
2CO|2|11||lest Satan should overreach us; for we know his devices.
2CO|2|12||Moreover, when I came to Troas in announcing the Messiah, and a door was opened to me by the Lord,
2CO|2|13||there was no quietude in my spirit, because I found not Titus my brother: and I took leave of them, and went into Macedonia.
2CO|2|14||But thanks be to God, who always procureth us a triumph in the Messiah, and manifesteth by us the odor of the knowledge of him in every place.
2CO|2|15||For, through the Messiah, we are unto God a sweet odor, in them that live and in them that perish:
2CO|2|16||to these, an odor of death unto death; and to those, an odor of life unto life. And who is adequate to these things!
2CO|2|17||For we are not like others, who dilute the words of God; but as of the truth, and as of God, we speak in the Messiah before God.
2CO|3|1||Do we begin again to show you who we are? Or do we, like others, need that letters recommendatory of us should be written to you? Or, that ye should write recommendations of us?
2CO|3|2||Ye are our epistle, written on our hearts, and known and read by every man.
2CO|3|3||For ye know that ye are an epistle of the Messiah, ministered by us; not written with ink, but by the Spirit of the living God; not on tables of stone, but on the tablets of the heart of flesh.
2CO|3|4||And such confidence have we in the Messiah towards God.
2CO|3|5||Not that we are sufficient to think any thing as of ourselves; but our efficiency is from God:
2CO|3|6||who hath fitted us to be ministers of the new Testament, not in the letter, but in the Spirit; for the letter killeth, but the Spirit giveth life.
2CO|3|7||Now if the ministration of death was engraved upon stones in writing, and was so glorious that the children of Israel could not look on the face of Moses, on account of the glory upon his face which vanished away;
2CO|3|8||how then shall not the ministration of the Spirit be still more glorious?
2CO|3|9||For if there was glory in the ministration of condemnation, how much more shall the ministration of justification excel in glory?
2CO|3|10||For that which was glorious, was as if not glorious, in comparison with this which excelleth in glory.
2CO|3|11||For if that which is abolished was glorious, much more must that which abideth be glorious.
2CO|3|12||Seeing therefore we have this hope, we the more speak with boldness;
2CO|3|13||and are not like Moses, who threw a vail over his face, that the children of Israel might not behold the termination of that which was abolished.
2CO|3|14||But they were blinded in their understanding; for until this day, when the old Testament is read, the same vail resteth upon them; nor is it manifest [to them], that it is abolished by the Messiah.
2CO|3|15||And unto this day, when Moses is read, a vail is thrown upon their hearts.
2CO|3|16||But when any of them is turned unto the Lord, the vail is taken from him.
2CO|3|17||Now the Lord himself is the Spirit. And where the Spirit of the Lord is, there is freedom.
2CO|3|18||And we all, with uncovered faces, behold as in a mirror the glory of the Lord; and are transformed into the same likeness, from glory to glory, as by the Lord the Spirit.
2CO|4|1||Therefore, we are not weary in this ministry which we have received, according to the mercies that have been upon us:
2CO|4|2||But we have renounced the concealments of dishonor, and we walk not in craftiness, nor do we treat the word of God deceitfully; but by the manifestation of the truth, we exhibit ourselves to all the consciences of men before God.
2CO|4|3||And if our gospel is vailed, it is vailed to them that perish;
2CO|4|4||to them whose minds the God of this world hath blinded, in order that they might not believe, lest the light of the gospel of the glory of the Messiah (who is the likeness of God) should dawn upon them.
2CO|4|5||For it is not ourselves that we preach, but the Messiah, Jesus our Lord; and, as to ourselves, that we are your servants for Jesus' sake.
2CO|4|6||Because God, who commanded the light to arise from darkness, hath himself shined in our hearts, that we might be illuminated with the knowledge of the glory of God on the face of Jesus the Messiah.
2CO|4|7||But we have this treasure in an earthen vessel, that the excellency of the power might be from God, and not from us.
2CO|4|8||And in every thing we are oppressed, but not suffocated; we are corrected, but not condemned;
2CO|4|9||we are persecuted, but not forsaken; we are prostrated, but perish not.
2CO|4|10||For we bear in our body, at all times, the dying of Jesus; that the life also of Jesus might be manifested in our body.
2CO|4|11||For if we are delivered over alive unto death, for Jesus' sake, even so also will the life of Jesus be manifested in this our mortal body.
2CO|4|12||Now therefore, in us death is active, but in you, life.
2CO|4|13||Having therefore the same spirit of faith, (as it is written, I believed, therefore also have I spoken,) we also believe, and therefore speak;
2CO|4|14||knowing that he, who resuscitated our Lord Jesus, will also resuscitate us by Jesus, and will receive us, with you, to himself.
2CO|4|15||For all things are for your sakes, that while grace aboundeth by means of many, thanksgiving may abound to the glory of God.
2CO|4|16||For this cause we faint not; for though our outward man perish, yet the inner [man] is renovated day by day.
2CO|4|17||For the affliction of the present time, though very small and light, prepareth for us great glory, without end, for ever and ever;
2CO|4|18||while we look not at these seen things, but at those not seen; for these seen things are temporary, but those not seen are eternal.
2CO|5|1||For we know that, if our house on earththis of the body, were dissolved, yet we have a building of God, a house not made with hands, eternal in heaven.
2CO|5|2||And on this account also, we groan, and wish to be clothed with our house from heaven:
2CO|5|3||if indeed, when clothed, we shall not be found naked.
2CO|5|4||For while we are here in this house, we groan under its burden; yet ye desire, not to throw it off; but to be clothed over it, so that its mortality may be absorbed in life.
2CO|5|5||And he that prepareth us for this thing, is God: who hath given us the earnest of his Spirit.
2CO|5|6||Therefore, because we know and are persuaded, that while we lodge in the body we sojourn away from our Lord;
2CO|5|7||(for we walk by faith, and not by sight;)
2CO|5|8||therefore we are confident, and desirous to be away from the body, and to be with our Lord.
2CO|5|9||We are assiduous, that whether we are absent, or whether at home, we may please him.
2CO|5|10||For we are all to stand before the judgment-seat of the Messiah, that each may receive retribution in the body, [for] what he hath done in it, whether of good, or whether of evil.
2CO|5|11||Therefore because we know the fear of our Lord we persuade men; and we are made manifest unto God; and I hope also, we are made manifest to your minds.
2CO|5|12||We do not again laud ourselves to you; but we give you occasion to glory in us, to them who glory in appearance and not in heart.
2CO|5|13||For if we are extravagant, it is for God: and if we are discreet, it is for you.
2CO|5|14||For the love of the Messiah constraineth us to reason thus: One died for all; therefore are all dead.
2CO|5|15||And he died for all, that they who live should not live to themselves, but to him who died for them and rose again.
2CO|5|16||And therefore, we know no person after the flesh: and if we have known the Messiah after the flesh, yet henceforth we know [him] no more.
2CO|5|17||Whoever therefore is in the Messiah, is a new creature: old things have passed away;
2CO|5|18||and all things are made new, by God; who hath reconciled us to himself by the Messiah, and hath given to us the ministry of reconciliation.
2CO|5|19||For God was in the Messiah, who hath reconciled the world with his majesty, and did not reckon to them their sins; and who hath placed in us the word of reconciliation.
2CO|5|20||We are therefore ambassadors for the Messiah, and it is as if God was beseeching you by us. In behalf of the Messiah, therefore, we beseech [you], be ye reconciled to God.
2CO|5|21||For, on your account, he hath made him who knew no sin to be sin, that we might by him become the righteousness of God.
2CO|6|1||And as aiders we entreat of you, that the grace of God which ye have received, may not be ineffectual in you.
2CO|6|2||For he hath said, In an acceptable time have I heard thee, and in the day of life I have aided thee. Behold, now is the acceptable time! and behold, now is the day of life!
2CO|6|3||Give ye no occasion of offence to any one in any thing, that there may be no reproach on our ministry.
2CO|6|4||But we, in all things, would show ourselves to be the ministers of God, in much endurance, in afflictions, in necessity, in distresses,
2CO|6|5||in scourgings, in imprisonments, in tumults, in toil, in watching, in fasting;
2CO|6|6||by purity, by knowledge, by long suffering, by benignity, by the Holy Spirit, by love unfeigned,
2CO|6|7||by the speaking of truth, by the energy of God, by the armor of righteousness on the right hand and on the left;
2CO|6|8||amid honor and dishonor, amid praise and contumely; as deceivers, and yet true;
2CO|6|9||as not known, and yet we are well known; as dying, and behold, we live; as chastised, yet not killed;
2CO|6|10||as sorrowful, yet always rejoicing; as indigent, yet enriching many; as possessing nothing, yet having all things.
2CO|6|11||O ye Corinthians, our mouth is opened towards you, and our heart expanded.
2CO|6|12||Ye are not straitened in us, but ye are straitened in your own bowels.
2CO|6|13||I speak as to [my] children, Pay me the debt which ye owe, and expand your love towards me.
2CO|6|14||And be ye not yoke-fellows with them that believe not: for what fellowship hath righteousness with iniquity? or what communion hath light with darkness?
2CO|6|15||or what concord hath the Messiah with Satan? or what part hath a believer with an unbeliever?
2CO|6|16||or what agreement hath the temple of God with that of demons? For ye are the temple of the living God; as it is said, I will dwell among them, and walk among them, and will be their God, and they shall be my people.
2CO|6|17||Wherefore, come ye out from among them, and be ye separate from them, saith the Lord; and come not near the unclean thing, and I will receive you;
2CO|6|18||and will be to you a Father, and ye shall be sons and daughters to me, saith the Lord Almighty.
2CO|7|1||Seeing, therefore, we have these promises, my beloved, let us cleanse ourselves from all defilement of the flesh and of the spirit; and let us work righteousness, in the fear of God.
2CO|7|2||Bear with us, my brethren; we have done evil to no one; we have corrupted no one; we have wronged no one.
2CO|7|3||I speak [thus], not to condemn you; for I have said before, that ye are treasured in our hearts, to die and to live together.
2CO|7|4||I have great assurance before you, and have much glorying in you; and I am full of comfort. And joy greatly aboundeth to me, in all my afflictions.
2CO|7|5||For, after we came to Macedonia, there was no rest for our body, but we were distressed in every thing; without was conflict, and within was fear.
2CO|7|6||But God who comforteth the depressed, comforted us by the arrival of Titus.
2CO|7|7||And not merely by his arrival, but also by the refreshing with which he was refreshed by you. For he told us of your love towards us, and of your grief, and of your zeal in our behalf: and when I heard it, my joy was great.
2CO|7|8||And although I made you sad by the epistle, I do not regret it, though I did regret it; for I see that that epistle, though for a time it made you sad,
2CO|7|9||yet it procured me joy, not because ye had sorrow, but because your sorrow brought you to repentance; for ye sorrowed in godly sorrow; so that ye received no detriment from us.
2CO|7|10||For, sorrowing on account of God, worketh a conversion of the soul which is not reversed, and a turning unto life: but the sorrowing of the world worketh death.
2CO|7|11||For behold this same thing, that ye were distressed on account of God, what solicitude it wrought in you, and apologizing and indignation, and fear, and love, and zeal, and revenge? And in all things ye have shown, that ye are [now] pure in that matter.
2CO|7|12||And it will be [seen] that I wrote to you, not for the sake of him who did the wrong, nor for the sake of him who received the wrong, [only,] but that your solicitude in respect to us might be known before God.
2CO|7|13||Wherefore we were comforted; and with our consolation, we were the more joyful for the joy of Titus, because his spirit was refreshed by you all:
2CO|7|14||so that I was not ashamed of that in which I had gloried to him, respecting you; but as in every thing we spoke the truth to you, so also our glorying before Titus, is found to be in truth:
2CO|7|15||and also his bowels are the more enlarged towards you, while he remembereth the submission of you all, and how ye received him with fear and trembling.
2CO|7|16||I rejoice, that in every thing I have full confidence in you.
2CO|8|1||And, my brethren, we make known to you the grace of God which was conferred on the churches of the Macedonians;
2CO|8|2||that in the great trial of their affliction, there was an abounding to their joy, and the depth of their poverty was exuberant in the riches of their liberality.
2CO|8|3||For I testify that, according to their ability, and beyond their ability, in the spontaneity of their mind,
2CO|8|4||they besought us, with much entreaty, that they might participate in the beneficence of the ministration to the saints.
2CO|8|5||And not [only] as we had expected, but they first gave themselves unto the Lord, and to us by the will of God.
2CO|8|6||So that we requested Titus, that as he had begun, so he would perfect in you also the same beneficence.
2CO|8|7||And as ye are enriched in every thing, in faith, and speech, and knowledge, and in all diligence, and in our love towards you, so abound ye in this beneficence also.
2CO|8|8||I do not actually command you, but by the promptitude of your fellow [disciples], I would test the sincerity of your love.
2CO|8|9||For ye know the goodness of our Lord Jesus the Messiah, who when he was rich, for your sakes became poor, that by his poverty ye might be made rich.
2CO|8|10||And I urgently recommend to you, that which is for your advantage; inasmuch as ye began, a year ago, not only to purpose, but also to perform.
2CO|8|11||And now complete ye by action, what ye purposed; that as ye had a promptitude in your purposing, so ye may fulfill [it] in action, according to your ability.
2CO|8|12||For if there is a willingness, a person is accepted according to what he hath, and not according to what he hath not.
2CO|8|13||For it is not, that others may have easement, and you pressure;
2CO|8|14||but that ye may be on equality at the present time; and that your abundance may be [a supply] to their want; that their abundance likewise may be [a supply] to your want; that there may be equality.
2CO|8|15||As it is written, He who gathered much, had nothing over; and he that gathered little, was not deficient.
2CO|8|16||But thanks be to God, who put into the heart of Titus this solicitude for you.
2CO|8|17||For he received our exhortation; and, because he was very anxious, he cheerfully set out to visit you.
2CO|8|18||And we also sent with him that our brother, whose praise in the gospel is in all the churches;
2CO|8|19||inasmuch as he likewise had been expressly chosen by the churches, to accompany me with this beneficence which is ministered by us to the glory of God and to our cordiality.
2CO|8|20||And we hereby guarded, that no one should cast censure on us, in [respect to] this abundance which is ministered by us.
2CO|8|21||For we are attentive to things commendable, not only before God, but also before men.
2CO|8|22||And we also sent with them that brother of ours, who hath often, and in many things, been proved diligent by us; and is now particularly diligent, from the great confidence [he hath] in you.
2CO|8|23||And therefore, if Titus [be inquired about], he is my associate and assistant among you: or if our other brethren, they are the legates of the churches of the Messiah's glory.
2CO|8|24||Therefore exhibit ye to them, in the presence of all the churches, a demonstration of your love and of our glorying respecting you.
2CO|9|1||And concerning the ministration by the saints, it would be superfluous for me to write to you:
2CO|9|2||for I know the goodness of your mind; and therefore I gloried of you before the Macedonians, that Achaia was ready a year ago; and your zeal hath excited many.
2CO|9|3||Yet I sent the brethren, lest the glorying with which we have gloried in you in regard to this matter, should prove vain; and that ye, as I said, may be ready;
2CO|9|4||so that, if the Macedonians should come with me, and should find you unprepared, wenot to say, yeshould be put to shame for that glorying in which we gloried.
2CO|9|5||Therefore I was careful to request these my brethren, to go before me unto you, that they might make up this benefaction, of which ye were advised long before to have it ready, as being a benefaction, and not a matter of cupidity.
2CO|9|6||And this [I say]: He that soweth sparingly, shall also reap sparingly; and he that soweth bountifully, shall also reap bountifully.
2CO|9|7||Every man, according to his own views, not with sadness, not by constraint: for the Lord loveth a joyous giver.
2CO|9|8||For it is in the power of God, to make all good abound to you, so that ye may have, at all times, and in every thing, what is sufficient for you; and may abound in every good work.
2CO|9|9||As it is written, He hath dispersed and given to the poor; and his righteousness is established for ever.
2CO|9|10||Now he that giveth seed to the sower, and bread for food, may he give and multiply your seed, and increase the fruits of your righteousness:
2CO|9|11||so that in every thing, ye may be enriched unto all liberality, to the completion of our thanksgiving to God.
2CO|9|12||For the performance of this ministration, not only supplieth the want of the saints, but is also rich in many thanksgivings to God.
2CO|9|13||For on account of the test of this ministration, we glorify God, that ye do subject yourselves to the profession of the gospel of the Messiah, and that in your liberality, ye communicate with them and with all men:
2CO|9|14||and they put up prayer for you, with much love, because of the abundance of the grace of God that is upon you.
2CO|9|15||Thanks be to God for his unspeakable gift.
2CO|10|1||Now I, Paul, beseech you, by the mildness and gentleness of the Messiah, although I am mild towards you when present, but bold towards you when absent!
2CO|10|2||yet I beseech of you that, when I come, I may not be compelled by the boldness that is in me to be daring, as I estimate it, towards the persons who think we walk according to the flesh.
2CO|10|3||For, although we walk in the flesh, our warfare is not after the flesh.
2CO|10|4||For the arms of our warfare are not those of the flesh, but those of the power of God; by which we subdue rebellious castles.
2CO|10|5||And we demolish imaginations, and every lofty thing that exalteth itself against the knowledge of God, and subjugate all reasonings to obedience to the Messiah.
2CO|10|6||And we are prepared, when your obedience shall be complete, to execute judgment on all the disobeying.
2CO|10|7||Do ye look on outward appearances? If any one is confident in himself that he is of the Messiah, let him know, from himself, that as he is of the Messiah, so also are we.
2CO|10|8||For if I should glory somewhat more, in the authority which our Lord hath given me, I should not be ashamed; for he gave it to us for your edification, and not for your destruction.
2CO|10|9||But I forbear, lest I should be thought to terrify you terribly, by my epistles.
2CO|10|10||For there are some who say, [His] epistles are weighty and forcible, but his bodily presence is weak, and his speech contemptible.
2CO|10|11||But let him who saith so, consider this, that such as we are in our epistolary discourse, when absent, such also are we in action, when present.
2CO|10|12||For we dare not value, or compare ourselves, with those who vaunt: but they, because they compare themselves with themselves, are not wise.
2CO|10|13||But we will not glory beyond our measure, but within the measure of the limits which God hath imparted to us, that we should reach as far as you.
2CO|10|14||For we do not stretch ourselves, as if not reaching to you; for we do reach as far as you in the annunciation of the Messiah.
2CO|10|15||And we do not glory beyond our measure, in the toil of others: but we have the hope, that when your faith shall mature, we shall be magnified by you, as [being within] our measure;
2CO|10|16||and that we shall so abound also, as to make announcements beyond you. It is not in the measure of others, [and] in things ready prepared, that we will glory.
2CO|10|17||But let him that will glory, glory in the Lord.
2CO|10|18||For not he who praiseth himself, is approved; but he whom the Lord praiseth.
2CO|11|1||I would that ye could bear with me a little, that I might talk foolishly: and indeed, bear ye with me.
2CO|11|2||For I am jealous over you, with a godly jealousy: for I have espoused you to a husband as a chaste virgin, whom I would present to the Messiah.
2CO|11|3||But I fear, lest, as the serpent beguiled Eve by his craftiness, so your minds should be corrupted from simplicity towards the Messiah.
2CO|11|4||For if he that cometh to you, had proclaimed to you another Jesus, whom we have not proclaimed; or if ye had received another Spirit, which ye have not received; or another gospel, which ye have not accepted; ye might well have given assent.
2CO|11|5||For, I suppose, I came not short of those legates who most excel.
2CO|11|6||For, though I be rude in speech, yet not in knowledge; but in all things we have been manifest among you.
2CO|11|7||Did I indeed commit an offence, by humbling myself that ye might be exalted? and by proclaiming the gospel of God to you gratis?
2CO|11|8||And I robbed other churches, and I took pay [of them] for ministering to you.
2CO|11|9||And when I came among you and was needy, I was burdensome to none of you; for the brethren who came from Macedonia, supplied my wants: and in all things I kept myself, and I will keep myself, from being burdensome to you.
2CO|11|10||As the truth of the Messiah is in me, this glorying shall not be made vain as to me in the regions of Achaia.
2CO|11|11||Why? Because I do not love you? God knoweth.
2CO|11|12||But what I do, that also I will do; that I may cut off occasion, from them who seek occasion: so that in the thing wherein they glory, they may be found even as we.
2CO|11|13||For they are false legates, crafty workers, and feign themselves to be legates of the Messiah.
2CO|11|14||And in this there is nothing strange. For if Satan feigneth himself an angel of light,
2CO|11|15||it is no great thing if his ministers feign themselves ministers of righteousness; whose end shall be according to their works.
2CO|11|16||Again I say, let no one think of me, as being a fool: or if otherwise, receive me as a fool, that I may glory a little.
2CO|11|17||What I am [now] saying, I say not in our Lord, but as in folly, in this matter of glorying.
2CO|11|18||Because many glory after the flesh, I also will glory.
2CO|11|19||For ye hear with indulgence them who lack reason, seeing ye are wise.
2CO|11|20||And ye give ear to him, who putteth you in bondage; and to him, who devoureth you; and to him, who taketh from you; and to him, who exalteth himself over you; and to him, who smiteth you in the face.
2CO|11|21||I speak as if under contempt: I speak as if we were impotent, through deficiency of understanding; that in whatever thing any one is presuming, I also am presuming.
2CO|11|22||If they are Hebrews, so I also: or if they are Israelites, I also. If they are the seed of Abraham, I also.
2CO|11|23||If they are ministers of the Messiah, (in defect of understanding, I say it,) I am superior to them: in toils more than they, in stripes more than they, in bonds more than they, in deaths many times.
2CO|11|24||By the Jews, five times was I scourged, each time with forty stripes save one.
2CO|11|25||Three times was I beaten with rods: at one time I was stoned: three times I was in shipwreck, by day and by night; I have been in the sea, without a ship.
2CO|11|26||In journeyings many, in peril by rivers, in peril by robbers, in peril from my kindred, in peril from Gentiles: I have been in peril in cities; I have been in peril in the desert, in peril in the sea, in peril from false brethren.
2CO|11|27||In toil and weariness, in much watching, in hunger and thirst, in much fasting, in cold and nakedness:
2CO|11|28||besides many other things, and the thronging around me every day, and my anxiety for all the churches.
2CO|11|29||Who becometh weak, and I become not weak? Who is stumbled, and I burn not?
2CO|11|30||If I must glory, I will glory in my infirmities.
2CO|11|31||God, the Father of our Lord Jesus the Messiah, blessed for ever and ever, he knoweth that I lie not.
2CO|11|32||At Damascus, the commander of the army of Aretas the king, guarded the city of the Damascenes, to seize me.
2CO|11|33||And from a window, in a basket, they let me down from the wall, and I escaped from his hands.
2CO|12|1||Glorying must be, but it is not profitable: so I proceed to visions and revelations of our Lord.
2CO|12|2||I knew a man in the Messiah fourteen years ago, (but whether in a body, or whether out of a body, I know not; God knoweth:) who was caught up to the third [region] of heaven.
2CO|12|3||And I knew this same man; (but whether in a body, or out of a body, I know not; God knoweth;)
2CO|12|4||and he was caught up to Paradise, and heard ineffable words, which it is not permitted a man to utter.
2CO|12|5||Of him I will glory: but of myself I will not glory, except in my infirmities.
2CO|12|6||Yet if I were disposed to glory, I should not be without reason; for I declare the truth. But I refrain, lest any one should think of me, beyond what he seeth in me and heareth from me.
2CO|12|7||And, that I might not be uplifted by the excellency of the revelations, there was imparted to me a thorn in my flesh, the angel of Satan, to buffet me, that I might not be uplifted.
2CO|12|8||Respecting this, I thrice besought my Lord, that it might depart from me.
2CO|12|9||And he said to me, My grace is sufficient for thee; for my power is perfected in weakness. Gladly, therefore, will I glory in my infirmities, that the power of the Messiah may rest upon me.
2CO|12|10||Therefore I have pleasure in infirmities, in reproach, in afflictions, in persecutions, in distresses, which are for the Messiah's sake: for when I am weak, then am I strong.
2CO|12|11||Behold, I have become foolish in my glorying, for ye compelled me. For ye ought to bear witness for me; because I was inferior in nothing to those legates who most excel, although I was nothing.
2CO|12|12||I wrought among you the signs of the legates, with all patience; and in prodigies, and in wonders, and in mighty deeds.
2CO|12|13||For in what fell ye short of the other churches; except in this, that I was not burdensome to you? Forgive me this fault.
2CO|12|14||Behold, this third time I am ready to come to you, and I will not burden you; for I seek not yours, but you: for children ought not to lay up treasures for the parents, but the parents for their children.
2CO|12|15||And cheerfully will I both pay [my] expenses, and also give myself for your souls; although the more I love you, the less ye love me.
2CO|12|16||But perhaps, though I was not burdensome to you, yet, like a cunning man, I filched from you by craftiness!
2CO|12|17||Was it by the hand of some other person whom I sent to you, that I pilfered from you?
2CO|12|18||I requested Titus, and with him I sent the brethren: did Titus pilfer any thing from you? Did we not walk in one spirit, and in the same steps?
2CO|12|19||Do ye again suppose, that we would apologize to you? Before God, in the Messiah we speak: and all these things, my beloved, [are] for the sake of your edification.
2CO|12|20||For I fear, lest I should come to you and not find you such as I would wish; and lest I also should be found by you, such as ye would not wish; lest [there should be] contention, and envying, and anger, and obstinacy, and slandering, and murmuring, and insolence, and commotion;
2CO|12|21||lest, when I come to you, my God should humble me; and I should mourn over many, who have sinned, and have not repented of the impurity, the whoredom, and the lasciviousness, which they have committed.
2CO|13|1||This is the third time that I have prepare to come to you; that, by the mouth of two or three witnesses, every word may be established.
2CO|13|2||I have before said to you, and again I say to you beforehand, (as also I said to you a second time, while I was with you; and now also, while absent, I write to those who have sinned and to the others,) that if I come again, I will not spare:
2CO|13|3||because ye demand proof, that it is the Messiah that speaketh by me, who hath not been powerless among you, but powerful among you.
2CO|13|4||For, though he was crucified in weakness, yet he liveth with the power of God. We also are weak with him; yet we are alive with him, by that power of God which is among you.
2CO|13|5||Examine yourselves, whether ye stand in the faith: prove yourselves. Do ye not acknowledge that Jesus the Messiah is in you? And if [he is] not, ye are reprobates.
2CO|13|6||But, I trust, ye will know that we are not reprobates.
2CO|13|7||And I beseech God, that there may be no evil in you, so that the proof of us may appear: and yet, that ye may be doers of good things, though we be as reprobates.
2CO|13|8||For we can do nothing against the truth, but [only] for the truth.
2CO|13|9||And we rejoice, when we are weak and ye are strong. And this also we pray for, that ye may be perfected.
2CO|13|10||Therefore, while absent, I write these things; lest when I come, I should act with rigor, according to the authority which my Lord hath given me for your edification, and not for your destruction.
2CO|13|11||Finally, my brethren, rejoice, and be perfected, and be comforted: and may harmony and quietness be among you; and the God of love and of peace will be with you.
2CO|13|12||Salute ye one another, with a holy kiss.
2CO|13|13||All the saints salute you.
2CO|13|14||The peace of our Lord Jesus the Messiah, and the love of God, and the communion of the Holy Spirit be with you all. Amen.
GAL|1|1||Paul, a legate, not from men, nor by man, but by Jesus the Messiah, and God his Father, who raised him from the dead;
GAL|1|2||and all the brethren who are with me; unto the churches which are in Galatia.
GAL|1|3||Grace be with you, and peace, from God the Father, and from our Lord Jesus the Messiah;
GAL|1|4||who gave himself for our sins, that he might deliver us from this evil world, agreeably to the pleasure of God our Father:
GAL|1|5||to whom be glory for ever and ever. Amen.
GAL|1|6||I admire, how soon ye have turned from the Messiah, who called you by his grace, unto another gospel;
GAL|1|7||which doth not exist, except as there are some who would disquiet you, and are disposed to pervert the gospel of the Messiah.
GAL|1|8||But if we, or an angel from heaven, should announce to you differently from what we have announced to you, let him be accursed.
GAL|1|9||As I have just said, and now I again say it, that if any one announce to you differently from what ye received, let him be accursed.
GAL|1|10||For do I now persuade men, or God? Or do I seek to please men? For if I had till now pleased men, I should not have been a servant of the Messiah.
GAL|1|11||But I make known to you, my brethren, that the gospel announced by me, was not from man.
GAL|1|12||For I did not receive it and learn it from man, but [I had it] by revelation from Jesus the Messiah.
GAL|1|13||For ye have heard of my former course of life in Judaism, that I persecuted the church of God exceedingly, and destroyed it:
GAL|1|14||and that I went much farther in Judaism than many of my contemporaries who were of my nation, and was peculiarly zealous for the doctrine of my fathers.
GAL|1|15||But when it pleased him, who separated me from my mother's womb, and called me by his grace,
GAL|1|16||to reveal his Son by me, that I should proclaim him among the Gentiles; forthwith, I did not open it to flesh and blood;
GAL|1|17||nor did I go to Jerusalem, to them who were legates before me; but I went into Arabia, and returned again to Damascus:
GAL|1|18||and after three years, I went to Jerusalem to see Cephas; and I remained with him fifteen days.
GAL|1|19||But others of the legates I saw not, except James, our Lord's brother.
GAL|1|20||In the things which I am writing to you, behold, before God! I lie not.
GAL|1|21||And after that, I went to the regions of Syria and Cilicia.
GAL|1|22||And the churches in Judaea which were in the Messiah; did not know me personally:
GAL|1|23||but this only had they heard, that he who before persecuted us, now preacheth that faith which in time preceding he subverted:
GAL|1|24||and they glorified God in me.
GAL|2|1||And again, after fourteen years, I went up to Jerusalem with Barnabas; and I took with me Titus.
GAL|2|2||And I went up by revelation: and I explained to them the gospel which I announce among the Gentiles; and I stated it to them who were esteemed prominent, between myself and them: lest I should have run, or might run in vain.
GAL|2|3||Also Titus, who was with me, and was a Gentile, was not compelled to be circumcised.
GAL|2|4||And in regard to the false brethren, who had crept in to spy out the liberty we have in Jesus the Messiah, in order to bring me under subjection;
GAL|2|5||not for the space of an hour, did we throw ourselves into subjection to them; so that the truth of the gospel might remain with you.
GAL|2|6||And they who were esteemed prominent, (what they were, I care not; for God regardeth not the persons of men,)even these persons added nothing to me.
GAL|2|7||But, otherwise; for they saw, that the gospel of the uncircumcision was intrusted to me, as to Cephas was intrusted that of the circumcision.
GAL|2|8||For he that was operative with Cephas in the legateship of the circumcision, was also operative with me in the legateship of the Gentiles.
GAL|2|9||And James, Cephas, and John, who were accounted pillars, when they perceived the grace that was given to me, gave to me and Barnabas the right hand of fellowship; that we [should labor] among the Gentiles, and they among the circumcision.
GAL|2|10||Only [they desired] that we would be mindful of the needy; and I was solicitous to do the same.
GAL|2|11||But when Cephas was come to Antioch, I rebuked him to his face; because they were stumbled by him.
GAL|2|12||For before certain ones came from James, he ate with the Gentiles: but when they came, he withdrew himself, and separated; because he was afraid of them of the circumcision.
GAL|2|13||And the rest of the Jews also were with him in this thing; insomuch that even Barnabas was induced to regard persons.
GAL|2|14||And when I saw, that they did not walk correctly, in the truth of the gospel, I said to Cephas, before them all: If thou art a Jew, and livest in the Gentile way, and not in the Jewish, why dost thou compel the Gentiles to live in the Jewish way?
GAL|2|15||For if we, who are Jews by nature, and are not sinners of the Gentiles,
GAL|2|16||because we know that a man is not made just by the works of the law, but by faith in Jesus the Messiah; even we have believed in Jesus the Messiah, in order to be made just by faith in the Messiah, and not by the works of the law: for, by the deeds of the law, no flesh is made just.
GAL|2|17||And if, while we seek to become just by the Messiah, we are found to be ourselves sinners, is Jesus the Messiah therefore the minister of sin? Far be it!
GAL|2|18||For if I should build up again the things I had demolished, I should show myself to be a transgressor of the precept.
GAL|2|19||For I, by the law, have become dead to the law, that I might live to God; and I am crucified with the Messiah.
GAL|2|20||And henceforth it is no more I who live, but the Messiah liveth in me: and the life I now live in the flesh, I live by faith in the Son of God, who loved me and gave himself for me.
GAL|2|21||I do not spurn the grace of God. For if righteousness is by means of the law, the Messiah died in vain.
GAL|3|1||O ye Galatians, deficient in understanding! Who hath fascinated you? For lo, Jesus the Messiah hath been portrayed as in a picture, crucified before your eyes.
GAL|3|2||This only would I learn from you, Was it by works of the law, that ye received the Spirit? or by the hearing of faith?
GAL|3|3||Are ye so foolish, that having begun in the Spirit, ye now would consummate in the flesh?
GAL|3|4||And have ye borne all these things in vain? And I would, it were in vain!
GAL|3|5||He therefore who giveth the Spirit in you, and who worketh miracles among you, [doth he these things] by the deeds of the law? or by the hearing of faith?
GAL|3|6||In like manner Abraham believed God, and it was accounted to him for righteousness.
GAL|3|7||Know ye, therefore, that those who are of faith, they are the children of Abraham.
GAL|3|8||For, because God knew beforehand that the Gentiles would be made just by faith, he preannounced it to Abraham; as saith the holy scripture, In thee shall all nations be blessed.
GAL|3|9||Believers, therefore, it is, who are blessed with believing Abraham.
GAL|3|10||For they who are of the deeds of the law, are under the curse: for it is written, Cursed is every one who shall not do every thing written in this law.
GAL|3|11||And that no one becometh just before God, by the law, is manifest: because it is written, The just by faith, shall live.
GAL|3|12||Now the law is not of faith; but, whoever shall do the things written in it, shall live by them.
GAL|3|13||But the Messiah hath redeemed us from the curse of the law, and hath been a curse for us; (for it is written, Cursed is everyone that is hanged on a tree;)
GAL|3|14||that the blessing of Abraham might be on the Gentiles, through Jesus the Messiah; that we might receive the promise of the Spirit by faith.
GAL|3|15||My brethren, I speak as among men; a man's covenant which is confirmed, no one setteth aside, or changeth any thing in it.
GAL|3|16||Now to Abraham was the promise made, and to his seed. And it said to him, not, to thy seeds, as being many; but to thy seed, as being one, which is the Messiah.
GAL|3|17||And this I say: That the covenant which was previously confirmed by God in the Messiah, the law which was four hundred and thirty years after, cannot set it aside, and nullify the promise.
GAL|3|18||And if the inheritance were by the law, it would not be by promise: but God gave it to Abraham by promise.
GAL|3|19||What then is the law? It was added on account of transgression, until that seed should come, to whom belonged the promise: and the law was given by angels through a mediator.
GAL|3|20||Now a mediator is not of one; but God is one.
GAL|3|21||Is the law then opposed to the promise of God? Far be it. For if a law had been given, which could make alive, certainly, righteousness would have been by the law.
GAL|3|22||But the scripture hath inclosed all under sin, that the promise by faith in Jesus the Messiah might be given to them that believe.
GAL|3|23||But before the faith came, the law kept us shut up unto the faith that was to be revealed.
GAL|3|24||The law, therefore, was a monitor for us unto the Messiah, that we might become just by faith.
GAL|3|25||But the faith having come, we are not under the monitor.
GAL|3|26||For ye are all the children of God, by faith in Jesus the Messiah.
GAL|3|27||For they who have been baptized into the Messiah, have put on the Messiah.
GAL|3|28||There is neither Jew nor Gentile, neither slave nor free-born, neither male nor female; for ye are all one in Jesus the Messiah.
GAL|3|29||And if ye are the Messiah's, then are ye the seed of Abraham, and heirs by the promise.
GAL|4|1||But I say, that the heir, so long as he is a child, differeth not from a servant, although he is lord of all;
GAL|4|2||but he is under supervisors and stewards, until the time established by his father.
GAL|4|3||So also we, while we were children, were in subordination under the elements of the world.
GAL|4|4||But when the consummation of the time arrived, God sent forth his Son; and he was from a woman, and was under the law;
GAL|4|5||that he might redeem them that were under the law; and that we might receive the adoption of sons.
GAL|4|6||And, because ye are sons, God hath sent forth the Spirit of his Son into your hearts, who crieth, Father, our Father.
GAL|4|7||Wherefore, ye are no longer servants, but sons; and if sons, then heirs of God through Jesus the Messiah.
GAL|4|8||For then, when ye knew not God, ye served them who in their nature are not gods.
GAL|4|9||But now, since ye have known God, or rather, have been known by God, ye turn yourselves again to the weak and beggarly elements, and wish again to be under them!
GAL|4|10||Ye observe days and moons, and set times, and years!
GAL|4|11||I am afraid, lest I have labored among you in vain.
GAL|4|12||Be ye like me; because I have been like you. My brethren, I beseech you. Ye have not injured me at all.
GAL|4|13||For ye know, that under the infirmity of my flesh, I at first announced the gospel to you;
GAL|4|14||and the trial in my flesh, ye did not despise nor nauseate: but ye received me as an angel of God, and as Jesus the Messiah.
GAL|4|15||Where then is your blessedness? For I testify of you, that if it had been possible, ye would have plucked out your eyes, and have given them to me.
GAL|4|16||Have I become an enemy to you, by preaching to you the truth?
GAL|4|17||They are zealous towards you, yet not for good; but they wish to shut you up, that ye may be zealous towards them.
GAL|4|18||And it is a good thing to be zealous at all times in good things; and not merely when I am present with you.
GAL|4|19||[Ye are] my children, of whom I travail in birth again, till the Messiah be formed in you.
GAL|4|20||And I could wish to be now with you, and to change the tone of my voice; because I am astonished at you.
GAL|4|21||Tell me, ye who desire to be under the law, do ye not hear the law?
GAL|4|22||For it is written, that Abraham had two sons, one by the bondmaid, and one by the free woman.
GAL|4|23||But he that was by the bondmaid, was born after the flesh; and he that was by the free woman, was by the promise.
GAL|4|24||And these are allegorical of the two covenants; the one from mount Sinai, which bringeth forth for bondage, is Hagar.
GAL|4|25||For Hagar is the mount Sinai in Arabia, and correspondeth with the present Jerusalem, and is serving in bondage, she and her children.
GAL|4|26||But the Jerusalem above, is the free woman, who is the mother of us.
GAL|4|27||For it is written, Be joyful, thou barren, who bearest not: exult and shout, thou who hast not travailed: for more numerous are the children of the desolate than the children of the married woman.
GAL|4|28||Now we, my brethren, like Isaac, are the children of the promise.
GAL|4|29||And as then, he that was born after the flesh, persecuted him [who was born] of the Spirit; so also [is it] now.
GAL|4|30||But what saith the scripture? Cast out the bondmaid, and her son; because the son of the bondmaid shall not inherit with the son of the free woman.
GAL|4|31||So then, my brethren, we are not sons of the bondwoman, but sons of the free woman.
GAL|5|1||Stand fast, therefore, in the liberty with which the Messiah hath made us free; and be not subjected again to the yoke of bondage.
GAL|5|2||Behold, I Paul say to you, That if ye become circumcised, the Messiah is of no advantage to you.
GAL|5|3||And again, I testify to every one who becometh circumcised, that he is bound to fulfill the whole law.
GAL|5|4||Ye have renounced the Messiah, ye who seek justification by the law: and ye have apostatized from grace.
GAL|5|5||For we, through the Spirit, which is from faith, are waiting for the hope of righteousness.
GAL|5|6||For, in the Messiah Jesus, circumcision is nothing, neither is uncircumcision, but the faith that is perfected by love.
GAL|5|7||Ye did run well: who hath interrupted you, that ye acquiesce not in the truth?
GAL|5|8||The bias of your mind is not from him who called you.
GAL|5|9||A little leaven leaveneth the whole mass.
GAL|5|10||I confide in you through our Lord, that ye will entertain no other thoughts. And he that disquieteth you, shall bear his judgment, whoever he may be.
GAL|5|11||And I, my brethren, if I still preached circumcision, why should I suffer persecution? Hath the offensiveness of the cross ceased?
GAL|5|12||But I would, that they who disquiet you, were actually cut off.
GAL|5|13||And ye, my brethren, have been called into liberty: only let not your liberty be an occasion to the flesh; but, by love, be ye servants to each other.
GAL|5|14||For the whole law is fulfilled in one sentence; in this, Thou shalt love thy neighbor as thyself.
GAL|5|15||But if ye bite and devour one another, beware, lest ye be consumed one by another.
GAL|5|16||And I say: Walk ye in the Spirit; and never follow the cravings of the flesh.
GAL|5|17||For the flesh craveth that which is repugnant to the Spirit; and the Spirit craveth that which is repugnant to the flesh: and the two are the opposites of each other, so that ye do not that which ye desire.
GAL|5|18||But if ye are guided by the Spirit, ye are not under the law.
GAL|5|19||For the works of the flesh are known, which are whoredom, impurity, lasciviousness,
GAL|5|20||idol-worship, magic, malice, contention, rivalry, wrath, strife, divisions, discords,
GAL|5|21||envy, murder, drunkenness, revelling, and all the like things. And they who perpetrate these things, as I have before told you, and also now tell you, do not inherit the kingdom of God.
GAL|5|22||But the fruits of the Spirit are, love, joy, peace, long suffering, suavity, kindness, fidelity, modesty, patience.
GAL|5|23||Against these there standeth no law.
GAL|5|24||And they who are of the Messiah, have crucified their flesh, with all its passions and its cravings.
GAL|5|25||Let us therefore live in the Spirit; and let us press on after the Spirit.
GAL|5|26||And let us not be vain-glorious, despising one another, and envying one another.
GAL|6|1||My brethren, if one of you should be overtaken in a fault, do ye who are of the Spirit recover him, in a spirit of meekness: and be ye cautious, lest ye also be tempted.
GAL|6|2||And bear ye one another's burdens, that so ye may fulfill the law of the Messiah.
GAL|6|3||For if any one thinketh himself to be something, when he is not, he deceiveth himself.
GAL|6|4||But let a man examine his own conduct; and then his glorying will be within himself, and not in others.
GAL|6|5||For every man must take up his own load.
GAL|6|6||And let him that heareth the word, communicate to him who instructeth him, in all good things.
GAL|6|7||Do not mistake; God is not deceived; for what a man soweth, that also will he reap.
GAL|6|8||He who soweth in the flesh, reapeth from the flesh corruption: and he who soweth in the Spirit, will from the Spirit reap life everlasting.
GAL|6|9||And while we do what is good, let it not be wearisome to us; for the time will come when we shall reap, and it will not be tedious to us.
GAL|6|10||Now, therefore, while we have the opportunity, let us practice good works towards all men, and especially towards them of the household of faith.
GAL|6|11||Behold, this epistle have I written to you with my own hand.
GAL|6|12||They who are disposed to glory in the flesh, they urge you to become circumcised, only that they may not be persecuted on account of the cross of the Messiah.
GAL|6|13||For not even they themselves, who are circumcised, keep the law: but they wish you to become circumcised, that they may glory in your flesh.
GAL|6|14||But as for me, let me not glory, except in the cross of our Lord Jesus the Messiah; by whom the world is crucified to me, and I am crucified to the world.
GAL|6|15||For circumcision is nothing; neither is uncircumcision; but a new creation.
GAL|6|16||And they who press forward in this path, peace be on them, and mercy; and on the Israel of God.
GAL|6|17||Henceforth let no one put trouble upon me; for I bear in my body the marks of our Lord Jesus the Messiah.
GAL|6|18||My brethren, the grace of our Lord Jesus the Messiah, be with your spirit. Amen.
EPH|1|1||Paul, a legate of Jesus the Messiah by the pleasure of God, to them who are at Ephesus, sanctified, and believing in Jesus the Messiah:
EPH|1|2||Peace be with you, and grace from God our Father, and from our Lord Jesus the Messiah.
EPH|1|3||Blessed be God, the Father of our Lord Jesus the Messiah, who hath blessed us with all blessings of the Spirit in heaven, by the Messiah:
EPH|1|4||according as he had previously chosen us in him, before the foundation of the world, that we might be holy and without blame before him; and, in love, predestinated us for himself;
EPH|1|5||and adopted us for sons, in Jesus the Messiah, as was agreeable to his pleasure:
EPH|1|6||that the glory of his grace might be glorified, which he poured upon us by his Beloved One;
EPH|1|7||by whom we have redemption, and the forgiveness of sins by his blood, according to the riches of his grace,
EPH|1|8||which hath abounded in us, in all wisdom and all spiritual understanding.
EPH|1|9||And he hath made us know the mystery of his pleasure, which he had before determined in himself to accomplish,
EPH|1|10||in the dispensation of the fullness of times; that all things might again be made new in the Messiah, things in heaven and [things] on earth.
EPH|1|11||And in him we are elected, according as he predestined us and willed, who worketh all things according to the counsel of his pleasure;
EPH|1|12||that we should be they who first hoped in the Messiah, to the honor of his glory.
EPH|1|13||In whom, ye also have heard the word of truth, which is the gospel of your life, and have believed in him; and have been sealed with the Holy Spirit, who was promised,
EPH|1|14||who is the earnest of our inheritance, until the redemption of them that are alive, and for the praise of his glory.
EPH|1|15||Therefore, lo I also, since I heard of your faith in our Lord Jesus the Messiah, and of your love towards all the saints,
EPH|1|16||cease not to give thanks on your account, and to remember you in my prayers;
EPH|1|17||that the God of our Lord Jesus the Messiah, the Father of glory, may give to you the Spirit of wisdom and of revelation, in the recognition of him;
EPH|1|18||and that the eyes of your hearts may be enlightened, so that ye may know what is the hope of his calling, and what the riches of the glory of his inheritance in the saints;
EPH|1|19||and what is the excellence of the majesty of his power in us who believe; according to the efficiency of the strength of his power,
EPH|1|20||which he put forth in the Messiah, and raised him from the dead, and seated him at his right hand in heaven,
EPH|1|21||high above all principalities, and authorities, and powers, and lordships, and above every name that is named, not only in this world but also in that to come:
EPH|1|22||and he hath subjected all things under his feet; and hath given him who is high over all, to be the head of the church;
EPH|1|23||which is his body, and the fullness of him who filleth all in all:
EPH|2|1||and also you, [he filleth,] who were dead in your sins, and in your offences,
EPH|2|2||in the which ye before walked, according to the worldliness of this world, and according to the pleasure of the prince potentate of the air, that spirit which is active in the children of disobedience:
EPH|2|3||in which deeds we also, formerly, were conversant, in the cravings of our flesh; and we did the pleasure of our flesh, and of our mind, and were altogether the children of wrath, like the rest.
EPH|2|4||But God who is rich in his mercies, because of the great love with which he loved us,
EPH|2|5||when we were dead in our sins, quickened us with the Messiah, and rescued us by his grace;
EPH|2|6||and resuscitated us with him, and seated us with him in heaven, in Jesus the Messiah:
EPH|2|7||that he might show to the coming ages the magnitude of the riches of his grace, and his benignity towards us in Jesus the Messiah.
EPH|2|8||For it is by his grace we are rescued, through faith; and this is not of yourselves, but it is the gift of God:
EPH|2|9||not of works, lest any one glory.
EPH|2|10||For we are his creation; who are created in Jesus the Messiah, for good works, which God hath before prepared for us to walk in.
EPH|2|11||Wherefore be mindful, that ye formerly were carnal Gentiles; and ye were called the uncircumcision, by that which is called the circumcision, and which is the work of the hands in the flesh.
EPH|2|12||And ye were, at that time, without the Messiah; and were aliens from the regulations of Israel; and strangers to the covenant of the promise; and were without hope, and without God, in the world.
EPH|2|13||But now, by Jesus the Messiah, ye who before were afar off, have been brought near by the blood of the Messiah.
EPH|2|14||For he is himself our peace, who hath made the two [become] one, and hath demolished the wall which stood in the midst, and the enmity, by his flesh;
EPH|2|15||and by his prescriptions he hath abolished the law of ordinances; that, in himself, he might make the two to be one new man; and he hath made peace,
EPH|2|16||and hath reconciled both with God, in one body, and hath slain the enmity by his cross.
EPH|2|17||And he came, and proclaimed peace to you afar off, and to those near:
EPH|2|18||because, by him there is access for us both, by one Spirit, unto the Father.
EPH|2|19||Wherefore, ye are not strangers, nor sojourners, but ye are fellow-citizens with the saints, and of the household of God.
EPH|2|20||And ye are built upon the foundations of the legates and the prophets; and Jesus the Messiah hath become the head of the corner in the edifice.
EPH|2|21||And in him all the edifice is framed together, and groweth into a holy temple in the Lord;
EPH|2|22||while ye also are builded in him, for a habitation of God through the Spirit.
EPH|3|1||On this account, I Paul am a prisoner of Jesus the Messiah, for the sake of you Gentiles:
EPH|3|2||if so be, ye have heard of the dispensation of the grace of God, which was given to me among you:
EPH|3|3||that by revelation there was made known to me the mystery, (as I have [now] written to you in brief,
EPH|3|4||so that while ye read, ye might be able to understand my knowledge of the mystery of the Messiah,)
EPH|3|5||which in other generations was not made known to the sons of men, as it is now revealed to his holy legates and to his prophets, by the Spirit;
EPH|3|6||that the Gentiles should be sharers. of his inheritance, and partakers of his body, and of the promise which is given in him by the gospel;
EPH|3|7||of which I have been a minister, according to the gift of the goodness of God, which was imparted to me by the operation of his power:
EPH|3|8||to me, who am the least of all the saints, hath this grace been given, that I should announce among the Gentiles the unsearchable riches of the Messiah,
EPH|3|9||and should show to all men what is the dispensation of the mystery, which for ages was hid up in God the Creator of all [things]:
EPH|3|10||so that, by means of the church, the manifold wisdom of God might become known to the principalities and powers that are in heaven:
EPH|3|11||which [wisdom] he arranged ages before, and he hath executed it by Jesus the Messiah our Lord;
EPH|3|12||through whom we have boldness and access, in the confidence of his faith.
EPH|3|13||Therefore I pray, that I may not be discouraged by my afflictions, which are for your sakes; for this is your glory.
EPH|3|14||And I bow my knees to the Father of our Lord Jesus the Messiah,
EPH|3|15||from whom the whole family in heaven and on earth is named;
EPH|3|16||that he would grant you, according to the riches of his glory, to be strengthened with might by his Spirit; that in your inner man
EPH|3|17||the Messiah may dwell by faith, and in your hearts by love, while your root and your foundation waxeth strong;
EPH|3|18||and that ye may be able to explore, with all the saints, what is the height and depth, and length and breadth,
EPH|3|19||and may know the greatness of the Messiah's love; and [that] ye may be filled with all the fullness of God.
EPH|3|20||Now to him who is able, by his almighty power, to do for us even more than we ask or think, according to his power that worketh in us;
EPH|3|21||to him be glory, in his church, by Jesus the Messiah, in all generations, for ever and ever. Amen.
EPH|4|1||I therefore, a prisoner in our Lord, beseech of you, that ye walk, (as it becometh the calling wherewith ye are called,)
EPH|4|2||with all lowliness of mind, and quietness, and long suffering; and that ye be forbearing one towards another, in love.
EPH|4|3||And be ye solicitous to keep the unity of the Spirit, in a bond of peace;
EPH|4|4||so that ye may become one body, and one Spirit; even as ye are called unto one hope of your calling.
EPH|4|5||For, the Lord is one, and the faith one, and the baptism one;
EPH|4|6||and one God is the Father of all, and over all, and by all, and in us all.
EPH|4|7||And to each of us grace is given, according to the measure of the gift of the Messiah.
EPH|4|8||Wherefore it is said: He ascended on high, and carried captivity captive, and gave gifts to men.
EPH|4|9||Now that he ascended, what is it but that he also previously descended to the interior [regions] of the earth?
EPH|4|10||He who descended, is also the same that ascended up, high above all the heavens, that he might fulfill all things.
EPH|4|11||And he gave some, legates; and some, prophets; and some, evangelists; and some, pastors and teachers:
EPH|4|12||for perfecting the saints, for the work of the ministry, for the edification of the body of the Messiah;
EPH|4|13||until we all become one and the same, in faith and in the knowledge of the Son of God, and one complete man according to the measure of the stature of the fullness of Messiah:
EPH|4|14||and that we might not be children, agitated and turned about by every wind of the crafty doctrines of men who plot to seduce by their subtilty:
EPH|4|15||but that we might be established in our love; and that every thing in us might progress in the Messiah, who is the head:
EPH|4|16||and from him [it is], the whole body is framed together and compacted by all the junctures, according to the gift that is imparted by measure to each member, for the growth of the body; that his edifice may be perfected in love.
EPH|4|17||And this I say, and testify in the Lord, that henceforth ye walk not as the other Gentiles, who walk in the vanity of their mind:
EPH|4|18||and they are dark in their understandings, and are alienated from the life of God, because there is not in them knowledge, and because of the blindness of their heart.
EPH|4|19||They have cut off their hope, and have given themselves over to lasciviousness, and to the practice of all uncleanness in their greediness.
EPH|4|20||But ye have not so learned the Messiah;
EPH|4|21||if ye have truly heard him, and by him have learned as the truth is in Jesus.
EPH|4|22||But [ye have learned], that ye should lay aside your former practices, the old man that is corrupted with the lusts of error;
EPH|4|23||and should be renewed in the spirit of your minds;
EPH|4|24||and should put on the new man, that is created by God in righteousness and in the holiness of truth.
EPH|4|25||Wherefore, put away from you lying, and speak ye the truth each with his neighbor; for we are members one of another.
EPH|4|26||Be ye angry, and sin not: and let not the sun go down upon your wrath.
EPH|4|27||And give no place to the Accuser.
EPH|4|28||And let him that stole, steal no more; but let him labor with his hands, and do good acts; that he may have to give to him who needeth.
EPH|4|29||Let no hateful language come from your mouth, but that which is decorous, and useful for edification, that it may convey grace to those who hear.
EPH|4|30||And grieve not the Holy Spirit of God, whereby ye are sealed for the day of redemption.
EPH|4|31||Let all bitterness, and anger, and wrath, and clamoring, and reviling, be taken from you, with all malice:
EPH|4|32||and be ye affectionate towards one another, and sympathetic; and forgive ye one another, as God by the Messiah hath forgiven us.
EPH|5|1||Be ye therefore imitators of God, as dear children:
EPH|5|2||and walk in love; as the Messiah also hath loved us, and hath given up himself for us, an offering and a sacrifice to God, for a sweet odor.
EPH|5|3||But whoredom, and all impurity, and avarice let them not be at all heard of among you, as it becometh the saints;
EPH|5|4||Neither obscenities, nor words of folly, or of division, or of scurrility, which are not useful; but instead of these, thanksgiving.
EPH|5|5||For this know ye, that every man who is a whoremonger, or impure, or avaricious, or a worshipper of idols, hath no inheritance in the kingdom of the Messiah and of God.
EPH|5|6||Let no man deceive you with vain words; for it is on account of these things that the wrath of God cometh on the children of disobedience.
EPH|5|7||Therefore be ye not like them.
EPH|5|8||For ye were heretofore darkness, but now are ye light in our Lord: therefore, as the children of light, so walk ye.
EPH|5|9||For the fruits of the light are in all goodness, and righteousness, and truth.
EPH|5|10||And search out what is pleasing before our Lord:
EPH|5|11||And have no commerce with the works of darkness which are unfruitful, but reprove them.
EPH|5|12||For the things they do in secret, it is nauseous even to mention.
EPH|5|13||For all things are exposed and made manifest by the light: and whatever maketh manifest, is light.
EPH|5|14||Wherefore it is said: Awake thou that sleepest, and arise from the dead, and the Messiah will illuminate thee.
EPH|5|15||See therefore, that ye walk circumspectly; not like the simple,
EPH|5|16||but like the wise, who purchase their opportunity; because the days are evil.
EPH|5|17||Therefore, be not lacking in understanding; but understand ye what is the pleasure of God.
EPH|5|18||And be not drunk with wine, in which is dissoluteness; but be ye filled with the spirit.
EPH|5|19||And converse with yourselves in psalms and hymns; and with your hearts sing to the Lord, in spiritual songs.
EPH|5|20||And give thanks to God the Father, at all times, for all men, in the name of our Lord Jesus the Messiah.
EPH|5|21||And be submissive one to another, in the love of the Messiah.
EPH|5|22||Wives, be ye submissive to your husbands, as to our Lord.
EPH|5|23||Because the husband is the head of the wife, even as the Messiah is the head of the church; and he is the vivifier of the body.
EPH|5|24||And as the church is subject to the Messiah, so also let wives be to their husbands in all things.
EPH|5|25||Husbands, love your wives, even as the Messiah loved his church, and delivered himself up for it;
EPH|5|26||that he might sanctify it, and cleanse it, by the washing of water, and by the word;
EPH|5|27||and might constitute it a glorious church for himself, in which is no stain, and no wrinkle, and nothing like them; but that it might be holy and without blemish.
EPH|5|28||It behooveth men so to love their wives, as [they do] their own bodies. For he that loveth his wife loveth himself.
EPH|5|29||For no one ever hated his own body; but nourisheth it, and provideth for it, even as the Messiah the church.
EPH|5|30||For we are members of his body and of his flesh, and of his bones.
EPH|5|31||For this reason, a man should quit his father and his mother, and adhere to his wife; and the two should be one flesh.
EPH|5|32||This is a great mystery; but I am speaking of the Messiah, and of his church.
EPH|5|33||Nevertheless, let each of you severally so love his wife, even as himself: and let the wife reverence her husband.
EPH|6|1||Children, obey your parents in our Lord; for this is right.
EPH|6|2||And the first commandment with promise, is this: Honor thy father and thy mother;
EPH|6|3||that it may be well with thee, and that thy life may be prolonged on the earth.
EPH|6|4||And parents, anger not your children; but train them up in the discipline and doctrine of our Lord.
EPH|6|5||Servants, be obedient to your masters after the flesh, with fear, and with trepidation, and with simplicity of heart, as unto the Messiah.
EPH|6|6||Not in the sight of the eye, as if ye were pleasing men; but as the servants of the Messiah, who are doing the will of God.
EPH|6|7||And serve them with your whole heart, in love, as if serving our Lord and not men;
EPH|6|8||knowing that whatever good thing a man may do, the same will be recompensed to him by our Lord, whether he be a servant or a free man.
EPH|6|9||Also ye masters, do ye so to your servants. Forgive them a fault; because ye know, that ye have a master in heaven; and there is no respect of persons with him.
EPH|6|10||Finally, my brethren, be strong in our Lord, and; in the energy of his power:
EPH|6|11||And put ye on; the whole armor of God, so that ye may be able to stand against the wiles of the Accuser.
EPH|6|12||For our conflict is not with flesh and blood, but with principalities, and with those in authority, and with the possessors of this dark world, and with the evil spirits that are beneath heaven.
EPH|6|13||Therefore put ye on the whole armor of God, that ye may be able to meet the evil [one]; and, being in all respects prepared, may stand firm.
EPH|6|14||Stand up therefore, and gird your loins with truth; and put on the breastplate of righteousness;
EPH|6|15||and defend your feet with the preparation of the gospel of peace.
EPH|6|16||And herewith take to you the confidence of faith, by which ye will have power to quench all the fiery darts of the evil [one].
EPH|6|17||And put on the helmet of rescue; and take hold of the sword of the Spirit, which is the word of God.
EPH|6|18||And pray ye, with all prayers and supplications, in spirit, at all times: and in prayer be watchful, at all seasons, praying constantly, and interceding for all the saints:
EPH|6|19||and also for me; that language may be given me, in the opening of my mouth; so that I may boldly proclaim the mystery of the gospel,
EPH|6|20||of which I am a messenger in chains; that I may utter it boldly, as I ought to utter it.
EPH|6|21||And that ye also may know my affairs, and what I am doing, lo, Tychicus, a beloved brother, and a faithful minister in our Lord, will acquaint you;
EPH|6|22||whom I have sent to you for this purpose, that ye might know what is [going on] with me, and that your hearts may be comforted.
EPH|6|23||Peace be with the brethren, and love with faith, from God the Father, and from our Lord Jesus the Messiah.
EPH|6|24||Grace be with all them who love our Lord Jesus the Messiah without corruptness. Amen.
PHL|1|1||Paul and Timothy, servants of Jesus the Messiah, to all the saints that are in Jesus the Messiah at Philippi, with the elders and deacons.
PHL|1|2||Grace be with you, and peace from God our Father, and from our Lord Jesus the Messiah.
PHL|1|3||I thank my God at the constant recollection of you,
PHL|1|4||in all my prayers respecting you; and while I rejoice, I adore;
PHL|1|5||on account of your fellowship in the gospel, from the first day until now.
PHL|1|6||Because I am confident of this, that he who hath begun the good works in you, will accomplish them until the day of our Lord Jesus the Messiah.
PHL|1|7||For thus it is right for me to think of you all, because ye are permanently in my heart, and because, both in my bonds and in the vindication of the truth of the gospel, ye are my associates in grace.
PHL|1|8||For God is my witness, how I love you in the bowels of Jesus the Messiah.
PHL|1|9||And this I pray for, that your love may still increase and abound, in knowledge, and In all spiritual understanding:
PHL|1|10||so that ye may discern the things that are suitable; and may be pure and without offence, in the day of the Messiah,
PHL|1|11||and be full of the fruits of righteousness which are by Jesus the Messiah, to the praise and glory of God.
PHL|1|12||And I would that ye might know, my brethren, that the transaction in regard to me, hath eventuated rather for the furtherance of the gospel;
PHL|1|13||so that my bonds, on account of the Messiah, are matter of notoriety in all the court, and to all others.
PHL|1|14||And many of the brethren in our Lord have become confident, on account of my bonds, and are more bold to speak the word of God without fear.
PHL|1|15||And they herald [it], some from envy and contention; but others with good will, and with love for the Messiah;
PHL|1|16||because they know that I am appointed for the vindication of the gospel.
PHL|1|17||And they who herald the Messiah in contention, do it not sincerely; but they hope to add pressure to my bonds.
PHL|1|18||And in this I have rejoiced, and do rejoice, that in every form, whether in pretence or in truth, the Messiah is heralded.
PHL|1|19||For I know, that these things will be found [conducive] to my life, through your prayers and the gift of the Spirit of Jesus the Messiah.
PHL|1|20||So that I hope and expect, that I shall in nothing be put to shame; but with uncovered face, as at all times, so now, the Messiah will be magnified in my body, whether by life or by death.
PHL|1|21||For my life is, the Messiah; and if I die, it is gain to me.
PHL|1|22||But if I have fruits of my labors in this life of the flesh, I know not what I shall choose.
PHL|1|23||For the two press upon me: I desire to be liberated, that I may be with the Messiah; and this would be very advantageous to me.
PHL|1|24||But also the business in regard to you, urges upon me to remain in the body.
PHL|1|25||And this I confidently know, that I shall continue and remain, for your joy, and for the furtherance of your faith;
PHL|1|26||so that when I come again to you, your glorying, which is in Jesus the Messiah only, will abound through me.
PHL|1|27||Let your conduct be as becometh the gospel of the Messiah; so that if I come I may see you, and if absent I may hear of you, that ye stand fast in one spirit and in one soul, and that ye strive together in the faith of the gospel.
PHL|1|28||And in nothing be ye startled, by those who rise up against us; [which is] an indication of their destruction, and of life for you.
PHL|1|29||And this is given to you by God, that ye not only really believe in the Messiah, but also that ye suffer on his account;
PHL|1|30||and that ye endure conflict, as ye have seen in me, and now hear concerning me.
PHL|2|1||If, therefore, ye have consolation in the Messiah, or if a commingling of hearts in love, or if a fellowship of the Spirit, or if compassions and sympathies;
PHL|2|2||complete ye my joy, by having one apprehension, and one love, and one soul, and one mind.
PHL|2|3||And do nothing in strife, or in vain glory; but, with lowliness of mind, let each esteem his neighbor as better than himself.
PHL|2|4||And let not each be solicitous [only] for himself, but every one also for his neighbor.
PHL|2|5||And think ye so in yourselves, as Jesus the Messiah also thought;
PHL|2|6||who, as he was in the likeness of God, deemed it no trespass to be the coequal of God;
PHL|2|7||yet divested himself, and assumed the likeness of a servant, and was in the likeness of men, and was found in fashion as a man;
PHL|2|8||and he humbled himself, and became obedient unto death, even the death of the cross.
PHL|2|9||Wherefore, also, God hath highly exalted him, and given him a name which is more excellent than all names;
PHL|2|10||that at the name of Jesus every knee should bow, of [beings] in heaven, and on earth, and under the earth;
PHL|2|11||and that every tongue should confess that Jesus the Messiah is the Lord, to the glory of God his Father.
PHL|2|12||Therefore, my beloved, as ye have at all times obeyed, not only when I was near to you, but now when I am far from you, prosecute the work of your life, more abundantly, with fear and with trembling.
PHL|2|13||For God is operating in you, both to purpose, and also to perform that which ye desire.
PHL|2|14||Do all things without murmuring, and without altercation;
PHL|2|15||that ye may be perfect and without blemish, as the sincere children of God, who are resident in a perverse and crooked generation; and that ye may appear among them as luminaries in the world;
PHL|2|16||so that ye may be to them in place of life; for my glory in the day of the Messiah, that I may not have run in vain or toiled for naught.
PHL|2|17||And if I should be made a libation upon the sacrifice and service of your faith, I rejoice and exult with you all.
PHL|2|18||And so also do ye rejoice and exult with me.
PHL|2|19||But I hope in our Lord Jesus, that I shall shortly send Timothy unto you, so that I also may have composure, when informed concerning you.
PHL|2|20||For I have no other one here, who, like my self, will sincerely care for your welfare.
PHL|2|21||For they all seek their own, not the [things] of Jesus the Messiah.
PHL|2|22||But ye know the proof of him, that as a son with his father, so he labored with me in the gospel.
PHL|2|23||Him I hope shortly to send to you, when I shall have seen how [things result] with me.
PHL|2|24||And I trust in my Lord, that I shall shortly come myself to you.
PHL|2|25||But now, a circumstance urged me to send to you Epaphroditus, the brother who is an assistant and laborer with me, but is your legate and minister to my wants.
PHL|2|26||For he longed to see you all, and was anxious, because he knew ye had heard, that he was sick.
PHL|2|27||And indeed he was sick, nigh unto death: but God had mercy on him: nor was it on him only, but also on me, that I might not have trouble upon trouble.
PHL|2|28||Promptly, therefore, have I sent him to you; so that when ye see him, ye may again be joyful, and I may have a little breathing.
PHL|2|29||Receive him then in the Lord, with all joy; and hold in honor those who are such.
PHL|2|30||For, because of the Messiah's work, he came near to death, and little regarded his life, that he might fulfill what you lacked in the ministration to me.
PHL|3|1||Finally, my brethren, rejoice in our Lord. To write these [things] again and again to you, is not irksome to me, because they make you cautious.
PHL|3|2||Beware of dogs; beware of evil doers; beware of the clipped in flesh.
PHL|3|3||For we are the [real] circumcision, who worship God in spirit, and glory in Jesus the Messiah, and place no reliance on the flesh.
PHL|3|4||And yet I might place reliance on the flesh. For, if any one thinketh that his reliance should be on the flesh, I might [do so] more than he.
PHL|3|5||Circumcised when eight days old; of the stock of Israel; of the tribe of Benjamin; a Hebrew, descendant of Hebrews; as to the law, a Pharisee;
PHL|3|6||as to zeal, a persecutor of the church; and as to the righteousness of the law, I was without fault.
PHL|3|7||But these things, which had been my excellence, I have accounted a detriment, because of the Messiah.
PHL|3|8||And now also I account them all a detriment, because of the excellency of the knowledge of Jesus the Messiah my Lord; for the sake of whom, I have parted with all things, and have accounted [them] as dung, that I might gain the Messiah,
PHL|3|9||and be found in him; since my righteousness is not [now] that from the law, but that which is from faith in the Messiah, that is, the righteousness which is from God;
PHL|3|10||that thereby I might know Jesus, and the efficacy of his resurrection; and might participate in his sufferings, and be assimilated to his death:
PHL|3|11||if so be, I may attain to the resurrection from the dead.
PHL|3|12||Not as though I had already taken [the prize], or were already complete; but I run [in the race], if so I may take that, for which Jesus the Messiah took me.
PHL|3|13||My brethren, I do not consider myself, as having taken [it]. But one thing I know, that I forget the things behind me, and reach for the things before me;
PHL|3|14||and I run straight for the goal, that I may obtain the [prize] of victory of the call of God from on high, by Jesus the Messiah.
PHL|3|15||Therefore let those who are perfect, have these views; and if ye differently view any thing, God will reveal that also to you.
PHL|3|16||Nevertheless, that we may attain to this, let us proceed on in one path, and with one consent.
PHL|3|17||Be like me, my brethren; and contemplate them, who walk after the pattern ye have seen in us.
PHL|3|18||For there are many who walk otherwise; of whom I have often told you, and I now tell you, with weeping, that they are adversaries of the cross of the Messiah;
PHL|3|19||whose end is destruction; whose god is their belly, and their glory their shame; whose thoughts are on things of the earth.
PHL|3|20||But our concern is with heaven; and from thence we expect our Vivifier, our Lord, Jesus the Messiah;
PHL|3|21||who will change the body of our abasement, that it may have the likeness of the body of his glory, according to his great power, whereby all things are made subject to him.
PHL|4|1||Wherefore, my beloved and dear brethren, my joy and my crown!---so stand ye fast in our Lord, my beloved!
PHL|4|2||I beseech of Euodias and Syntyche, that they be of one mind in our Lord.
PHL|4|3||I also beseech of thee, my true yokefellow, that thou assist those women who toiled with me in the gospel; together with Clement, and with the rest of my helpers, whose names are written in the book of life.
PHL|4|4||Rejoice ye in our Lord, at all times; and again I say, Rejoice.
PHL|4|5||Let your humility be recognized among all men. Our Lord is near.
PHL|4|6||Be anxious for nothing; but at all times, by prayer and supplication with thanksgiving, make known your requests before God.
PHL|4|7||And the peace of God, which surpasseth all knowledge, will keep your hearts and your minds, through Jesus the Messiah.
PHL|4|8||Finally, my brethren, what things are true, and what things are decorous, and what things are right, and what things are pure, and what things are lovely, and what things are commendable, and deeds of praise and approbation, on these be your thoughts.
PHL|4|9||What things ye have learned, and received, and heard, and seen, in me, these do ye: and the God of peace will be with you.
PHL|4|10||And I rejoice greatly in our Lord, that ye have [again] commenced caring for me; even as ye had before cared [for me,] but ye had not the opportunity.
PHL|4|11||Yet I say this, not because I was in want; for I have learned to make that satisfy me, which I have.
PHL|4|12||I know how to be depressed, and I also know how to abound in every thing; and in all things am I exercised, both in fullness and in famine, in abundance and in penury.
PHL|4|13||I find strength for every thing, in the Messiah who strengtheneth me.
PHL|4|14||Yet ye have done well, in that ye communicated to my necessities.
PHL|4|15||And ye know also, Philippians, that in the beginning of the annunciation, when I left Macedonia, not one of the churches communicated with me in respect to receiving and giving, except ye only;
PHL|4|16||that also at Thessalonica, once and again ye sent me relief.
PHL|4|17||Not that I desire a gift; but I wish fruits may multiply unto you.
PHL|4|18||I have [now] received all, and I abound, and am full: and I accepted all that ye sent to me by Epaphroditus, a sweet odor, and an acceptable sacrifice that pleaseth God.
PHL|4|19||And may God supply all your necessity, according to his riches, in the glory of Jesus the Messiah.
PHL|4|20||And to God our Father, be glory and honor, for ever and ever. Amen.
PHL|4|21||Salute all the saints who are in Jesus the Messiah. The brethren who are with me, salute you.
PHL|4|22||All the saints salute you, especially those of Caesar's household.
PHL|4|23||The grace of our Lord Jesus the Messiah, be with you all. Amen.
COL|1|1||Paul, a legate of Jesus the Messiah by the pleasure of God, and Timothy a brother,
COL|1|2||to them who are at Colosse, the brethren, holy and believing in Jesus the Messiah: peace be with you, and grace from God our Father.
COL|1|3||We give thanks to God, the Father of our Lord Jesus the Messiah, at all times, and pray for you;
COL|1|4||lo, ever since we heard of your faith in Jesus the Messiah, and of your love to all the saints;
COL|1|5||because of the hope that is laid up for you in heaven, of which ye heard before in the word of truth of the gospel;
COL|1|6||which is announced to you, as also to all the world; and which groweth and yieldeth fruits, as it doth also among you from the day ye heard and knew the grace of God in reality:
COL|1|7||as ye learned from Epaphras, our beloved fellow-servant, who is for you a faithful minister of the Messiah;
COL|1|8||and who hath made known to us your love in the Spirit.
COL|1|9||Therefore we also, from the day we heard [of it], have not ceased to pray for you; and to ask that ye may be filled with a knowledge of the good pleasure of God, in all wisdom, and in all spiritual understanding;
COL|1|10||that ye may walk as is right, and may please God with all good works, and may yield fruits, and grow in the knowledge of God;
COL|1|11||and may be strengthened with all strength, according to the greatness of his glory, in all patience and long suffering;
COL|1|12||and may, with joy, give thanks to God the Father, who hath fitted us for a portion of the inheritance of the saints in light;
COL|1|13||and hath rescued us from the dominion of darkness, and transferred us to the kingdom of his beloved Son;
COL|1|14||by whom we have redemption and remission of sins:
COL|1|15||who is the likeness of the invisible God, and the first-born of all creatures:
COL|1|16||and by him was created every thing that is in heaven and on earth, all that is seen and all that is unseen, whether thrones, or dominions, or principalities, or sovereignties; every thing was through him, and was created by him:
COL|1|17||and he was prior to all, and by him every thing exists.
COL|1|18||And he is the head of the body the church; as he is the head and first-born from among the dead, that he might be the first in all things.
COL|1|19||For it pleased [the Father], that in him all fullness should dwell;
COL|1|20||and by him, to reconcile all things to himself; and through him, he hath pacified, with the blood of his cross, both [those] on earth and those in heaven.
COL|1|21||And also to you, who were before alienated and enemies in your minds, because of your evil deeds,
COL|1|22||to you, he hath now given peace, by the body of his flesh, and by his death; that he might establish you in his presence, holy, without blemish, and without offence;
COL|1|23||provided ye continue in your faith, your foundation being firm, and ye be not removed from the hope of the gospel; of which ye have heard, that it is proclaimed in all the creation beneath heaven; of which [gospel] I Paul am a minister.
COL|1|24||And I rejoice in the sufferings which are for your sakes; and, in my flesh, I fill up the deficiency in the afflictions of the Messiah, in behalf of his body, which is the church;
COL|1|25||of which I am a minister, according to the dispensation of God which is given to me among you, that I should fulfill the word of God,
COL|1|26||[namely,] that mystery, which was hidden for ages and generations, but is now revealed to his saints;
COL|1|27||to whom God would make known what is the riches of the glory of this mystery among the Gentiles; which [mystery] is the Messiah; who in you is the hope of our glory;
COL|1|28||whom we proclaim, and teach and make known to every man, in all wisdom; that we may present every man perfect in Jesus the Messiah.
COL|1|29||And for this also, I toil and strive, with the aid of the strength that is imparted to me.
COL|2|1||And I wish you to know, what a struggle I have for you, and for them of Laodicea, and for the others who have not seen my face in the flesh;
COL|2|2||that their hearts may be comforted, and that they, by love, may come to all the riches of assurance, and to the understanding of the knowledge of the mystery of God the Father, and of the Messiah,
COL|2|3||in whom are hid all the treasures of wisdom and of knowledge.
COL|2|4||And this I say, lest any one should mislead you by the persuasiveness of words.
COL|2|5||For though I am separated from you in the flesh, yet I am with you in spirit; and I rejoice at beholding your good order, and the stability of your faith in the Messiah.
COL|2|6||As therefore ye have received Jesus the Messiah our Lord, walk ye in him,
COL|2|7||strengthening your roots and building up yourselves in him, and establishing yourselves in the faith which ye have learned, in which may ye abound in thanksgiving.
COL|2|8||Beware, lest any man make you naked by philosophy, and by vain deception, according to the doctrines of men, according to the rudiments of the world, and not according to the Messiah,
COL|2|9||in whom dwelleth all the fullness of the Divinity corporeally.
COL|2|10||And in him ye are also complete, because he is the head of all principalities and authorities.
COL|2|11||And in him ye have been circumcised with a circumcision without hands, by casting off the flesh of sins, by a circumcision of the Messiah.
COL|2|12||And ye have been buried with him, by baptism; and by it ye have risen with him; while ye believed in the power of God, who raised him from the dead.
COL|2|13||And you, who were dead in your sins, and by the uncircumcision of your flesh, he hath vivified with him; and he hath forgiven us all our sins:
COL|2|14||and, by his mandates, he blotted out the handwriting of our debts, which [handwriting] existed against us, and took [it] from the midst, and affixed [it] to his cross.
COL|2|15||And, by yielding up his body, he showed contempt for principalities and authorities; and put them to shame, openly, in his own person.
COL|2|16||Let no one therefore disquiet you about food and drink, or about the distinctions of festivals, and new moons, and sabbaths;
COL|2|17||which were shadows of the things then future; but the body is the Messiah.
COL|2|18||And let no one wish, by abasing the mind, to bring you under bonds, that ye subject yourselves to the worship of angels; while he is prying into that which he hath not seen, and is vainly inflated in his fleshly mind,
COL|2|19||and holdeth not the head, from which the whole body is framed and constructed, with joints and members, and groweth with the growth [given] of God.
COL|2|20||For if ye are dead with the Messiah from the rudiments of the world, why are ye judged as if ye were living in the world?
COL|2|21||But, touch thou not, and taste thou not, and handle thou not:
COL|2|22||for these things perish in the using; and they are the commandments and doctrines of men.
COL|2|23||And they seem to have a kind of wisdom, in a show of humility, and of the fear of God, and of not sparing the body; not in any thing of excellence, but in things subservient to the body.
COL|3|1||If then ye have risen with the Messiah, seek the things on high, where the Messiah sitteth on the right hand of God.
COL|3|2||Think of things on high; not of the things on earth:
COL|3|3||for ye are dead; and your life is hidden with the Messiah, in God.
COL|3|4||And when the Messiah, who is our life, shall be manifested, then shall ye also be manifested with him in glory.
COL|3|5||Mortify therefore your members that are on the earth; whoredom, impurity, and the passions, and evil concupiscence, and avarice which is idolatry.
COL|3|6||For on account of these [things], the wrath of God cometh on the children of disobedience.
COL|3|7||And in these [things] ye also formerly walked, when ye lived in them.
COL|3|8||But now, put away from you all these, wrath, anger, malice, reviling, filthy talking:
COL|3|9||and lie not one to another; but put off the old man, with all his practices;
COL|3|10||and put ye on the new [man], that is renewed in knowledge, after the likeness of his Creator;
COL|3|11||where there is neither Jew nor Gentile, neither circumcision nor uncircumcision, neither Greek nor barbarian, neither bond nor free; but the Messiah is all, and in all.
COL|3|12||Therefore, holy and beloved, as the elect of God, put ye on compassions, and tenderness, and suavity, and humbleness of mind, and gentleness, and long suffering.
COL|3|13||And be ye indulgent towards one another, and forgiving to one another: and if any one has a complaint against his neighbor, as the Messiah forgave you, so also do ye forgive.
COL|3|14||And with all these, [join] love, which is the girdle of perfection.
COL|3|15||And let the peace of the Messiah direct your hearts; for to that ye have been called, in one body; and be ye thankful to the Messiah.
COL|3|16||And let his word dwell in you richly, in all wisdom. And teach and admonish yourselves, by psalms and hymns and spiritual songs, and with grace in your hearts sing ye unto God.
COL|3|17||And whatever ye do in word or act, do it in the name of our Lord Jesus the Messiah, and give thanksgiving through him to God the Father.
COL|3|18||Wives, be ye subject to your husbands, as is right in the Messiah.
COL|3|19||Husbands, love ye your wives, and be not bitter towards them.
COL|3|20||Children, obey your parents in every thing; for this is pleasing before our Lord.
COL|3|21||Parents, anger not your children, lest they be discouraged.
COL|3|22||Servants, obey in all things your bodily masters; not in the sight of the eye only, as those who please men, but with a simple heart, and in the fear of the Lord.
COL|3|23||And whatever ye do, do it with your whole soul, as unto our Lord, and not as to men:
COL|3|24||and know ye, that from our Lord ye will receive a recompense as the inheritance; for ye serve the Lord the Messiah.
COL|3|25||But the delinquent will receive a recompense, according to the delinquency; and there is no respect of persons.
COL|4|1||Masters, do equity and justice to your servants; and be conscious that ye also have a master in heaven.
COL|4|2||Persevere in prayer; and be watchful in it, and in giving thanks.
COL|4|3||And pray also for us, that God would open to us a door of speech, for uttering the mystery of the Messiah, for the sake of which I am in bonds;
COL|4|4||that I may unfold it, and utter it, as it behooveth me.
COL|4|5||Walk in wisdom towards them without: and redeem your opportunity.
COL|4|6||And let your speech at all times be with grace; as it were, seasoned with salt: and know ye, how ye ought to give answer to every man.
COL|4|7||And what is [occurrent] with me, will Tychicus make known to you; who is a beloved brother, and a faithful minister, and our fellow-servant in the Lord:
COL|4|8||whom I have sent to you for this purpose, that he might know your affairs, and might comfort your hearts;
COL|4|9||together with Onesimus, a faithful and beloved brother, who is from among you. These will make known to you what is [occurrent] with us.
COL|4|10||Aristarchus, my fellow-captive, saluteth you; also Marcus, an uncle's son to Barnabas, of whom ye have received directions, that if he come to you, ye may kindly receive him:
COL|4|11||also Jesus, who is called Justus. These are of the circumcision, and they only have aided me in the kingdom of God; and they have been a comfort to me.
COL|4|12||Epaphras saluteth you, who is from among you, a servant of the Messiah, always laboring for you in prayer, that ye may stand perfect and complete in all the good pleasure of God.
COL|4|13||For I testify for him, that he hath great zeal for you, and for them of Laodicea, and for them of Hierapolis.
COL|4|14||Luke the physician, our beloved, saluteth you; also Demas.
COL|4|15||Salute ye the brethren in Laodicea, and Nymphas, and the church in his house.
COL|4|16||And when this epistle shall have been read among you, cause it to be read also in the church of the Laodiceans; and that which is written from Laodicea, do ye read.
COL|4|17||And say to Archippus: Be attentive to the ministry which thou hast received in our Lord, that thou fulfill it.
COL|4|18||This salutation is by the hand of me Paul. Remember my bonds. Grace be with you. Amen.
1TS|1|1||I Paul and Sylvanus and Timothy, to the church of the Thessalonians, which is in God the Father and in our Lord Jesus the Messiah: Grace be with you, and peace.
1TS|1|2||We give thanks to God at all times, on account of you all, and remember you continually in our prayers:
1TS|1|3||and we call to mind before God the Father the works of your faith, and the toil of your love, and the patience of your hope in our Lord Jesus the Messiah.
1TS|1|4||For we know your election, my brethren, beloved of God.
1TS|1|5||For our preaching among you, was not in words only; but also in power, and in the Holy Spirit, and in genuine persuasion. Ye also know, how we were among you for your sakes.
1TS|1|6||And ye became imitators of us, and of our Lord, in that ye received the word in great affliction, and with the joy of the Holy Spirit.
1TS|1|7||And ye were a pattern for all the believers who are in Macedonia and in Achaia.
1TS|1|8||For from you the word of our Lord sounded forth; [and] not only in Macedonia and Achaia, but in every place, your faith in God is heard of; so that we have no need to say any thing concerning you.
1TS|1|9||For they declare, what an ingress we had to you, and how ye turned from the worship of idols unto God, that ye might worship the living and true God;
1TS|1|10||while ye wait for his Son from heaven, that Jesus whom he raised from the dead, who delivereth us from the wrath to come.
1TS|2|1||And ye yourselves, my brethren, know our entrance among you, that it was not in vain:
1TS|2|2||but we first suffered and were treated with indignity, as ye know, at Philippi; and then, in a great agony, with confidence in our God, we addressed to you the gospel of the Messiah.
1TS|2|3||For our exhortation proceeded not from deceit, nor from impurity, nor in guile:
1TS|2|4||but as we had been approved of God to be intrusted with the gospel, so we speak, not as pleasing men, but God who searcheth our hearts.
1TS|2|5||For at no time have we used flattering speech; as ye know; nor a cloak of cupidity, God is witness.
1TS|2|6||Neither have we sought glory from men, either from you or from others, when we might have been chargeable as legates of the Messiah.
1TS|2|7||But we were lowly among you; and like a nurse, who fondleth her children,
1TS|2|8||so we also fondled [you], and were desirous to impart to you, not the gospel of God merely, but also our own soul, because ye were dear to us.
1TS|2|9||For ye recollect, brethren, that we labored and toiled, working with our own hands, by night and by day, that we might not be chargeable to any one of you.
1TS|2|10||Ye are witnesses, and God [also], how we preached to you the gospel of God, purely, and uprightly, and were blameless towards all them that believe:
1TS|2|11||as yourselves know, we entreated each one of you, as a father his children, and comforted your hearts:
1TS|2|12||and we charged you, to walk as it becometh God, who hath called you to his kingdom and his glory.
1TS|2|13||Therefore also we give thanks unceasingly to God, that the word of God which ye received from us, ye did not receive as the word of men, but as being truly the word of God, which worketh efficiently in you and in them that believe.
1TS|2|14||For ye, my brethren, became assimilated to the churches of God in Judaea, the persons who are in Jesus the Messiah; in that ye so suffered, even ye from your own countrymen, as also they from the Jews,
1TS|2|15||the persons who slew our Lord Jesus the Messiah, and persecuted their own prophets and us; and they please not God, and are made hostile to all men;
1TS|2|16||and they forbid us to speak to the Gentiles, that they may have life; to fill up their sins at all times. And wrath cometh on them to the uttermost.
1TS|2|17||But we, my brethren, have been bereaved of you for a short time, (in visible presence, not in our hearts,) and have the more exerted ourselves, to behold your faces, with great affection.
1TS|2|18||And we purposed to come to you, I Paul, once and again; but Satan hindered me.
1TS|2|19||For what is our hope, and our joy, and the crown of our glorying; unless it be ye, before our Lord Jesus at his coming?
1TS|2|20||For ye are our glory, and our joy.
1TS|3|1||And, because we could no longer endure it, we were willing to be left alone at Athens,
1TS|3|2||and to send to you Timothy our brother, a servant of God, and our assistant in the announcement of the Messiah; that he might strengthen you, and inquire of you respecting your faith:
1TS|3|3||lest any of you should be disheartened by these afflictions; for ye know, that we are appointed thereto.
1TS|3|4||For also when we were with you, we forewarned you, that we were to be afflicted; as ye know did occur.
1TS|3|5||Therefore also I could not be quiet, until I sent to learn your faith; lest the Tempter should have tempted you, and our labor have been in vain.
1TS|3|6||But now, since Timothy hath come to us from among you, and hath informed us respecting your faith and your love, and that ye have a good remembrance of us at all times, and that ye desire to see us, even as we [to see] you;
1TS|3|7||therefore we are comforted in you, my brethren, amid all our straits and afflictions, on account of your faith.
1TS|3|8||And now, we live, if ye stand fast in our Lord.
1TS|3|9||For what thanks can we render to God in your behalf, for all the joy with which we are joyful on your account;
1TS|3|10||unless it be, that we the more supplicate before God, by night and by day, that we may see your faces, and may perfect what is lacking in your faith?
1TS|3|11||And may God our Father, and our Lord Jesus the Messiah, direct our way unto you;
1TS|3|12||and increase and enlarge your love towards one another, and towards all men, even as we love you;
1TS|3|13||and establish your hearts unblamable in holiness, before God our Father; at the advent of our Lord Jesus the Messiah, with all his saints.
1TS|4|1||Wherefore, my brethren, I entreat you, and beseech you by our Lord Jesus, that, as ye have received from us how ye ought to walk, and to please God, so ye would make progress more and more.
1TS|4|2||For ye know what command we gave you in our Lord Jesus the Messiah.
1TS|4|3||For this is the pleasure of God, your sanctification; and that ye be separated from all whoredom;
1TS|4|4||and that each one of you might know how to possess his vessel, in sanctity and in honor;
1TS|4|5||and not in the concupiscence of lust, like the rest of the Gentiles who know not God:
1TS|4|6||and that ye dare not to transgress and to overreach any one his brother, in this matter; because our Lord is the avenger of all these, as also we have said and testified to you in time past.
1TS|4|7||For God did not call you unto impurity, but to sanctification.
1TS|4|8||He therefore who spurneth, spurneth not man but God, who hath given his Holy Spirit in you.
1TS|4|9||Now concerning love to the brethren, ye need not that I should write to you; for ye yourselves are taught of God to love one another.
1TS|4|10||Ye likewise do so, to all the brethren who are in all Macedonia: but I entreat you, my brethren, to be exuberant:
1TS|4|11||and that ye strive to be quiet, and to attend to your own affairs; and that ye labor with your own hands; as we directed you;
1TS|4|12||and that ye walk becomingly towards those without; and that ye be dependent on no man.
1TS|4|13||And, I wish you to know, my brethren, that ye should not mourn over them who have fallen asleep, like other people who have no hope.
1TS|4|14||For if we believe that Jesus died and rose again, even so them who sleep, will God, by Jesus, bring with him.
1TS|4|15||And this we say to you, by the word of our Lord, that we who may survive and be alive, at the coming of our Lord, shall not precede them who have slept.
1TS|4|16||Because our Lord will himself descend from heaven, with the mandate, and with the voice of the chief angel, and with the trump of God; and the dead who are in the Messiah, will first arise;
1TS|4|17||and then, we who survive and are alive shall be caught up together with them to the clouds, to meet our Lord in the air; and so shall we be ever with our Lord.
1TS|4|18||Wherefore, comfort ye one another with these words.
1TS|5|1||But concerning the times and seasons, my brethren, ye need not that I write to you:
1TS|5|2||for ye know assuredly, that the day of our Lord so cometh, as a thief by night.
1TS|5|3||While they will be saying, Peace and quietness, then suddenly destruction will burst upon them, as distress upon a child-bearer, and they will not escape.
1TS|5|4||But ye, my brethren, are not in darkness, that that day should overtake you as a thief.
1TS|5|5||For ye are all children of the light, and children of the day; and are not children of the night, and children of darkness.
1TS|5|6||Let us not therefore sleep, like others; but let us be vigilant and considerate.
1TS|5|7||For they who sleep, sleep in the night; and they who are drunken, are drunken in the night.
1TS|5|8||But let us who are children of the day, be wakeful in mind, and put on the breastplate of faith and love, and take the helmet of the hope of life.
1TS|5|9||For God hath not appointed us to wrath, but to the acquisition of life, by our Lord Jesus the Messiah:
1TS|5|10||who died for us, that whether we wake or sleep, we might live together with him.
1TS|5|11||Therefore comfort one another, and edify one another, as also ye have done.
1TS|5|12||And we entreat you, my brethren, that ye recognize them who labor among you, and who stand before your faces in our Lord, and instruct you:
1TS|5|13||that they may be esteemed by you with abundant love; and, on account of their work, live ye in harmony with them.
1TS|5|14||And we entreat you, my brethren, that ye admonish the faulty, and encourage the faint-hearted, and bear the burdens of the weak, and be long suffering towards all men.
1TS|5|15||And beware, lest any of you return evil for evil, but always follow good deeds, towards one another, and towards all men.
1TS|5|16||And be joyful always.
1TS|5|17||And pray without ceasing.
1TS|5|18||And in every thing be thankful: For this is the pleasure of God in Jesus the Messiah, concerning you.
1TS|5|19||Quench not the Spirit.
1TS|5|20||Despise not prophesying.
1TS|5|21||Explore every thing, and hold fast the good:
1TS|5|22||and fly from every thing evil.
1TS|5|23||And may the God of peace sanctify you all, perfectly, and keep blameless your whole spirit, and your soul, and your body, till the coming of our Lord Jesus the Messiah.
1TS|5|24||Faithful is he that hath called you, who will do it.
1TS|5|25||My brethren, pray for us.
1TS|5|26||Salute all our brethren with a holy kiss.
1TS|5|27||I conjure you by our Lord, that this epistle be read to all the holy brethren.
1TS|5|28||The grace of our Lord Jesus the Messiah be with you. Amen.
2TS|1|1||PAUL and Sylvanus and Timothy, to the church of the Thessalonians, which is in God our Father and our Lord Jesus the Messiah:
2TS|1|2||Grace be with you, and peace, from God our Father, and from our Lord Jesus the Messiah.
2TS|1|3||We are bound to give thanks to God always, on your account, my brethren, as it is proper; because your faith groweth exceedingly, and, in you all, the love of each for his fellow increaseth.
2TS|1|4||Insomuch that we also boast of you in the churches of God, on account of your faith, and your patience in all the persecution and trials that ye endure;
2TS|1|5||for a demonstration of the righteous judgment of God; that ye may be worthy of his kingdom, on account of which ye suffer.
2TS|1|6||And since it is a righteous thing with God, to recompense trouble to them that trouble you:
2TS|1|7||and you, who are the troubled, he will vivify, with us, at the manifestation of our Lord Jesus the Messiah from heaven, with the host of his angels;
2TS|1|8||when he will execute vengeance, with the burning of fire, on them that know not God, and on them that acknowledge not the gospel of our Lord Jesus the Messiah.
2TS|1|9||For these will be recompensed with the judgment of eternal destruction, from the presence of our Lord, and from the glory of his power;
2TS|1|10||when he shall come to be glorified in his saints, and to display his wonders in his faithful ones; for our testimony concerning you, will be believed, in that day.
2TS|1|11||Therefore we pray for you, at all times; that God would make you worthy of your calling, and would fill you with all readiness for good deeds, and with the works of faith by power;
2TS|1|12||so that the name of our Lord Jesus the Messiah, may be glorified in you, (and) ye also in him; according to the grace of God, and of our Lord Jesus the Messiah.
2TS|2|1||But we entreat of you, my brethren, in regard to the coming of our Lord Jesus the Messiah, and in respect to our being congregated unto him,
2TS|2|2||that ye be not soon agitated in your mind, nor be troubled, neither by word, nor by spirit, nor by letter, as coming from us, that lo, the day of our Lord is at hand.
2TS|2|3||Let no one deceive you in any way; because [that day will not come], unless there previously come a defection, and that man of sin be revealed, the son of perdition;
2TS|2|4||who is an opposer, and exalteth himself above all that is called God and Worshipful; so that he also sitteth in the temple of God, as a God, and displayeth himself, as if he were God.
2TS|2|5||Do ye not remember, that, when I was with you, I told you these things?
2TS|2|6||And now, ye know what hindereth his being manifested in his time.
2TS|2|7||For the mystery of the evil One already beginneth to be operative: and only, if that which now hindereth shall be taken from the midst;
2TS|2|8||then at length will that evil One be revealed; whom our Lord Jesus will consume by the breath of his mouth, and will bring to naught by the visibility of his advent.
2TS|2|9||For the coming of that [evil One], is the working of Satan, with all power, and signs, and lying wonders,
2TS|2|10||and with all the deceptiveness of iniquity, in them that perish; because they did not receive the love of the truth, by which they might have life.
2TS|2|11||Therefore God will send upon them the operation of deception, that they may believe a lie;
2TS|2|12||and that they all may be condemned, who believe not the truth, but have pleasure in iniquity.
2TS|2|13||But we are bound to give thanks to God always, on your account, my brethren beloved of our Lord, that God hath from the beginning chosen you unto life, through sanctification of the Spirit, and through faith in the truth.
2TS|2|14||For unto these it was, that God called you by our preaching; that ye might be the glory to our Lord Jesus the Messiah.
2TS|2|15||Therefore, my brethren, be established, and persevere in the precepts which ye have been taught, whether by word or by our epistle.
2TS|2|16||And may our Lord Jesus the Messiah himself, and God our Father, who hath loved us, and given us everlasting consolation and a good hope through his grace,
2TS|2|17||comfort your hearts, and establish [you] in every good word, and in every good work.
2TS|3|1||Henceforth, brethren, pray ye for us, that the word of our Lord may, in every place, run and be glorified, as with you;
2TS|3|2||and that we may be delivered from evil and perverse men; for faith is not in all.
2TS|3|3||And faithful is the Lord, who will keep you and rescue you from the evil One.
2TS|3|4||And we have confidence in you, through our Lord, that what we have inculcated on you, ye both have done, and will do.
2TS|3|5||And may our Lord direct your hearts to the love of God, and to a patient waiting for the Messiah.
2TS|3|6||And we enjoin upon you, my brethren, in the name of our Lord Jesus the Messiah, that ye withdraw from every brother who walketh wickedly, and not according to the precepts which ye received from us.
2TS|3|7||For ye know how ye ought to imitate us, who did not walk wickedly among you.
2TS|3|8||Neither did we eat bread gratuitously from any of you; but, with toil and weariness, we labored by night and by day, that we might not be burdensome to any of you.
2TS|3|9||It was not because we have no authority, but that we might give you an example in ourselves, that ye might imitate us.
2TS|3|10||And while we were with you, we also gave you this precept, That every one who would not work, should likewise not eat.
2TS|3|11||For we hear, there are some among you who walk wickedly, and do nothing except vain things.
2TS|3|12||Now such persons, we command and exhort, by our Lord Jesus the Messiah, that in quietness they work, and eat their own bread.
2TS|3|13||And my brethren, let it not be wearisome to you, to do what is good.
2TS|3|14||And if any one hearkeneth not to these [my] words in this epistle, separate that man from you, and have no intimacy with him, that he may be ashamed.
2TS|3|15||Yet, hold him not as an enemy, but admonish him as a brother.
2TS|3|16||And may the Lord of peace give you peace, always, in every thing. Our Lord be with you all.
2TS|3|17||The salutation in the writing of my own hand, I Paul have written it; which is the token in all my epistles, so I write.
2TS|3|18||The grace of Jesus the Messiah be with you all, my brethren. Amen.
1TM|1|1||Paul, a legate of Jesus the Messiah, by the command of God our life-giver, and of the Messiah, Jesus our hope;
1TM|1|2||to Timothy, [my] true son in the faith: grace and mercy and peace, from God our Father, and the Messiah, Jesus our Lord.
1TM|1|3||When I was going into Macedonia, I requested thee to remain at Ephesus, and to charge certain persons not to teach different doctrines;
1TM|1|4||and not to throw themselves into fables and stories about genealogies, of which there is no end, which produce contention rather than edification in the faith of God.
1TM|1|5||Now the end of the command is love, which is from a pure heart, and from a good conscience, and from true faith.
1TM|1|6||But from these some have strayed, and have turned aside to vain words;
1TM|1|7||because they wished to be teachers of the law, while they understood not what they speak, nor the thing about which they contend.
1TM|1|8||Now, we know, that the law is a good thing, if a man conduct himself in it, according to the law,
1TM|1|9||he knowing that the law was not established for the righteous, but for the evil, and the rebellious, and the ungodly, and the sinful, and the perverse and for the impure, and for smiters of their fathers and smiters of their mothers, and for murderers,
1TM|1|10||and for whoremongers, and for copulators with males, and for the stealers of free people, and for liars, and for violators of oaths, and for whatever is contrary to sound doctrine,
1TM|1|11||[namely] that of the glorious gospel of the blessed God, with which I am intrusted.
1TM|1|12||And I thank him who strengthened me, [even] our Lord Jesus the Messiah; who accounted me faithful, and appointed me to his ministry;
1TM|1|13||me [I say], who before was a blasphemer, and a persecutor, and a reviler; but I obtained mercy, because I did it while ignorant and without faith.
1TM|1|14||And in me the grace of our Lord abounded, and faith and love, which is in Jesus the Messiah.
1TM|1|15||Faithful is the declaration, and worthy to be received, that Jesus the Messiah came into the world to give life to sinners, of whom I was the primary.
1TM|1|16||But for this cause had he mercy on me, that in me first Jesus the Messiah might display all his long suffering, for an example to them who were to believe on him unto life eternal.
1TM|1|17||And to the king eternal, incorruptible, and invisible, the sole God, be honor and glory for ever and ever! Amen.
1TM|1|18||This injunction I commit to thee, my son Timothy, according to the former predictions concerning thee, that in them thou mightest war this good warfare,
1TM|1|19||in faith and a good conscience; for they who have repudiated this, have become destitute of faith;
1TM|1|20||like Hymeneus and Alexander, whom I have delivered up to Satan, that they may learn not to be blasphemers.
1TM|2|1||I exhort thee, therefore, first of all, that thou present to God supplication, and prayer, and intercession, and thanksgiving, for all men:
1TM|2|2||for kings and magistrates, that we may dwell in a quiet and tranquil habitation, with all reverence for God, and with purity.
1TM|2|3||For this is good and acceptable before God our life-giver;
1TM|2|4||who would have all men live, and be converted to the knowledge of the truth.
1TM|2|5||For God is one; and the mediator between God and men is one, [namely] the man Jesus the Messiah;
1TM|2|6||who gave himself a ransom for every man; a testimony that arrived in due time,
1TM|2|7||of which I am constituted a herald and legate. I speak the truth, and do not lie, for I am the teacher of the Gentiles in the belief of the truth.
1TM|2|8||I desire therefore, that men may pray in every place, while they lift up their hands with purity, without wrath, and without disputations.
1TM|2|9||So also, that women [appear] in a chaste fashion of dress; and that their adorning be with modesty and chastity; not with curls, or with gold, or with pearls, or with splendid robes;
1TM|2|10||but with good works, as becometh women who profess reverence for God.
1TM|2|11||Let a woman learn in silence, with all submission:
1TM|2|12||for I do not allow a woman to teach, or to be assuming over the man; but let her remain in stillness.
1TM|2|13||For Adam was first formed, and then Eve.
1TM|2|14||And Adam was not seduced, but the woman was seduced and transgressed the command.
1TM|2|15||Yet she shall live by means of her children, if they continue in the faith, and in love, and in sanctity, and in chastity.
1TM|3|1||It is a faithful saying, that if a man desireth the eldership, he desireth a good work.
1TM|3|2||And an elder ought to be such, that no blame can be found in him; and he should be the husband of one wife, with a vigilant mind, and sober and regular [in his habits], and affectionate to strangers, and instructive;
1TM|3|3||and not a transgressor in regard to wine, and whose hand is not swift to strike; but he should be humble, and not contentious, nor a lover of money;
1TM|3|4||and one that guideth well his own house, and holdeth his children in subjection with all purity.
1TM|3|5||For if he knoweth not how to guide his own house well, how can he guide the church of God.
1TM|3|6||Neither let him be of recent discipleship; lest he be uplifted, and fall into the condemnation of Satan.
1TM|3|7||And there ought to be good testimony of him from those without; lest he fall into reproach and the snare of Satan.
1TM|3|8||And so also the deacons should be pure, and not speak double, nor incline to much wine, nor love base gains;
1TM|3|9||but should hold the mystery of the faith with a pure conscience.
1TM|3|10||And let them be first tried, and then let them serve, if they are without blame.
1TM|3|11||So also should the wives be chaste and of vigilant minds; and they should be faithful in all things; and they should not be slanderers.
1TM|3|12||Let the deacons be such as have each one wife and guide well their children and households.
1TM|3|13||For they who serve well [as deacons], procure for themselves a good degree, and much boldness in the faith of Jesus the Messiah.
1TM|3|14||These things I write to thee, while hoping soon to come to thee;
1TM|3|15||but if I should delay, that thou mayest know how thou oughtest to conduct thyself in the house of God, which is the church of the living God. The pillar and the foundation of the truth,
1TM|3|16||and truly great, is this mystery of righteousness, which was revealed in the flesh, and justified in the spirit, and seen by angels, and proclaimed among the Gentiles, and believed on in the world, and received up into glory.
1TM|4|1||But the Spirit saith explicitly, that in the latter times, some will depart from the faith; and will go after deceptive spirits, and after the doctrine of demons.
1TM|4|2||These will seduce, by a false appearance; and will utter a lie, and will be seared in their conscience;
1TM|4|3||and will forbid to marry; and will require abstinence from meats, which God hath created for use and for thankfulness, by them who believe and know the truth.
1TM|4|4||Because whatever is created by God is good; and there is nothing which should be rejected if it be received with thankfulness;
1TM|4|5||for it is sanctified by the word of God and by prayer.
1TM|4|6||If thou shalt inculcate these things on thy brethren, thou wilt be a good minister of Jesus the Messiah, being educated in the language of the faith, and in the good doctrine which thou hast been taught.
1TM|4|7||But the silly tales of old women, shun thou; and occupy thyself with righteousness.
1TM|4|8||For, exercising the body is profitable a little while; but righteousness is every way profitable and hath promise of the life of the present time and of that to come.
1TM|4|9||This is a faithful saying, and worthy of reception.
1TM|4|10||For on this account, we toil and suffer reproach; because we trust in the living God, who is the life-giver of all men, especially of the believers.
1TM|4|11||These things teach thou, and inculcate.
1TM|4|12||And let no one despise thy youth; but be thou a pattern for the believers, in speech, and in behavior, and in love, and in faith, and in purity.
1TM|4|13||Until I come, be diligent in reading, and in prayer, and in teaching.
1TM|4|14||Despise not the gift that is in thee, which was given thee by prophecy, and by the laying on of the hand of the eldership.
1TM|4|15||On these things meditate; give thyself wholly to them: that it may be obvious to all that thou makest advances.
1TM|4|16||Be attentive to thyself, and to thy teaching; and persevere in them. For in doing this, thou wilt procure life to thyself and to them who hear thee.
1TM|5|1||Chide not an elder, but entreat him as a father; and the younger men, as thy brothers;
1TM|5|2||and the elder women, as mothers; and the younger women, as thy sisters, with all purity.
1TM|5|3||Honor widows, who are truly widows.
1TM|5|4||But if a widow hath children, or grandchildren, let them first learn to show kindness to their own households, and to repay the obligations to their parents; for this is acceptable before God.
1TM|5|5||Now she who is truly a widow, and solitary, her hope is in God; and she persevereth in prayers, and in supplications, by night and by day:
1TM|5|6||But she who followeth pleasure, is dead while she liveth.
1TM|5|7||These things enjoin thou on them, that they may be blameless.
1TM|5|8||But if any one careth not for them who are his own, and especially for them who are of the household of faith, he hath rejected the faith, and is worse than the unbelievers.
1TM|5|9||Therefore elect thou the widow, who is not less than sixty years [old], and who hath been the wife of one man,
1TM|5|10||and hath a reputation for good works; if she have trained up children, if she have entertained strangers, if she have washed the feet of saints, if she have relieved the afflicted, if she have walked in every good work.
1TM|5|11||But the younger widows do thou reject; for they wax wanton against the Messiah, and desire to be married:
1TM|5|12||and their condemnation is fixed, because they have cast off their former faith.
1TM|5|13||And they also learn idleness, wandering from house to house; and not only idleness, but also to talk much, and to pursue vanities, and to utter what they ought not.
1TM|5|14||I would therefore, that the younger women marry, and bear children, and regulate their houses; and that they give no occasion to the adversary for reproach.
1TM|5|15||For some have already begun to turn aside after Satan.
1TM|5|16||If any believing man or believing woman have widows, let them support them; and let them not be a burden on the church; so that there may be a sufficiency for such as are really widows.
1TM|5|17||Let the elders who conduct themselves well, be esteemed worthy of double honor; especially they who labor in the word and in doctrine.
1TM|5|18||For the scripture saith Thou shalt not muzzle the ox in threshing; and, The laborer is worthy of his pay.
1TM|5|19||Against an elder, receive not a complaint, except at the mouth of two or three witnesses.
1TM|5|20||Those who sin before all rebuke; that the rest of the people may fear.
1TM|5|21||I charge thee, before God, and our Lord Jesus the Messiah, and his elect angels, that thou observe these things; and let not your mind be preoccupied by any thing: and do nothing with a respect for persons.
1TM|5|22||Lay not the hand hastily on any man; and participate not in the sins of others; keep thyself pure.
1TM|5|23||And hereafter drink not water, but drink a little wine; on account of thy stomach, and thy continuing infirmities.
1TM|5|24||There are persons, whose sins are known, and go before them to the place of judgment; and there are some, whom they follow after.
1TM|5|25||So also good deeds are known: and those which are otherwise cannot be hid.
1TM|6|1||Let them who are under the yoke of servitude, hold their masters in all honor; lest the name of God and his doctrine be reproached.
1TM|6|2||And let them who have believing masters, not treat them with disrespect, because they are their brethren; but let them be more obedient, because they are believers and beloved, in whose service they enjoy quietness. These things teach thou, and request of them.
1TM|6|3||But if there be any one, who teacheth a different doctrine, and doth not accede to the salutary words of our Lord Jesus the Messiah, and to the doctrine of the fear of God,
1TM|6|4||he is one that exalteth himself, while he knoweth nothing; and he languisheth in the search and inquiry about words, from which come envy, and contention, and railing, and evil surmising,
1TM|6|5||and the disputation of men, whose minds are corrupt and destitute of the truth, and who suppose that gain is godliness. But from these stand thou aloof.
1TM|6|6||But great is our gain, which is the fear of God, with the use of our competence.
1TM|6|7||For we brought nothing into the world; and we know that we can carry nothing out of it.
1TM|6|8||Therefore, food and clothing satisfy us.
1TM|6|9||But they who desire to become rich, fall into temptations, and into snares, and into many lusts which are foolish and hurtful, and which drown men in destruction and perdition:
1TM|6|10||for the love of money is the root of all these evils. And there are some who, coveting it, have erred from the faith, and brought themselves into many sorrows.
1TM|6|11||But thou, O man of God, flee from these things; and follow after righteousness, and rectitude, and faith, and love, and patience, and humility.
1TM|6|12||And contend in the good contest of faith; and lay hold of life eternal, to which thou art called, and [of which] thou hast confessed a good confession before many witnesses.
1TM|6|13||I charge thee, before God, who quickeneth all, and [before] Jesus the Messiah who attested a good testimony before Pontius Pilate,
1TM|6|14||that thou keep the injunction, without stain, and without blemish, until the manifestation of our Lord Jesus the Messiah;
1TM|6|15||which God will, in due time make visible; [God] the blessed and only Potentate, the King of kings, and the Lord of lords;
1TM|6|16||who only is incorruptible, and dwelleth in light to which no one can approach; and whom no man hath seen, or even can see: to him be glory and dominion for ever and ever. Amen.
1TM|6|17||Charge the rich of this world, that they be not uplifted in their minds; and that they confide not in riches, in which is no security; but in the living God, who giveth us all things abundantly for our comfort:
1TM|6|18||and that they do good works, and be rich in well-doings; and be ready to give and to communicate:
1TM|6|19||and that they lay up for themselves a good foundation for that which is future; that they may take hold of real life.
1TM|6|20||O Timothy, be careful of that which is committed to thee; and shun vain words, and the oppositions of false science:
1TM|6|21||for they who profess it, have erred from the faith. Grace be with thee. Amen.
2TM|1|1||PAUL, a legate of Jesus the Messiah by the pleasure of God, according to the promise of life which is in Jesus the Messiah;
2TM|1|2||to Timothy a beloved son; grace, and mercy, and peace, from God the Father, and from our Lord Jesus the Messiah.
2TM|1|3||I thank God, whom I serve from my forefathers with a pure conscience, that I continually remember thee in my prayers, by night and by day:
2TM|1|4||and I desire to see thee, and I call to mind thy tears; that I may be filled with joy,
2TM|1|5||by the recollection which I have, by thy genuine faith, which dwelt first in thy grandmother Lois, and in thy mother Eunice, and also, I am persuaded, in thee.
2TM|1|6||Wherefore I remind thee, that thou excite the gift of God, that is in thee by the imposition of my hands.
2TM|1|7||For God hath not given us a spirit of fear, but of energy, and of love, and of instruction.
2TM|1|8||Therefore be not thou ashamed of the testimony of our Lord, nor of me his prisoner; but endure evils in connection with the Gospel, through the power of God;
2TM|1|9||who hath vivified us, and called us with a holy calling; not according to our works, but according to his good pleasure, and his grace that was given us in Jesus the Messiah from time before the ages,
2TM|1|10||and is now made known by the appearing of our Vivifier, Jesus the Messiah; who hath abolished death, and hath made manifest life and immortality, by the gospel:
2TM|1|11||of which I am constituted a herald and a legate, and a teacher of the Gentiles.
2TM|1|12||Therefore I suffer these things: and I am not ashamed; for I know in whom I have believed, and I am persuaded that he is competent to keep for me my deposit against that day.
2TM|1|13||Let the form of sound words, which thou hast heard from me, abide with thee; with faith and love, in Jesus the Messiah.
2TM|1|14||Keep thou the good deposit, by the Holy Spirit who dwelleth in us.
2TM|1|15||This thou knowest, that all those in Asia have turned from me; and that among them are Phygellus and Hermogenes.
2TM|1|16||May our Lord bestow mercy on the house of Onesiphorus; for, many times, he refreshed me, and was not ashamed of the chains of my imprisonment.
2TM|1|17||But also, when he came to Rome, he sought for me with diligence, and found me.
2TM|1|18||May our Lord grant him, that he may find mercy with our Lord, in that day. And how he ministered to me at Ephesus, thou very well knowest.
2TM|2|1||Thou therefore, my son, be strong in the grace which is by Jesus the Messiah.
2TM|2|2||And the things thou hast heard from me by many witnesses, these commit thou to faithful men, who are competent to teach others also.
2TM|2|3||And endure evils, as a good soldier of Jesus the Messiah.
2TM|2|4||No man, on becoming a soldier, entangleth himself with the business of the world; that he may please him who enlisted him.
2TM|2|5||And if one contend [in the games], he is not crowned, unless he contendeth according to the rules.
2TM|2|6||The husbandman who laboreth, ought first to feed on his fruits.
2TM|2|7||Consider what I say. Our Lord give thee wisdom in all things.
2TM|2|8||Be mindful of Jesus the Messiah, that he arose from the dead; who was of the seed of David, according to my gospel,
2TM|2|9||in which I suffer evils unto bonds, as if an evil-doer: but the word of God is not in bonds.
2TM|2|10||Therefore I endure every thing, for the elect's sake; that they also may obtain life, in Jesus the Messiah, with eternal glory.
2TM|2|11||Faithful is the saying, For if we shall have died with him, we shall also live with him;
2TM|2|12||and, if we shall have suffered, we shall also reign with him. But if we shall have rejected him, he will reject us.
2TM|2|13||And if we shall have not believed in him, he abideth in his fidelity; for he cannot reject himself.
2TM|2|14||Of these things admonish thou them . and charge [them,] before our Lord, that they dispute not, with unprofitable words, to the subversion of those who hear them.
2TM|2|15||And study to present thyself before God, perfectly, a laborer who is not ashamed, one who correctly announceth the word of truth.
2TM|2|16||Avoid vain discourses, in which there is no profit; for they very much add to the wickedness of those occupied with them.
2TM|2|17||And their discourse, like an eating cancer, will lay hold upon many. And one of these is Hymeneus, and another Philetus;
2TM|2|18||who have wandered from the truth, while they say, The resurrection of the dead hath passed: and they subvert the faith of some.
2TM|2|19||But the firm foundation of God standeth; and it hath this seal, The Lord knoweth them who are his: and, Let every one who invoketh the name of our Lord, stand aloof from iniquity.
2TM|2|20||But in a great house, there are not only vessels of gold or silver, but also of wood and of pottery; and some of them for honor, and some for dishonor.
2TM|2|21||If therefore any one purge himself from these things, he will be a pure vessel for honor, fit for the use of his Lord, and prepared for every good work.
2TM|2|22||Fly from all the lusts of youth; and follow after righteousness, and faith, and love, and peace, with them that invoke our Lord with a pure heart.
2TM|2|23||Avoid those foolish discussions which afford no instruction; for thou knowest, that they generate contests.
2TM|2|24||And a servant of our Lord ought not to contend, but to be mild towards every one, and instructive, and patient;
2TM|2|25||that with mildness he may enlighten those who dispute against him, if perhaps God may give them repentance, and they may acknowledge the truth,
2TM|2|26||and may recollect themselves, and may escape out of the snare of Satan, at whose pleasure they have been held ensnared.
2TM|3|1||But this know thou, that in the latter days hard times will come:
2TM|3|2||and men will be lovers of themselves, and lovers of money, boasters, proud, censorious, unyielding towards their own people, denyers of grace, wicked,
2TM|3|3||calumniators, addicted to concupiscence, ferocious, haters of the good,
2TM|3|4||treacherous, rash, inflated, attached to pleasure more than to the love of God,
2TM|3|5||having a form of respect for God, but wide from the power of God. Them who are such, repel from thee.
2TM|3|6||For of them are they who creep into this and that house, and captivate the women who are plunged in sins and led away by divers lusts,
2TM|3|7||who are always learning, and can never come to the knowledge of the truth.
2TM|3|8||Now as Jannes and Jambres withstood Moses, so also do these withstand the truth: men whose mind is corrupted, and [they] reprobates from the faith.
2TM|3|9||But they will not make progress, for their infatuation will be understood by every one, as theirs also was understood.
2TM|3|10||But thou hast followed after my doctrine, and my manner of life, and my aims, and my faith, and my long suffering, and my love, and my patience,
2TM|3|11||and my persecution, and my sufferings. And thou knowest what I endured at Antioch, and at Iconium, and at Lystra; what persecution I endured: and from all these my Lord delivered me.
2TM|3|12||And likewise all, who choose to live in the fear of God, in Jesus the Messiah, will be persecuted.
2TM|3|13||But evil and seducing men will add to their wickedness, while they deceive and are deceived.
2TM|3|14||But continue thou in the things thou hast learned and been assured of; for thou knowest from whom thou learnedst;
2TM|3|15||because from thy childhood, thou wast taught the holy books, which can make thee wise unto life, by faith in Jesus the Messiah.
2TM|3|16||All scripture that was written by the Spirit, is profitable for instruction, and for confutation, and for correction, and for erudition in righteousness;
2TM|3|17||that the man of God may become perfect, and complete for every good work.
2TM|4|1||I charge thee, before God, and our Lord Jesus the Messiah, who is to judge the living and the dead, at the manifestation of his kingdom,
2TM|4|2||Proclaim the word; and persist [in it] with diligence, in time and out of time; admonish, and rebuke, with all patience and instructiveness.
2TM|4|3||For the time will come, when they will not give ear to sound teaching; but, according to their lusts, will multiply to themselves teachers, in the itching of their hearing;
2TM|4|4||and will turn away their ears from the truth, and incline after fables.
2TM|4|5||But be thou vigilant in all things; and endure evils, and do the work of an evangelist, and fulfill thy ministry.
2TM|4|6||But I am soon to be immolated; and the time of my dissolution hath come.
2TM|4|7||I have fought a good combat, I have completed my race, I have preserved my fidelity;
2TM|4|8||and henceforth there is preserved for me a crown of righteousness, with which my Lord, the righteous Judge, will recompense me in that day; and not me only, but them also who love his manifestation.
2TM|4|9||Exert thyself to come to me quickly.
2TM|4|10||For Demas hath left me; and hath loved this world and gone away to Thessalonica; Crispus to Galatia, Titus to Dalmatia.
2TM|4|11||Luke only is with me. Take Mark, and bring him with thee; for he is suitable for me, for ministration.
2TM|4|12||And Tychicus I have sent to Ephesus.
2TM|4|13||And when thou comest, bring the bookcase, which I left at Troas with Carpus, and the books, but especially the roll of parchments.
2TM|4|14||Alexander the coppersmith showed me many ills: our Lord will reward him according to his doings.
2TM|4|15||And do thou also beware of him; for he is very insolent against our words.
2TM|4|16||At my first defence, no one was with me, but they all forsook me. Let not this be reckoned to them.
2TM|4|17||But my Lord stood by me, and strengthened me; that by me the preaching might be fulfilled; and [that] all the Gentiles might hear: and I was rescued from the mouth of the lion.
2TM|4|18||And my Lord will rescue me from every evil work; and will give me life in his heavenly kingdom. To him be glory, for ever and ever. Amen.
2TM|4|19||Present a salutation to Priscilla and Aquila, and to the household of Onesiphorus.
2TM|4|20||Erastus hath stopped at Corinth; and Trophimus I left sick at the city of Miletus.
2TM|4|21||Exert thyself to come before winter. Eubulus saluteth thee, and Pudens, and Linus, and Claudia, and all the brethren.
2TM|4|22||Our Lord Jesus the Messiah be with thy spirit. Grace be with thee. Amen.
TIT|1|1||Paul, a servant of God, and a legate of Jesus the Messiah; according to the faith of the elect of God, and the knowledge of the truth which is in the fear of God,
TIT|1|2||concerning the hope of eternal life, which the veracious God promised before the times of the world;
TIT|1|3||and in due time he hath manifested his word, by means of our announcement, which was confided to me by the command of God our Life-giver;
TIT|1|4||to Titus, a real son after the common faith: Grace and peace from God our Father, and from our Lord Jesus the Messiah, our Life-giver.
TIT|1|5||For this cause left I thee in Crete, that thou mightest regulate the things deficient, and establish elders in every city, as I directed thee:
TIT|1|6||him who is blameless, who is the husband of one wife, and hath believing children, who are no revellers, nor ungovernable in sensuality.
TIT|1|7||For an elder ought to be blameless, as the steward of God; and not be self-willed, nor irascible, nor excessive in wine, nor with hands swift to strike, nor a lover of base gains.
TIT|1|8||But he should be a lover of strangers, and a lover of good [deeds], and be sober, upright, kind-hearted, and restraining himself from evil passions;
TIT|1|9||and studious of the doctrine of the word of faith, that he may be able by his wholesome teaching both to console, and to rebuke them that are contentious.
TIT|1|10||For many are unsubmissive, and their discourses vain; and they mislead the minds of people, especially such as are of the circumcision.
TIT|1|11||The mouth of these ought to be stopped: they corrupt many families; and they teach what they ought not, for the sake of base gains.
TIT|1|12||One of them, a prophet of their own, said, The Cretans are always mendacious, evil beasts, idle bellies.
TIT|1|13||And this testimony is true. Therefore chide them sharply; that they may be sound in the faith,
TIT|1|14||and may not throw themselves into Jewish fables, and into the precepts of men who hate the truth.
TIT|1|15||For to the pure, every thing is pure; but to them who are defiled and unbelieving, nothing is pure; but their understanding is defiled, and their conscience.
TIT|1|16||And they profess that they know God, but in their works they deny him; and they are odious, and disobedient, and to every good work reprobates.
TIT|2|1||But speak thou the things that belong to wholesome doctrine.
TIT|2|2||And teach the older men to be watchful in their minds, and to be sober, and to be pure, and to be sound in the faith, and in love and in patience.
TIT|2|3||And so also the elder women, that they be in behavior as becometh the fear of God; and not to be slanderers; and not to be addicted to much wine; and to be inculcators of good things,
TIT|2|4||making the younger women to be modest, to love their husbands and their children,
TIT|2|5||to be chaste and holy, and to take good care of their households, and to be obedient to their husbands; so that no one may reproach the word of God.
TIT|2|6||And likewise exhort young men to be sober.
TIT|2|7||And in every thing show thyself a pattern, as to all good works: and in thy teaching, let thy discourse be healthful,
TIT|2|8||such as is sober and uncorrupt; and let no one despise it: so that he who riseth up against us, may be ashamed, seeing he can say nothing odious against us.
TIT|2|9||Let servants obey their masters in every thing, and strive to please them, and not contradict, nor pilfer;
TIT|2|10||but let them manifest that their fidelity, in all respects, is good: so that they may adorn the doctrine of God our Life-giver, in all things.
TIT|2|11||For the all-vivifying grace of God, is revealed to all men;
TIT|2|12||and it teacheth us, to deny ungodliness and worldly lusts, and to live in this world in sobriety, and in uprightness, and in the fear of God,
TIT|2|13||looking for the blessed hope, and the manifestation of the glory of the great God, and our Life-giver, Jesus the Messiah;
TIT|2|14||who gave himself for us, that he might recover us from all iniquity, and purify for himself a new people, who are zealous in good works.
TIT|2|15||These things speak thou, and exhort, and inculcate, with all authority; and let no one despise thee.
TIT|3|1||And admonish them to be submissive and obedient to princes and potentates; and that they be ready for every good work;
TIT|3|2||and that they speak ill of no man; that they be not contentious, but mild; and that in every thing they manifest benignity towards all men.
TIT|3|3||For we also were formerly reckless, and disobedient, and erring, and serving divers lusts, and living in malice and envy, and were hateful and also hating one another.
TIT|3|4||But when the kindness and compassion of God our Life-giver was revealed,
TIT|3|5||not by works of righteousness which we had done, but according to his mercy, he vivified us, by the washing of the new birth, and by the renovation of the Holy Spirit,
TIT|3|6||which he shed on us abundantly, by Jesus the Messiah our Life-giver:
TIT|3|7||that we might be justified by his grace, and become heirs in the hope of eternal life.
TIT|3|8||Faithful is the word: and in these things, I would have thee also establish them; so that they, who have believed in God, may be careful to cultivate good works: these are the things, which are good, and profitable to men.
TIT|3|9||But foolish questions, and stories of genealogies, and the disputes and contests of the scribes, avoid: for there is no profit in them, and they are vain.
TIT|3|10||An heretical man, after thou hast instructed him once and again, avoid:
TIT|3|11||and know thou, that such a man is perverse, and sinful, and self-condemned.
TIT|3|12||When I shall send Artemas to thee, or Tychicus, strive thou to come to me at Nicopolis; for I have purposed to winter there.
TIT|3|13||As for Zenas the scribe, and Apollos, endeavor to help them well on their way, that they may want nothing.
TIT|3|14||And let our people learn also to perform good works, on occasions of emergency, that they may not be unfruitful.
TIT|3|15||All they that are with me salute thee. Salute all them who love us in the faith. Grace be with you all. Amen.
PHM|1|1||PAUL, a prisoner of Jesus the Messiah, and Timothy a brother;--- to the beloved Philemon, a laborer with us,
PHM|1|2||and to our beloved Apphia, and to Archippus a laborer with us, and to the church in thy house.
PHM|1|3||Grace be with you, and peace from God our father, and from our Lord Jesus the Messiah.
PHM|1|4||I thank my God always, and remember thee in my prayers,
PHM|1|5||lo, from the time that I heard of thy faith, and of the love thou hast towards our Lord Jesus, and towards all the saints;
PHM|1|6||that there may be a fellowship of thy faith, yielding fruits in works, and in the knowledge of all the good things ye possess in Jesus the Messiah.
PHM|1|7||For we have great joy and consolation, because the bowels of the saints are refreshed by thy love.
PHM|1|8||Therefore I might have great freedom in the Messiah, to enjoin upon thee the things that are right.
PHM|1|9||But for love's sake, I earnestly beseech thee---even I, Paul, who am aged, as thou knowest, and now also a prisoner for Jesus the Messiah.
PHM|1|10||I beseech thee for my son, whom I had begotten in my bonds---for Onesimus;
PHM|1|11||from whom formerly thou hadst no profit, but now very profitable will he be both to thee and to me; and whom I have sent to thee.
PHM|1|12||And receive thou him, as one begotten by me.
PHM|1|13||For I was desirous to retain him with me, that he might minister to me in thy stead, in these bonds for the gospel.
PHM|1|14||But I would do nothing without consulting thee; lest thy benefit should be as if by compulsion, and not with thy pleasure.
PHM|1|15||And, perhaps, also, he therefore departed from thee for a season, that thou mightest retain him for ever;
PHM|1|16||henceforth, not as a servant, but more than a servant, a brother dear to me, and much more to thee, both in the flesh and in our Lord?
PHM|1|17||If therefore thou art in fellowship with me, receive him as one of mine.
PHM|1|18||And if he hath wronged thee, or oweth thee aught, place it to my account.
PHM|1|19||I, Paul, have written [it] with my own hand, I will repay:---not to say to thee, that to me thou owest thy ownself.
PHM|1|20||Yes, my brother, let me be refreshed by thee in our Lord: refresh thou my bowels in the Messiah.
PHM|1|21||Being confident that thou wilt hearken to me, I have written to thee: and I know that thou wilt do more than I say.
PHM|1|22||And herewith, prepare also a house for me to lodge in; for I hope that, by your prayers, I shall be given to you.
PHM|1|23||Epaphras, a fellow-captive with me in Jesus the Messiah, saluteth thee;
PHM|1|24||and Mark, and Aristarchus, and Demas, and Luke, my coadjutors.
PHM|1|25||The grace of our Lord Jesus the Messiah be with your spirit, my brethren.---Amen.
HEB|1|1||In many ways, and many forms, God anciently conversed with our fathers, by the prophets:
HEB|1|2||But in these latter days, he hath conversed with us, by his Son; whom he hath constituted heir of all things, and by whom he made the worlds;
HEB|1|3||who is the splendor of his glory, and the image of himself, and upholdeth all by the energy of his word; and by himself he made a purgation of sins, and sat down on the right hand of the Majesty on high.
HEB|1|4||And he is altogether superior to the angels, as he hath also inherited a name which excelleth theirs.
HEB|1|5||For to which of the angels did God ever say, Thou art my SON, this day have I begotten thee? And again, I will be to him a Father, and he shall be to me a Son?
HEB|1|6||And again, when bringing the first begotten into the world, he said: Let all the angels of God worship him.
HEB|1|7||But of the angels he thus said: Who made his angels a wind, and his ministers a flaming fire.
HEB|1|8||But of the Son he said: Thy throne, O God, is for ever and ever; a righteous sceptre is the sceptre of thy kingdom.
HEB|1|9||Thou hast loved rectitude, and hated iniquity; therefore God, thy God, hath anointed thee with the oil of gladness more than thy associates.
HEB|1|10||And again, Thou hast from the beginning laid the foundations of the earth, and the heavens are the work of thy hands:
HEB|1|11||they will pass away, but thou endurest; and they all, like a robe, wax old;
HEB|1|12||and like a cloak, thou wilt fold them up. They will be changed; but thou wilt be as thou art, and thy years will not be finished.
HEB|1|13||And to which of the angels did he ever say: Sit thou at my right hand, until I shall place thy enemies a footstool under thy feet?
HEB|1|14||Are they not all spirits of ministration, who are sent to minister on account of them that are to inherit life?
HEB|2|1||Therefore we ought to be exceedingly cautious, in regard to what we have heard, lest we fall away.
HEB|2|2||For if the word uttered by the medium of angels was confirmed, and every one who heard it, and transgressed it, received a just retribution;
HEB|2|3||how shall we escape, if we despise the things which are our life, things which began to be spoken by our Lord, and were confirmed to us by them who heard from him,
HEB|2|4||while God gave testimony concerning them, by signs and wonders, and by various miracles and distributions of the Holy Spirit, which were given according to his pleasure?
HEB|2|5||For to the angels he hath not subjected the world to come, of which we speak.
HEB|2|6||But as the scripture testifieth, and saith: What is man, that thou art mindful of him? and the son of man, that thou attendest to him?
HEB|2|7||Thou hast depressed him somewhat lower than the angels: glory and honor hast thou put on his head; and thou hast invested him with authority over the work of thy hand.
HEB|2|8||And all things hast thou subjected under his feet. And in this subjecting of all things to him, he omitted nothing, which he did not subject. But now, we do not yet see all things subjected to him.
HEB|2|9||But we see him, who was depressed somewhat lower than the angels, to be this Jesus, because of the passion of his death; and glory and honor are placed on his head; for God himself, in his grace, tasted death for all men.
HEB|2|10||For it became him, by whom are all things, and on account of whom are all things, and [who] bringeth many sons unto his glory, to perfect the prince of their life by suffering.
HEB|2|11||For he that sanctifieth, and they who are sanctified, are all of one [nature]. Therefore he is not ashamed to call them brethren;
HEB|2|12||as he saith, I will announce thy name to my brethren; in the midst of the assembly, I will praise thee.
HEB|2|13||And again, I will confide in him. And again, Behold me, and the children whom thou, God, hast given to me.
HEB|2|14||For because the children participated in flesh and blood, he also, in like manner, took part in the same; that, by his death, he might bring to naught him who held the dominion of death, namely Satan;
HEB|2|15||and might release them, who, through fear of death, are all their lives subject to bondage.
HEB|2|16||For he did not assume [a nature] from angels, but he assumed [a nature] from the seed of Abraham.
HEB|2|17||Wherefore it was right, that he should be in all respects like his brethren; that he might be merciful, and a high priest faithful in the things of God, and might make expiation for the sins of the people.
HEB|2|18||For, in that he himself hath suffered, and been tempted, he is able to succor them who are tempted.
HEB|3|1||Wherefore, my holy brethren, who are called with a calling that is from heaven, consider this Legate and High Priest of our profession, Jesus the Messiah:
HEB|3|2||who was faithful to him that made him, as was Moses in all his house.
HEB|3|3||For much greater is the glory of this man, than that of Moses; just as the glory of the builder of a house, is greater than that of the edifice.
HEB|3|4||For every house is built by some man; but he who buildeth all things is God.
HEB|3|5||And Moses, as a servant, was faithful in all the house, for an attestation to those things that were to be spoken by him:
HEB|3|6||but the Messiah as the SON, [is] over his own house; and we are his house, if we retain unto the end assurance, and the triumph of hope in him.
HEB|3|7||Because the Holy Spirit hath said: To-day, if ye will hear his voice,
